[{"id":1,"question_id":1,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","text":"What types of data will you collect, create, acquire and/or record?","guidance":"Examples: Images, audio, video, text, tabular data, modeling data, spatial data, instrumentation data"},{"id":2,"question_id":2,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","text":"Are there are any existing data that you can re-use?  If so, please explain how you will obtain that data and integrate it into your research project.","guidance":"<p>There may be existing data that you can license or purchase for re-use.  <a href=\"http://databib.org/\" target=\"_blank\">Databib</a> and <a href=\"http://www.re3data.org/\" target=\"_blank\">re3data</a> are directories of disciplinary data repositories you can check for data.   You can also contact the <a href=\"http://www.library.ualberta.ca/aboutus/hss/data/\" target=\"_blank\">U of A Data Library</a> for help with finding and re-using existing data</p>"},{"id":3,"question_id":3,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","text":"What file formats will your data be collected in?  Will these formats allow for data re-use, sharing and long-term access to the data?","guidance":"<p>Proprietary file formats which require specialized software or hardware to use are not recommended, but may be necessary for certain data collection or analysis methods.  Using open file formats or industry-standard formats (e.g. those which are widely used by a given community) is preferred whenever possible.  </p>\r\n<p>Read more about file formats on the <a href=\"http://data-archive.ac.uk/create-manage/format/formats\" target=\"_blank\">UK Data Archive website</a>.</p>"},{"id":4,"question_id":4,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","text":"What documentation will be needed for the data to be read and interpreted correctly in the future?  This includes study-level documentation, data-level description, and any other contextual information required to make the data usable by other researchers","guidance":"<p>Your documentation may include study-level information about:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>who created/collected the data</li>\r\n<li>when it was created</li>\r\n<li>any relevant study documents</li>\r\n<li>conditions of use</li>\r\n<li>contextual details about data collection methods and procedural documentation about how data files are stored, structured, and modified.  </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>A complete description of the data files may include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>naming and labelling conventions</li>\r\n<li>explanations of codes and variables</li>\r\n<li>any information or files require to reproduce derived data.  </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>More information about data documentation is available at the <a href=\"http://www.data-archive.ac.uk/create-manage/document\" target=\"_blank\">UK Data Archive</a></p>"},{"id":5,"question_id":5,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","text":"Please list the metadata standard and tools you will use to document and describe your data.  If there is not an appropriate standard, please explain how you will ensure consistency in your documentation.","guidance":"<p>Metadata is a description of the contents and context of data files. Using a metadata standard (a set of required fields to fill out) helps ensure that your documentation is consistent, structured, and machine-readable, which is essential for depositing data in repositories and making it easily discoverable by search engines.</p>\r\n<p>There are general and discipline-specific <a href=\"http://www.dcc.ac.uk/resources/metadata-standards\" target=\"_blank\">metadata standards and tools</a> for research data.  For assistance with choosing a metadata standard, please contact <a href=\"mailto:data@ualberta.ca\">data@ualberta.ca</a>.</p>"},{"id":6,"question_id":6,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","text":"How will you make sure that documentation is created or captured consistently throughout your project?","guidance":"It is best to begin the documentation process at the start of a research project.  Details or procedures may be forgotten if documentation is created at the end of a project.  "},{"id":7,"question_id":7,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","text":"How will your data be stored and backed up during your research project?","guidance":"<p>Storing data on flash drives, laptops, computers, or external hard drives without a regular backup procedure is not recommended, because they are subject to hardware failure, viruses, file corruption, theft, loss, and human error. Likewise, multiple copies of data stored in the same physical location does little to mitigate risk. </p>\r\n<p>Using software which automatically backs up your data and keeps it synchronized with a master copy is recommended. Copies of data should ideally be stored in separate physical locations to mitigate physical risks, e.g. fire.  More about data storage from <a href=\"http://data-archive.ac.uk/create-manage/storage.aspx\" target=\"_blank\">UK Data Archive</a>.</p>\r\n<p>Many universities offer networked file storage which is automatically backed up. University of Alberta researchers have access to networked storage and to commercial cloud storage (Google Drive) through <a href=\"http://ist.ualberta.ca/ts\" target=\"_blank\">Information Services and Technology</a>.\r\nUniversity of Alberta Libraries also offers <a href=\"https://dataverse.library.ualberta.ca/dvn/\" target=\"_blank\">Dataverse</a> for storing and sharing small datasets. For assistance with Dataverse, contact <a href=\"mailto:data@ualberta.ca\">data@ualberta.ca</a>. </p>"},{"id":8,"question_id":8,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","text":"How will you ensure that sensitive data is stored securely and only accessible to the research team during the research project?","guidance":"<p>The security measures you choose to implement will depend on the sensitivity of the data being stored.  Data can be protected by limiting physical access to hard drives and file servers on which it is stored, by storing data on computers that do not have external network access (i.e. access to the Internet), through password protection, and by encrypting data files.</p>\r\n<p>Sharing sensitive data via email and cloud storage services such as Dropbox is not recommended, since the security of these services cannot be trusted.  More about security from the <a href=\"http://data-archive.ac.uk/create-manage/storage/security\" target=\"_blank\">UK Data Archive</a>.</p>\r\n"},{"id":9,"question_id":9,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-23 22:21:57 UTC","text":"Which data are selected for preservation and access will depend on potential reuse value, whether there are obligations to either retain or destroy data, and the resources required to properly curate the data and ensure that it remains usable in the future.  In some circumstances, it may be feasible to preserve all versions of the data (e.g. raw, processed, analyzed, final), but in others, it may be preferable to only keep only selected data (e.g. transcripts instead of audio interviews).","guidance":"Which data are selected for preservation and access will depend on potential reuse value, whether there are obligations to either retain or destroy data, and the resources required to properly curate the data and ensure that it remains usable in the future.  In some circumstances, it may be feasible to preserve all versions of the data (e.g. raw, processed, analyzed, final), but in others, it may be preferable to only keep only selected data (e.g. transcripts instead of audio interviews)."},{"id":10,"question_id":10,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","text":"At the end of your research project, where will you deposit your data for long-term preservation and access? ","guidance":"<p>Please describe how you will identify a data repository or data center for your data.  <a href=\"http://databib.org/\" target=\"_blank\">Databib</a>  and <a href=\"http://www.re3data.org/\" target=\"_blank\">re3data.org</a> are directories of potential data repositories.  Note any details about the curation of the data and what aspects of the curation are your responsibility versus what the repository assumes. See if the data repository will provide a statement agreeing to these terms of deposit that can be included with your data management plan. </p>\r\n<p>Researchers at the University of Alberta can deposit smaller datasets (less than 500MB) in <a href=\"https://dataverse.library.ualberta.ca/dvn/\" target=\"_blank\">Dataverse</a> for complex data formats such as those produced by SPSS or SAS, or <a href=\"https://era.library.ualberta.ca/public/home\" target=\"_blank\">ERA</a> for basic data formats such as Excel.  For larger datasets, please contact <a href=\"mailto:data@ualberta.ca\">data@ualberta.ca</a>.  </p>\r\n"},{"id":11,"question_id":11,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","text":"Please describe how you will prepare the data for preservation and access, including any necessary procedures for data cleaning, normalization or de-identification.  Explain how you will prevent data from being lost while processing and converting files. ","guidance":"<p>It is likely that you will have multiple versions of your data (raw, processed, analyzed, final), and your data may be stored in different file formats depending on how they were collected and analyzed.</p>\r\n<p>Digital information may be lost while converting files from one format to another (e.g. converting an image from a non-compressed ‘lossless’ TIFF file to a compressed ‘lossy’ JPG file), so changes to file formats should be clearly documented.</p>\r\n<p>Identify what steps are needed after your project is completed in order to ensure the data you are choosing to preserve or share is anonymous, error-free, and converted to recommended formats with a minimal risk of data loss.</p>\r\n<p>Read more about <a href=\"http://data-archive.ac.uk/create-manage/format/formats\" target=\"_blank\">file formats</a> and <a href=\"http://data-archive.ac.uk/create-manage/consent-ethics/anonymisation\" target=\"_blank\">anonymization</a> on the UK Data Archive Website.</p>"},{"id":12,"question_id":12,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","text":"What data will you be sharing and in what form? (e.g. raw, processed, analyzed, final). Consider which data may need to be shared in order to meet institutional or funding requirements, and which data may be restricted because of confidentiality/privacy i","guidance":""},{"id":13,"question_id":13,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","text":"How will you be sharing your data? (e.g. institutional repository, a specialized data archive, project website, informal/on-request sharing).  Include a brief description of any resources needed to share your data (equipment, systems, expertise, etc.). \r\n","guidance":"<p>Where you share your data depends on the complexity and size of your data.  Smaller, low-risk datasets can be shared via institutional or disciplinary repositories and project websites. Larger datasets or datasets with more stringent security requirements cannot be easily transferred over the Internet.  Read more about sharing data at the <a href=\"http://www.data-archive.ac.uk/create-manage/planning-for-sharing/how-to-share-data\" target=\"_blank\">UK Data Archive</a>.</p>\r\n<p>Researchers at the University of Alberta can deposit smaller datasets (less than 500MB) in <a href=\"https://dataverse.library.ualberta.ca/dvn/\" target=\"_blank\">Dataverse</a> (for complex data formats such as that produced by SPSS or SAS) or <a href=\"https://era.library.ualberta.ca/public/home\" target=\"_blank\">ERA</a> (for basic data formats such as Excel).  For larger datasets, please contact <a href=\"mailto:data@ualberta.ca\">data@ualberta.ca</a>. </p>"},{"id":14,"question_id":14,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","text":"Please describe whether there will be any restrictions placed on your data when they are made available and who may access them.  If data are not openly available, describe the process for gaining access.","guidance":"<p>It may be necessary or desirable to restrict access to your data for a limited time or to a limited number of people, for:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>ethical reasons (privacy and confidentiality) </li>\r\n<li>economic reasons (patents and commercialization)</li>\r\n<li>intellectual property reasons (e.g. ownership of the original dataset on which yours is based) </li>\r\n<li>or to comply with a journal publishing policy.  </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Strategies to mitigate these issues may include: </p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>anonymising or aggregating data</li>\r\n<li>gaining participant consent for data sharing</li>\r\n<li>gaining permissions to share adapted or modified data</li>\r\n<li>and agreeing to a limited embargo period.</li>\r\n</ul>"},{"id":15,"question_id":15,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-23 22:18:41 UTC","text":"Who will be responsible for data management during the project? (i.e. during collection, processing, analysis, documentation).  Identify staff and organizational roles and their responsibilities for carrying out the data management plan (DMP), including time allocations and training requirements.","guidance":""},{"id":16,"question_id":16,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","text":"What will happen when personnel changes occur or if the principal investigator leaves the institution before the project has concluded?","guidance":""},{"id":17,"question_id":17,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","text":"Who will be responsible for data sharing and preservation after the project has concluded? Indicate the party who will have primary responsibility for how the data will persist over time when the original personnel have moved on. ","guidance":""},{"id":18,"question_id":18,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","text":"If data are collected using laptops or mobile devices, please explain how will you will securely store and transfer the data.","guidance":"<p>The University of Alberta’s Encryption Procedure requires that sensitive information stored on mobile computing devices be encrypted.  <a href=\"http://www.vpit.ualberta.ca/encryption/\" target=\"_blank\">Read more about encryption</a></p>"},{"id":19,"question_id":19,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-23 22:21:04 UTC","text":"How much data do you anticipate collecting?  Include an estimate of how much storage space you will require (in megabytes, gigabytes, terabytes).  This estimate should also take into account storage space required for file versioning, backups, and the growth rate over time.","guidance":"<p>The type of data you collect will impact your storage requirements.  Textual and tabular data files are usually very small (a few megabytes) unless you have a lot of data.  Video files are usually very large (hundreds of megabytes up to several gigabytes).  If you have a large amount of data (gigabytes or terabytes), it will be more challenging to share and transfer it.  You may need to consider networked storage options or more sophisticated backup methods.</p>\r\n<p>If your data will be changing frequently, please estimate how much extra storage will be required to store multiple versions.  If you are collecting data over a long period of time (e.g. several months or years), please describe your plan for adding additional storage to accommodate the growth of your data.</p>"},{"id":20,"question_id":20,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","text":"What conventions and procedures will you use to structure, name and version control your files to ensure that your data is well-organized?\r\n","guidance":"<p>Ensuring that you and your research team are using the ‘master’ version of your data is extremely important.  Establishing conventions for naming and versioning your files is essential, especially when data may be available in different file formats or stored on different computers.</p>\r\n<p>More information on file naming and version control is available from <a href=\"http://libraries.mit.edu/guides/subjects/data-management/organizing.html\" target=\"_blank\">MIT</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.data-archive.ac.uk/create-manage/format/versions\" target=\"_blank\">UK Data Archive</a>.</p>\r\n<p>University of Alberta Libraries’ <a href=\"https://dataverse.library.ualberta.ca/dvn/\" target=\"_blank\">Dataverse</a> can help with version control of your files.</p>"},{"id":21,"question_id":21,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","text":"What type of end-user license will you include with your data? Please include a copy of this license with your Data Management Plan. ","guidance":"<p>Assigning an end-user license allows you to define the terms of use for your data.  We recommend a <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/choose/\" target=\"_blank\">Creative Commons license</a>.</p>"},{"id":22,"question_id":22,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","text":"What resources will you require to implement your plan? Will extra people, time or hardware, storage be required? How much will this cost (estimation)?","guidance":"<p>More information about estimating cost for data management is available through the <a href=\"http://data-archive.ac.uk/create-manage/planning-for-sharing/costing\" target=\"_blank\">UK Data Archive</a>. This information should be incorporated into any grant applications for your project.</p>"},{"id":23,"question_id":23,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","text":"Q. 1.1 Please enter the study title. ","guidance":""},{"id":24,"question_id":24,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","text":"Q. 1. 2. Please provide an outline description to your research. ","guidance":""},{"id":25,"question_id":25,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","text":"Q. 1.3 Please provide details of the primary efficacy variables. ","guidance":"This is required so that appropriate data management focus can be applied to this critical data. "},{"id":26,"question_id":26,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","text":"Q 1. 4. Please provide details of the secondary efficacy variables. ","guidance":""},{"id":27,"question_id":28,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","text":"Q. 1. 5. Please details what data constitutes the safety data (if any) for the study. ","guidance":"The safety data normally refers to the adverse events and lab data. However some studies may include additional safety data. "},{"id":28,"question_id":29,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","text":"Q. 1. 6. Please provide the definition of analysis populations. ","guidance":"Under some circumstances these definitions may be required to focus data management activity, for instance an interim analysis involving certain subsets of the study population. "},{"id":29,"question_id":30,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","text":"Q. 1. 7. Please provide details of the number of patients required in each group treatment/placebo/enrolled/randomized/completed as appropriate. ","guidance":""},{"id":30,"question_id":31,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","text":"Q. 1. 8 Please provide details of the study timelines. ","guidance":"Details of the timelines linclude first patient first visit, last patient last visit, scheduled visit intervals, interim analysis, database lock, final delivery, etc. "},{"id":31,"question_id":32,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","text":"Q. 1. 9. Is the study interventional or observational?","guidance":""},{"id":32,"question_id":33,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","text":"Q. 1. 10. Is this study a drug/device trial?","guidance":""},{"id":33,"question_id":35,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","text":"Q. 1. 11. Is the use of the drug/device within its approval?","guidance":"Trials of a medication or device that are outside the scope of its approval require CTA submission to Health Canada. "},{"id":34,"question_id":36,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","text":"Q. 1. 12. Is ethics approval required and has it been obtained?\r\n","guidance":"Typically ethics approval is required for the collection of subject related data. Note that where the subjects of the study are practicing medical personnel ethics approval may still be required. "},{"id":35,"question_id":38,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","text":"Q. 2. 1. What data sources do you anticipate collecting data from? Please include both paper and electronic. ","guidance":""},{"id":36,"question_id":40,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","text":"Q. 2. 2. How will the data be collected/captured? For a combination of data collection modes, please specify which sites/regions will be using Electronic Data Capture (EDC), and which ones are not.  ","guidance":"Electronic data capture (EDC), paper or a combination of data collection modes.  "},{"id":37,"question_id":41,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","text":"Q. 2. 3. Who is designing the Case Report Forms (CRFs)? Is CRIC (Clinical Research Informatics Core) input required?","guidance":"Clinical Research Informatics Core (CRIC) provides technology and technology based services to help MICYRN researchers creating CRFs (Case Report Forms), which is a data collection tool used in clinical trials to support investigators and coordinators in capturing all protocol-required information."},{"id":38,"question_id":42,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","text":"Q. 2. 4. What systems are to be used to collect the data? What file formats will your electronic data be collected in? Will these formats allow for data re-use, sharing and long-term access to the data?","guidance":""},{"id":39,"question_id":43,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","text":"Q. 2. 5. How the study will be randomized/blinded? Please provide details on any applicable code break procedures.  ","guidance":""},{"id":40,"question_id":45,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","text":"Q. 3. 1. Who will be responsible to monitor paper CRFs? Identify staff and organizational roles and their responsibilities for carrying out the monitoring task, including time allocations and training requirements. ","guidance":""},{"id":41,"question_id":46,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","text":"Q. 3. 2.  What procedure should be followed when monitoring paper CRFs to ensure accuracy, adherence to the protocol and GCP conformance?","guidance":""},{"id":42,"question_id":47,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","text":"Q. 3. 3. Electronic CRFs (OpenClinica, REDCap, etc) will be monitored electronically for accuracy (source document verification), adherence to the protocol and GCP conformance. Who will be responsible to monitor electronic CRFs? Identify staff and organiz","guidance":""},{"id":43,"question_id":48,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","text":"Q. 3. 4. Please describe additional data validation procedures to the electronic CRFs, if any. Who will be responsible for these data validation tasks? Identify staff and their responsibilities for carrying out these data validation steps. \r\n\r\n\r\n","guidance":""},{"id":44,"question_id":49,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","text":"Q. 4.1. Who should the documents received directly from investigational staff be delivered to? These include CRFs and other documents required for data entry, and should always accompany with a CRF Transmittal Form? \r\n","guidance":"The CRF Transmittal form will detail the documents in the delivery. The personnel received the documents will reconcile the transmittal form against the delivered documents. Any discrepancies will be noted on the form, which will be returned to the PI by way of receipt. \r\n"},{"id":45,"question_id":50,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","text":"Q. 4. 2. How will the CRFs and other documents be stored during the study? ","guidance":""},{"id":46,"question_id":51,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","text":"Q. 4.4. How will you track the documents that are collected and removed from the storage for data entry?","guidance":""},{"id":47,"question_id":53,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","text":"Q. 5. 1. How will you do data entry for paper CRFs?","guidance":""},{"id":48,"question_id":54,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","text":"Q. 5. 2. How will you do data entry from photocopies?","guidance":""},{"id":49,"question_id":55,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","text":"Q. 5. 3. How will you do data entry for CRFs that are not photocopied?","guidance":""},{"id":50,"question_id":56,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","text":"Q. 5. 4. How will you handle data entry for EDCs?","guidance":""},{"id":51,"question_id":57,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","text":"Q. 6. 1. What documentation will be needed for the data handling? How will you ensure the documentation is created and updated consistently throughout your study?","guidance":""},{"id":52,"question_id":58,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","text":"Q. 7. 1. How will you validate the data recorded? What is your query process during the study?","guidance":"Please summarize relationship between data management/monitors/site/sponsor for query processing. "},{"id":53,"question_id":59,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","text":"Q. 7. 2. How will you validate data with EDC forms? ","guidance":""},{"id":54,"question_id":60,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","text":"Q. 7. 3. How will you validate data with paper CRFs?","guidance":""},{"id":55,"question_id":62,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","text":"Q. 7.4. How will you verify the source documents?","guidance":"The above procedures only partially address the issue of transcription errors arising during form\r\ncompletion, some of which will be caught by online data validation. It is strongly recommended that\r\nprocedures are implemented within the research clinic in order to identify and correct transcription errors.\r\nAn example of such a procedure is an ongoing, systematic review of source documents (patient chart) for\r\na randomly selected sample of subjects."},{"id":56,"question_id":63,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:50 UTC","text":"Q. 7. 5. What is your procedure for data quality audit?","guidance":""},{"id":57,"question_id":64,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","text":"Q. 6. 2. [Interventional Studies only] How will you handle serious adverse events? Please provide an overview of SAE handling procedure, including relationship between site/sponsor/monitor and CRIC regarding SAE handling. \r\n\r\n","guidance":""},{"id":58,"question_id":65,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","text":"Q. 8. 1. Is data coding required, for example adverse event coding? If so, please list what data requires coding, and which dictionaries will be used (for example: MedDRA and WHODDE)? ","guidance":""},{"id":59,"question_id":67,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","text":"Q. 9. 1. What data will you be sharing and in what form? (e.g. raw, processed, analyzed, final). ","guidance":"Consider which data may need to be shared in order to meet institutional or funding requirements, and which data may be restricted because of confidentiality/privacy issue. "},{"id":60,"question_id":68,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","text":"Q. 9. 2. How will you extract the data?","guidance":""},{"id":61,"question_id":69,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","text":"Q. 9. 3. How will you be sharing your data? (e.g. institutional repository, a specialized data archive, project website, informal/on-request sharing etc. ). Please include a brief description of any resources needed to share your data (equipment, systems,","guidance":""},{"id":62,"question_id":70,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","text":"Q. 9. 4. Please describe whether there will be any restrictions placed on your data when they are made available and who may access them. If data are not openly available, describe the process for gaining access. ","guidance":""},{"id":63,"question_id":71,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","text":"Q. 9. 5. What type of end-user license will you include with your data? Please include a copy of this license with your Data Management Plan. ","guidance":""},{"id":64,"question_id":72,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","text":"Q. 10. 1. How will your data be stored and archived after your study?","guidance":""},{"id":65,"question_id":73,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","text":"Q. 10.2.  At the end of your study, which data will you select for long-term preservation and access? And where will you deposit the selected data? ","guidance":""},{"id":66,"question_id":74,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","text":"Q. 10. 3. How will you archive the study materials after study completion? Please include both paper and electronic records. ","guidance":""},{"id":67,"question_id":75,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","text":"Q. 11. 1. Please list who is responsible for the following data management tasks during the study:\r\n1. CRF design\r\n2. Database configuration\r\n3. Database documentation\r\n4. Database acceptance testing\r\n5. Monitoring\r\n6. Document flow and tracking\r\n7. Data ","guidance":""},{"id":68,"question_id":76,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","text":"Q. 11. 2. What will happen when personnel changes occur or if the principal investigator leaves the institution before the study has concluded?","guidance":""},{"id":69,"question_id":77,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","text":"Q. 11. 3. Who will be responsible for data sharing and preservation after the study has concluded? Indicate the party who will have primary responsibility for how the data will persist over time when the original personnel have moved on. ","guidance":""},{"id":70,"question_id":78,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","text":"Q. 4. 3. How will you ensure that sensitive data is stored securely and only accessible to the research team during the study?","guidance":""},{"id":71,"question_id":79,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","text":"Q. 6. 3. What documentation will be needed for the data to be read and interpreted correctly in the future? This includes study-level documentation, data-level description, and any other contextual information required to make the data usable by other res","guidance":""},{"id":72,"question_id":110,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","text":"What access control features exist in the data repository to be used that will provide an appropriate level access to the data?","guidance":"<p>Intelligent access describes providing access to data that is appropriate to the level of restrictions associated with the content.</p>"},{"id":73,"question_id":111,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","text":"How will access control be provided if the data repository does not support this feature?","guidance":""},{"id":74,"question_id":159,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","text":"Indicate the sources of the data that you will be using in this project.","guidance":"<p>If your project will be creating new data from one or more existing data sources or if data being collected in your project is being integrated with existing data, please check both boxes.</p>"},{"id":75,"question_id":160,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","text":"To reproduce your findings, will any special software or code be needed?","guidance":"<p>You should document any derived variables added to the data during analysis. &nbsp;This metadata may be in a descriptive statement or expressed in code.</p>"},{"id":76,"question_id":161,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","text":"How will access to any special software or code be provided?","guidance":"<p><a href=\"https://github.com/\">Github</a>&nbsp;is a web-based service for source code management and for&nbsp;distributed revision control.</p>\r\n<p>A data repository is a web-based service that allows researchers to upload and govern&nbsp;access to data and files that they wish to share.</p>"},{"id":77,"question_id":162,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","text":"Are there any restrictions associated with the data?","guidance":"<p>Data from human participants in research require privacy safeguards and assurances around the purposes for which the data will be used. This is typically addressed in an ethics application.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Data acquired from other sources may have conditions stipulated in a licence about its redissemination. Often researchers are granted the right to analyze the data but not to share it directly with others outside their project.</p>"},{"id":78,"question_id":163,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","text":"How will access be provided to sensitive or confidential data?","guidance":"<p>If the data are from human participants, consider preparing a consent form that seeks the participants' approval to share the data with other researchers. This form will require ethics approval.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Another approach is to de-identify the data to minimize the risk of disclosing the identity of participants. Several methods exist for de-identifying data.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Instead of employing methods to make the data safer, another approach is to place the data in a safe environment and then control who has access to the data. Commonly known as data enclaves or research data centres, this option is the most restrictive in making the data available to other researchers. </p>"},{"id":79,"question_id":164,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","text":"If you are using data from another producer or provider, describe how other researchers can obtain access to these data.","guidance":"<p>Consider requesting from the data owner a special data licence that allows you to share just the data that you used in producing your findings.</p>"},{"id":80,"question_id":165,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","text":"If you will deposit your data with an existing data repository, please identify the repository by its URL.","guidance":"<p>Having chosen a&nbsp;data repository, it is recommended that you meet with one of the data curators with&nbsp;this repository to discuss how best to prepare your data for sharing and to explore your options in preparing the&nbsp;metadata to accompany your data.&nbsp;</p>"},{"id":81,"question_id":166,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","text":"How will the data be accessible if they have not been deposited in an existing data repository?","guidance":"<p>Placing data on a website for downloading may seem like a straightforward solution, however data repositories typically provide a variety of services&nbsp;that better support&nbsp;secondary uses of data, including metadata, versioning, and access control features.</p>"},{"id":82,"question_id":167,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","text":"How will persistent identifiers for the data be provided?","guidance":"<p>A persistent identifier is a unique code that is associated with your data and serves in the digital realm a function similar to what the ISBN does in the print world.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Digital Object Identifiers (DOIs) are one type of persistent identifier and is the method of choice of for DataCite.</p>\r\n<p>Researchers are being requested to identify a persistent identifier early in their projects to facilitate linkages between subsequent publications and data on the Internet. An article or report can include&nbsp;the persistent identifier for the data, which will allow jumping easily from the article to the data.</p>"},{"id":83,"question_id":168,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","text":"Who will register DOIs for the data with DataCite?","guidance":"<p>DataCite is an international registry for data and in Canada, the National Research Council provides DataCite registration services. DataCite uses DOIs as persistent identifiers.</p>"},{"id":84,"question_id":169,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","text":"What access control features exist in the data repository to be used that will provide an appropriate level access to the data?","guidance":"<p>Intelligent access describes providing access to data that is appropriate to the level of restrictions associated with the content.</p>"},{"id":85,"question_id":170,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","text":"How will access control be provided if the data repository does not support this feature?","guidance":""},{"id":86,"question_id":171,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","text":"How will the citation practice for the data be determined?","guidance":"<p>Citation practices for data are varied. The UK Digital Curation Centre provides an <a href=\"http://www.dcc.ac.uk/resources/briefing-papers/introduction-curation/data-citation-and-linking\">overview</a>&nbsp;without recommending a specific style. The DataCite website provides some <a href=\"https://www.datacite.org/whycitedata\">examples</a>. Dataverse, a data repository platform, generates a citation for a project from the <a href=\"http://thedata.org/citation\">metadata</a>&nbsp;that is entered for a study.&nbsp;</p>"},{"id":87,"question_id":172,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","text":"What types of data will you collect, create, acquire and/or record?","guidance":"Examples: Images, audio, video, text, tabular data, modeling data, spatial data, instrumentation data"},{"id":88,"question_id":173,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","text":"What file formats will your data be collected in? Will these formats allow for data re-use, sharing and long-term access to the data?","guidance":"<p>Proprietary file formats which require specialized software or hardware to use are not recommended, but may be necessary for certain data collection or analysis methods. Using open file formats or industry-standard formats (e.g. those which are widely used by a given community) is preferred whenever possible.</p>\r\n<p>Read more about file formats on UBC Library <a href=\"http://researchdata.library.ubc.ca/plan/format-your-data/\" target=\"_blank\">Research Data Website</a></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>"},{"id":89,"question_id":174,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","text":"If data are collected using laptops or mobile devices, please explain how will you will securely store and transfer the data.","guidance":"<p>Ensure that laptops or mobile devices are encrypted to prevent unauthorized access to information. UBC Information Technology provides<a href=\"http://it.ubc.ca/services/security/encryption-services\" target=\"_blank\"> encryption services</a>, including McAfee Whole Disk Encryption (WDE) which is appropriate for laptops. Supporting documentation is available for other<a href=\"http://cio.ubc.ca/sites/cio.ubc.ca/files/documents/resources/Encrypting%20Mobile%20Devices%20Guideline.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"> mobile devices</a>, including<a href=\"http://cio.ubc.ca/sites/cio.ubc.ca/files/documents/resources/How%20to%20encrypt%20USB%20sticks%20and%20other%20removable%20media%20Guideline.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"> storage media</a>. <a href=\"http://www.universitycounsel.ubc.ca/files/2013/06/policy104.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">UBC Policy #104</a> outlines the responsibilities of members of the University community with respect to the acceptable use and security of University electronic information and the services, devices and facilities that store or transmit this information.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>"},{"id":90,"question_id":175,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","text":"How much data do you anticipate collecting?  Include an estimate of how much storage space you will require (in megabytes, gigabytes, terabytes).  This estimate should also take into account storage space required for file versioning, backups, and the gro","guidance":"<p>The type of data you collect will impact your storage requirements.  Textual and tabular data files are usually very small (a few megabytes) unless you have a lot of data.  Video files are usually very large (hundreds of megabytes up to several gigabytes).  If you have a large amount of data (gigabytes or terabytes), it will be more challenging to share and transfer it.  You may need to consider networked storage options or more sophisticated backup methods.</p>\r\n<p>If your data will be changing frequently, please estimate how much extra storage will be required to store multiple versions.  If you are collecting data over a long period of time (e.g. several months or years), please describe your plan for adding additional storage to accommodate the growth of your data.</p>"},{"id":91,"question_id":176,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","text":"Are there are any existing data that you can re-use?  If so, please explain how you will obtain that data and integrate it into your research project.","guidance":"<p>There may be existing data that you can license or purchase for re-use. <a href=\"http://www.re3data.org/\" target=\"_blank\">re3data</a> is a directory of disciplinary data repositories you can check for data. Check the <a href=\"mailto:research.data@ubc.ca\" target=\"_blank\">&nbsp;</a><a href=\"http://researchdata.library.ubc.ca/find/\" target=\"_blank\">UBC Research Data Website</a> for help with finding and reusing existing data</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>"},{"id":92,"question_id":177,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","text":"What conventions and procedures will you use to structure, name and version control your files to ensure that your data is well-organized?\r\n","guidance":"<p>Ensuring that you and your research team are using the &lsquo;master&rsquo; version of your data is extremely important. Establishing conventions for naming and versioning your files is essential, especially when data may be available in different file formats or stored on different computers.</p>\r\n<p>More information on file naming and version control is available from the <a href=\"http://researchdata.library.ubc.ca/plan/organize-your-data/\" target=\"_blank\">UBC Research Data Website</a></p>\r\n<p>UBC Library&rsquo;s <a href=\"http://dvn.library.ubc.ca/dvn/\" target=\"_blank\">Dataverse </a>research data system can help with version control of your files.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>"},{"id":93,"question_id":178,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","text":"How will you make sure that documentation is created or captured consistently throughout your project?","guidance":"It is best to begin the documentation process at the start of a research project. Details or procedures may be forgotten if documentation is created at the end of a project."},{"id":94,"question_id":179,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","text":"Please list the metadata standard and tools you will use to document and describe your data.  If there is not an appropriate standard, please explain how you will ensure consistency in your documentation.","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-size: 14px;\">Metadata is a description of the contents and context of data files. Using a metadata standard (a set of required fields to fill out) helps ensure that your documentation is consistent, structured, and machine-readable, which is essential for depositing data in repositories and making it easily discoverable by search engines.</span></p>\r\n<p><span id=\"docs-internal-guid-dc9be2f5-e526-4591-7947-ae36301e4655\">There are general and discipline-specific <a href=\"http://researchdata.library.ubc.ca/plan/document-describe-your-data/\" target=\"_blank\">metadata standards and tools</a> for research data. For assistance with choosing a metadata standard, please contact us at <a href=\"mailto:research.data@ubc.ca\" target=\"_blank\">research.data@ubc.ca</a></span></p>"},{"id":95,"question_id":180,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","text":"What documentation will be needed for the data to be read and interpreted correctly in the future?  This includes study-level documentation, data-level description, and any other contextual information required to make the data usable by other researchers","guidance":"<p>Your documentation may include study-level information about:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>who created/collected the data</li>\r\n<li>when it was created</li>\r\n<li>any relevant study documents</li>\r\n<li>conditions of use</li>\r\n<li>contextual details about data collection methods and procedural documentation about how data files are stored, structured, and modified.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>A complete description of the data files may include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>naming and labelling conventions</li>\r\n<li>explanations of codes and variables</li>\r\n<li>any information or files require to reproduce derived data.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">More information about metadata is available at the UBC Library <a href=\"http://researchdata.library.ubc.ca/plan/document-describe-your-data/\" target=\"_blank\">Research Data Website</a></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>"},{"id":96,"question_id":181,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","text":"How will you ensure that sensitive data is stored securely and only accessible to the research team during the research project?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-size: 14px;\">The security measures you choose to implement will depend on the sensitivity of the data being stored. Data can be protected by limiting physical access to hard drives and file servers on which it is stored, by storing data on computers that do not have external network access (i.e. access to the Internet), through password protection, and by encrypting data files.<br /></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 14px;\">Sharing sensitive data via email and cloud storage services such as Dropbox is not recommended, since the security of these services cannot be trusted. Read more about security at the UBC Library </span><a href=\"http://researchdata.library.ubc.ca/plan/protect-your-data/\" target=\"_blank\">Research Data Website</a></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>"},{"id":97,"question_id":182,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","text":"How will your data be stored and backed up during your research project?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-size: 14px;\">Storing data on flash drives, laptops, computers, or external hard drives without a regular backup procedure is not recommended, because they are subject to hardware failure, viruses, file corruption, theft, loss, and human error. Likewise, multiple copies of data stored in the same physical location does little to mitigate risk.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 14px;\">Using software which automatically backs up your data and keeps it synchronized with a master copy is recommended. Copies of data should ideally be stored in separate physical locations to mitigate physical risks, e.g. fire. See more about data storage at UBC Library </span><a href=\"http://researchdata.library.ubc.ca/plan/store-and-back-up-your-data/\" target=\"_blank\">Research Data Website</a></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 14px;\">UBC Library also offers </span><a href=\"http://dvn.library.ubc.ca/dvn/\" target=\"_blank\">Dataverse </a><span style=\"font-size: 14px;\">for working with, storing and sharing datasets. For assistance with Dataverse, please contact </span><a href=\"mailto:research.data@ubc.ca\" target=\"_blank\">research.data@ubc.ca</a></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>"},{"id":98,"question_id":183,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","text":"Please describe how you will prepare the data for preservation and access, including any necessary procedures for data cleaning, normalization or de-identification.  Explain how you will prevent data from being lost while processing and converting files. ","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-size: 14px;\">It is likely that you will have multiple versions of your data (raw, processed, analyzed, final), and your data may be stored in different file formats depending on how they were collected and analyzed.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 14px;\">Digital information may be lost while converting files from one format to another (e.g. converting an image from a non-compressed &lsquo;lossless&rsquo; TIFF file to a compressed &lsquo;lossy&rsquo; JPG file), so changes to file formats should be documented.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 14px;\">Identify what steps are needed after your project is completed in order to ensure the data you are choosing to preserve or share is anonymous, error-free, and converted to recommended formats with a minimal risk of data loss.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 14px;\">Read more about </span><a href=\"http://data-archive.ac.uk/create-manage/format/formats\" target=\"_blank\">file formats</a><span style=\"font-size: 14px;\"> and </span><a href=\"http://data-archive.ac.uk/create-manage/consent-ethics/anonymisation\" target=\"_blank\">anonymization</a><span style=\"font-size: 14px;\"> on the UK Data Archive Website.</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>"},{"id":99,"question_id":184,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","text":"At the end of your research project, where will you deposit your data for long-term preservation and access? ","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-size: 14px;\">Please describe how you will identify a data repository or data centre for your data. </span><a href=\"http://www.re3data.org/\" target=\"_blank\">re3data.org</a><span style=\"font-size: 14px;\"> is a directory of potential open data repositories. Note any details about the curation of the data and what aspects of the curation are your responsibility versus what the repository assumes. See if the data repository will provide a statement agreeing to these terms of deposit that can be included with your data management plan.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 14px;\">UBC researchers can deposit datasets in </span><a href=\"http://dvn.library.ubc.ca/dvn/\" target=\"_blank\">Dataverse</a><span style=\"font-size: 14px;\"> for various&nbsp;data formats such as those produced by SPSS, R or SAS, or </span><a href=\"https://circle.ubc.ca/\" target=\"_blank\">cIRcle </a><span style=\"font-size: 14px;\">for basic data formats such as Excel. For larger datasets, please contact </span><a href=\"mailto:research.data@ubc.ca\" target=\"_blank\">research.data@ubc.ca</a></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>"},{"id":100,"question_id":185,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","text":"Which data are selected for preservation and access will depend on potential reuse value, whether there are obligations to either retain or destroy data, and the resources required to properly curate the data and ensure that it remains usable in the futur","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-size: 14px;\">This will depend on potential reuse value, whether there are obligations to either retain or destroy data, and the resources required to properly curate the data and ensure that it remains usable in the future. In some circumstances, it may be feasible to preserve all versions of the data (e.g. raw, processed, analyzed, final), but in others, it may be preferable to only keep only selected data (e.g. transcripts instead of audio interviews).</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>"},{"id":101,"question_id":186,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","text":"What data will you be sharing and in what form? (e.g. raw, processed, analyzed, final). Consider which data may need to be shared in order to meet institutional or funding requirements, and which data may be restricted because of confidentiality/privacy i","guidance":""},{"id":102,"question_id":187,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","text":"How will you be sharing your data? (e.g. institutional repository, a specialized data archive, project website, informal/on-request sharing).  Include a brief description of any resources needed to share your data (equipment, systems, expertise, etc.). \r\n","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-size: 14px;\">Where you share your data depends on the complexity and size of your data. Smaller, low-risk datasets can be shared via institutional or disciplinary repositories and project websites. Larger datasets or datasets with more stringent security requirements cannot be easily transferred over the Internet. Read more about sharing data at the UBC Library </span><a href=\"http://researchdata.library.ubc.ca/share/\" target=\"_blank\">Research Data Website</a></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 14px;\">Researchers at UBC can deposit datasets in </span><a href=\"http://dvn.library.ubc.ca/dvn/\" target=\"_blank\">Dataverse</a><span style=\"font-size: 14px;\"> for complex data formats such as those produced by SPSS, R or SAS, or </span><a href=\"https://circle.ubc.ca/\" target=\"_blank\">cIRcle </a><span style=\"font-size: 14px;\">for basic data formats such as Excel. For large datasets, please contact </span><a href=\"mailto:research.data@ubc.ca\" target=\"_blank\">research.data@ubc.ca</a></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>"},{"id":103,"question_id":188,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","text":"Please describe whether there will be any restrictions placed on your data when they are made available and who may access them.  If data are not openly available, describe the process for gaining access.","guidance":"<p>It may be necessary or desirable to restrict access to your data for a limited time or to a limited number of people, for:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>ethical reasons (privacy and confidentiality) </li>\r\n<li>economic reasons (patents and commercialization)</li>\r\n<li>intellectual property reasons (e.g. ownership of the original dataset on which yours is based) </li>\r\n<li>or to comply with a journal publishing policy.  </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Strategies to mitigate these issues may include: </p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>anonymising or aggregating data</li>\r\n<li>gaining participant consent for data sharing</li>\r\n<li>gaining permissions to share adapted or modified data</li>\r\n<li>and agreeing to a limited embargo period.</li>\r\n</ul>"},{"id":104,"question_id":189,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","text":"What type of end-user license will you include with your data? Please include a copy of this license with your Data Management Plan. ","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-size: 14px;\">Assigning an end-user license allows you to define the terms of use for your data. Please consider a </span><a href=\"http://researchdata.library.ubc.ca/share/license-your-data/\" target=\"_blank\">Creative Commons or Open Data license</a><span style=\"font-size: 14px;\">.</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>"},{"id":105,"question_id":190,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","text":"Who will be responsible for data management during the project? (i.e. during collection, processing, analysis, documentation).  Identify staff and organizational roles and their responsibilities for carrying out the data management plan (DMP), including t","guidance":""},{"id":106,"question_id":191,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","text":"What will happen when personnel changes occur or if the principal investigator leaves the institution before the project has concluded?","guidance":""},{"id":107,"question_id":192,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","text":"Who will be responsible for data sharing and preservation after the project has concluded? Indicate the party who will have primary responsibility for how the data will persist over time when the original personnel have moved on. ","guidance":""},{"id":108,"question_id":193,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:39:51 UTC","text":"Who will be responsible for data sharing and preservation after the project has concluded? Indicate the party who will have primary responsibility for how the data will persist over time when the original personnel have moved on. ","guidance":"<p>More information about estimating cost for data management is available through the <a href=\"http://data-archive.ac.uk/create-manage/planning-for-sharing/costing\" target=\"_blank\">UK Data Archive</a>. This information should be incorporated into any grant applications for your project.</p>"},{"id":109,"question_id":194,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:11 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:11 UTC","text":"What types of data will you collect, create, link to, acquire and/or record?","guidance":"<p>Examples: numeric, images, audio, video, text, tabular data, modeling data, spatial data, instrumentation data.</p>"},{"id":110,"question_id":195,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:11 UTC","updated_at":"2020-09-11 17:42:01 UTC","text":"What file formats will your data be collected in? Will these formats allow for data re-use, sharing and long-term access to the data?","guidance":"<p>Proprietary file formats requiring specialized software or hardware to use are not recommended, but may be necessary for certain data collection or analysis methods. Using open file formats or industry-standard formats (e.g. those widely used by a given community) is preferred whenever possible.</p>\r\n<p>Read more about file formats: <a href=\"http://researchdata.library.ubc.ca/plan/format-your-data/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">UBC Library</a> or <a href=\"https://www.ukdataservice.ac.uk/manage-data/format/file-formats.aspx\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">UK Data Service</a>.</p>"},{"id":111,"question_id":196,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:11 UTC","updated_at":"2020-09-11 17:43:07 UTC","text":"What conventions and procedures will you use to structure, name and version-control your files to help you and others better understand how your data are organized?","guidance":"<p>It is important to keep track of different copies or versions of files, files held in different formats or locations, and information cross-referenced between files. This process is called 'version control'.</p>\r\n<p>Logical file structures, informative naming conventions, and clear indications of file versions, all contribute to better use of your data during and after your research project. &nbsp;These practices will help ensure that you and your research team are using the appropriate version of your data, and minimize confusion regarding copies on different computers and/or on different media.</p>\r\n<p>Read more about file naming and version control: <a href=\"http://researchdata.library.ubc.ca/plan/organize-your-data/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">UBC Library</a> or <a href=\"https://www.ukdataservice.ac.uk/manage-data/format/versioning.aspx\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">UK Data Service</a>.</p>"},{"id":112,"question_id":197,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:11 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:11 UTC","text":"What documentation will be needed for the data to be read and interpreted correctly in the future?","guidance":"<p>Typically, good documentation includes information about the study, data-level descriptions, and any other contextual information required to make the data usable by other researchers.  Other elements you should document, as applicable, include: research methodology used, variable definitions, vocabularies, classification systems, units of measurement, assumptions made, format and file type of the data, a description of the data capture and collection methods, explanation of data coding and analysis performed (including syntax files), and details of who has worked on the project and performed each task, etc.</p>"},{"id":113,"question_id":198,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:11 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:11 UTC","text":"How will you make sure that documentation is created or captured consistently throughout your project?","guidance":"<p>Consider how you will capture this information and where it will be recorded, ideally in advance of data collection and analysis, to ensure accuracy, consistency, and completeness of the documentation.  Often, resources you've already created can contribute to this (e.g. publications, websites, progress reports, etc.).  It is useful to consult regularly with members of the research team to capture potential changes in data collection/processing that need to be reflected in the documentation.  Individual roles and workflows should include gathering data documentation as a key element.</p>"},{"id":114,"question_id":199,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:11 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:11 UTC","text":"If you are using a metadata standard and/or tools to document and describe your data, please list here.","guidance":"<p>There are many general and domain-specific metadata standards.  Dataset documentation should be provided in one of these standard, machine readable, openly-accessible formats to enable the effective exchange of information between users and systems.  These standards are often based on language-independent data formats such as XML, RDF, and JSON. There are many metadata standards based on these formats, including discipline-specific standards.</p> <p>Read more about metadata standards:  <a href=\"http://dcc.ac.uk/resources/metadata-standards\" target=\"_blank\">UK Digital Curation Centre's Disciplinary Metadata</a>. </p>"},{"id":115,"question_id":200,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:11 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:11 UTC","text":"What are the anticipated storage requirements for your project, in terms of storage space (in megabytes, gigabytes, terabytes, etc.) and the length of time you will be storing it?","guidance":"<p>Storage-space estimates should take into account requirements for file versioning, backups, and growth over time.  </p> <p>If you are collecting data over a long period (e.g. several months or years), your data storage and backup strategy should accommodate data growth. Similarly, a long-term storage plan is necessary if you intend to retain your data after the research project.</p>"},{"id":116,"question_id":201,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:11 UTC","updated_at":"2020-09-11 17:44:37 UTC","text":"How and where will your data be stored and backed up during your research project?","guidance":"<p>The risk of losing data due to human error, natural disasters, or other mishaps can be mitigated by following the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://dataabinitio.com/?p=501\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">3-2-1 backup rule</a>:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Have at least three copies of your data.</li>\r\n<li>Store the copies on two different media.</li>\r\n<li>Keep one backup copy offsite</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Data may be stored using optical or magnetic media, which can be removable (e.g. DVD and USB drives), fixed (e.g. desktop or laptop hard drives), or networked (e.g. networked drives or cloud-based servers). Each storage method has benefits and drawbacks that should be considered when determining the most appropriate solution.</p>\r\n<p>Further information on storage and backup practices is available from the <a href=\"https://www.sheffield.ac.uk/library/rdm/storage\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">University of Sheffield Library</a> and the <a href=\"https://www.ukdataservice.ac.uk/manage-data/store.aspx\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">UK Data Service</a>.</p>"},{"id":117,"question_id":202,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:11 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:11 UTC","text":"How will the research team and other collaborators access, modify, and contribute data throughout the project?","guidance":"<p>An ideal solution is one that facilitates co-operation and ensures data security, yet is able to be adopted by users with minimal training. Transmitting data between locations or within research teams can be challenging for data management infrastructure. Relying on email for data transfer is not a robust or secure solution. Third-party commercial file sharing services (such as Google Drive and Dropbox) facilitate file exchange, but they are not necessarily permanent or secure, and are often located outside Canada. Please contact your Library to develop the best solution for your research project.</p>"},{"id":118,"question_id":203,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:11 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:11 UTC","text":"Where will you deposit your data for long-term preservation and access at the end of your research project?","guidance":"<p>The issue of data retention should be considered early in the research lifecycle.  Data-retention decisions can be driven by external policies (e.g. funding agencies, journal publishers), or by an understanding of the enduring value of a given set of data.  The need to preserve data in the short-term (i.e. for peer-verification purposes) or long-term (for data of lasting value), will influence the choice of data repository or archive.  A helpful analogy is to think of creating a 'living will' for the data, that is, a plan describing how future researchers will have continued access to the data.</p><p>If you need assistance locating a suitable data repository or archive, please contact your Library.</p><p><a href=\"http://www.re3data.org/\" target=\"_blank\">re3data.org</a> is a directory of potential open data repositories. Verify whether or not the data repository will provide a statement agreeing to the terms of deposit outlined in your Data Management Plan.</p>"},{"id":119,"question_id":204,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:11 UTC","updated_at":"2020-09-11 17:46:15 UTC","text":"Indicate how you will ensure your data is preservation ready. Consider preservation-friendly file formats, ensuring file integrity, anonymization and de-identification, inclusion of supporting documentation.","guidance":"<p>Some data formats are optimal for long-term preservation of data. For example, non-proprietary file formats, such as text ('.txt') and comma-separated ('.csv'), are considered preservation-friendly. The UK Data Service provides a useful table of file formats for various types of data. Keep in mind that preservation-friendly files converted from one format to another may lose information (e.g. converting from an uncompressed TIFF file to a compressed JPG file), so changes to file formats should be documented.</p>\r\n<p>Identify steps required following project completion in order to ensure the data you are choosing to preserve or share is anonymous, error-free, and converted to recommended formats with a minimal risk of data loss.</p>\r\n<p>Read more about anonymization: <a href=\"https://researchdata.library.ubc.ca/share/anonymize-and-de-identify/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">UBC Library</a> or <a href=\"https://www.ukdataservice.ac.uk/manage-data/legal-ethical/anonymisation.aspx\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">UK Data Service</a>.</p>"},{"id":120,"question_id":205,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:11 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:11 UTC","text":"What data will you be sharing and in what form? (e.g. raw, processed, analyzed, final).","guidance":"<p><b>Raw data</b> are the data directly obtained from the instrument, simulation or survey.</p><p><b>Processed data</b> result from some manipulation of the raw data in order to eliminate errors or outliers, to prepare the data for analysis, to derive new variables, or to de-identify the human participants. </p><p><b>Analyzed data</b> are the the results of qualitative, statistical, or mathematical analysis of the processed data. They can be presented as graphs, charts or statistical tables.</p><p><b>Final data</b> are processed data that have, if needed, been converted into a preservation-friendly format.</p><p>Consider which data may need to be shared in order to meet institutional or funding requirements, and which data may be restricted because of confidentiality/privacy/intellectual property considerations.</p>"},{"id":121,"question_id":206,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:11 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:11 UTC","text":"Have you considered what type of end-user license to include with your data?","guidance":"<p>Licenses determine what uses can be made of your data. Funding agencies and/or data repositories may have end-user license requirements in place; if not, they may still be able to guide you in the development of a license. Once created, please consider including a copy of your end-user license with your Data Management Plan.  Note that only the intellectual property rights holder(s) can issue a license, so it is crucial to clarify who owns those rights. </p><p>There are several types of standard licenses available to researchers, such as the <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/choose/\" target=\"_blank\">Creative Commons licenses</a> and the <a href=\"http://opendatacommons.org/licenses/\" target=\"_blank\">Open Data Commons licenses</a>. In fact, for most datasets it is easier to use a standard license rather than to devise a custom-made one. Note that even if you choose to make your data part of the public domain, it is preferable to make this explicit by using a license such as Creative Commons'  CC0. </p> <p>Read more about data licensing: <a href=\"http://www.dcc.ac.uk/resources/how-guides/license-research-data\" target=\"_blank\">UK Digital Curation Centre</a>. </p>"},{"id":122,"question_id":207,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:11 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:11 UTC","text":"What steps will be taken to help the research community know that your data exists?","guidance":"<p>Possibilities include: data registries, repositories, indexes, word-of-mouth, publications.</p><p>How will the data be accessed (Web service, ftp, etc.)? If possible, choose a repository that will assign a persistent identifier (such as a DOI) to your dataset. This will ensure a stable access to the dataset and make it retrievable by various discovery tools.</p><p>One of the best ways to refer other researchers to your deposited datasets is to cite them the same way you cite other types of publications (articles, books, proceedings). The Digital Curation Centre provides a detailed <a href=\"http://www.dcc.ac.uk/resources/how-guides/cite-datasets\" target=\"_blank\">guide</a> on data citation.Note that some data repositories also create links from datasets to their associated papers, thus increasing the visibility of the publications.</p><p>Contact your Library for assistance in making your dataset visible and easily accessible. </p><p>Reused from NIH. (2009). <a href=\"https://grants.nih.gov/grants/sharing_key_elements_data_sharing_plan.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Key Elements to Consider in Preparing a Data Sharing Plan Under NIH Extramural Support</a>. National Institutes of Health.</p>"},{"id":123,"question_id":208,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:11 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:11 UTC","text":"Identify who will be responsible for managing this project's data during and after the project and the major data management tasks for which they will be responsible.","guidance":"<p>Your data management plan has identified important data activities in your project. Identify who will be responsible -- individuals or organizations -- for carrying out these parts of your data management plan. This could also include the timeframe associated with these staff responsibilities and any training needed to prepare staff for these duties.</p>"},{"id":124,"question_id":209,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:12 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:12 UTC","text":"How will responsibilities for managing data activities be handled if substantive changes happen in the personnel overseeing the project's data, including a change of Principal Investigator?","guidance":"<p>Indicate a succession strategy for these data in the event that one or more people responsible for the data leaves (e.g. a graduate student leaving after graduation). Describe the process to be followed in the event that the Principal Investigator leaves the project. In some instances, a co-investigator or the department or division overseeing this research will assume responsibility.</p>"},{"id":125,"question_id":210,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:12 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:12 UTC","text":"What resources will you require to implement your data management plan? What do you estimate the overall cost for data management to be?","guidance":"<p>This estimate should incorporate data management costs incurred during the project as well as those required for the longer-term support for the data after the project is finished. Items to consider in the latter category of expenses include the costs of curating and providing long-term access to the data. Some funding agencies state explicitly the support that they will provide to meet the cost of preparing data for deposit. This might include technical aspects of data management, training requirements, file storage & backup, and contributions of non-project staff.</p>"},{"id":126,"question_id":211,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:12 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:12 UTC","text":"If your research project includes sensitive data, how will you ensure that it is securely managed and accessible only to approved members of the project?","guidance":"<p>Consider where, how, and to whom sensitive data with acknowledged long-term value should be made available, and how long it should be archived. These decisions should align with Research Ethics Board requirements. The methods used to share data will be dependent on a number of factors such as the type, size, complexity and degree of sensitivity of data. Outline problems anticipated in sharing data, along with causes and possible measures to mitigate these. Problems may include confidentiality, lack of consent agreements, or concerns about Intellectual Property Rights, among others. In some instances, an embargo period may be justified; these may be defined by a funding agency's policy on research data. </p><p>Reused from: DCC. (2013). <a href=\"http://www.dcc.ac.uk/resources/data-management-plans\" target=\"_blank\">Checklist for a Data Management Plan</a>. v.4.0. Edinburgh: Digital Curation Centre</p><p>Restrictions can be imposed by limiting physical access to storage devices, by placing data on computers that do not have external network access (i.e. access to the Internet), through password protection, and by encrypting files.  Sensitive data should never be shared via email or cloud storage services such as Dropbox.</p>"},{"id":127,"question_id":212,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:12 UTC","updated_at":"2020-09-11 17:47:09 UTC","text":"If applicable, what strategies will you undertake to address secondary uses of sensitive data?","guidance":"<p>Obtaining the appropriate consent from research participants is an important step in assuring Research Ethics Boards that the data may be shared with researchers outside your project. The consent statement may identify certain conditions clarifying the uses of the data by other researchers. For example, it may stipulate that the data will only be shared for non-profit research purposes or that the data will not be linked with personally identified data from other sources.</p>\r\n<p>Read more about data security: <a href=\"https://www.ukdataservice.ac.uk/manage-data/store/security.aspx\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">UK Data Service</a></p>"},{"id":128,"question_id":213,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:12 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:12 UTC","text":"How will you manage legal, ethical, and intellectual property issues?","guidance":"<p>Compliance with privacy legislation and laws that may impose content restrictions in the data should be discussed with your institution's privacy officer or research services office. Research Ethics Boards are central to the research process.</p><p>Include here a description concerning ownership, licensing, and intellectual property rights of the data. Terms of reuse must be clearly stated, in line with the relevant legal and ethical requirements where applicable (e.g., subject consent, permissions, restrictions, etc.).</p>"},{"id":129,"question_id":194,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:12 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:12 UTC","text":"Quels types de données allez-vous recueillir, créer, lier, acquérir ou enregistrer?","guidance":"<p>Exemples : données numériques, images, audio, vidéo, texte, données tabulaires, données de modélisation, données spatiales, données d'instrumentation</p>"},{"id":130,"question_id":195,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:12 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:12 UTC","text":"Dans quels formats de fichier vos données seront-elles recueillies? Ces formats permettront-ils la réutilisation des données, le partage et l'accès à long terme aux données?","guidance":"<p>Les formats propriétaires nécessitant l'utilisation de logiciels ou de matériels spécialisés ne sont pas recommandés, mais peuvent être nécessaires pour certaines méthodes d'analyse ou de collecte des données. L'utilisation de formats de fichier ouverts ou de formats conformes aux normes de l'industrie (p. ex. les formats largement utilisés par une communauté donnée) est préférable dans la mesure du possible. </p>Pour en savoir plus sur les formats de fichier, consultez les sites suivants : <a href=\"http://researchdata.library.ubc.ca/plan/format-your-data/\" target=\"_blank\">UBC Library</a> ou <a href=\"http://data-archive.ac.uk/create-manage/format/formats\" target=\"_blank\">UK Data Archive</a>.</p>"},{"id":131,"question_id":196,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:12 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:12 UTC","text":"Quelles conventions et procédures utiliserez-vous pour structurer et nommer vos fichiers et en contrôler les versions afin de vous aider, ainsi que les utilisateurs potentiels, à mieux comprendre la façon dont vos données sont organisées?","guidance":"<p>Il est important de garder la trace des multiples copies ou versions des fichiers, des différents fichiers conservés dans plus d'un format ou à divers emplacements et des renseignements qui font l'objet de renvois croisés entre les fichiers. Ce processus s'appelle « contrôle de versions ».  </p>Des structures de fichier logiques, des conventions d'appellation informatives et des indications claires des versions de fichier aident à mieux utiliser vos données pendant et après votre projet de recherche. Ces pratiques permettront à votre équipe de recherche et vous de vous assurer que vous utilisez toujours la version appropriée de vos données et de réduire la confusion concernant les copies enregistrées sur différents ordinateurs  ou médias. </p>Pour en savoir plus sur l'appellation des fichiers et le contrôle des versions, consultez les sites suivants : <a href=\"http://researchdata.library.ubc.ca/plan/organize-your-data/\" target=\"_blank\">UBC Library</a> ou <a href=\"http://data-archive.ac.uk/create-manage/format/versions\" target=\"_blank\">UK Data Archive</a>.</p>"},{"id":132,"question_id":197,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:12 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:12 UTC","text":"Quels documents seront nécessaires pour que les données soient lues et interprétées correctement dans le futur?","guidance":"<p>Normalement, une bonne documentation comprend des renseignements sur l'étude, des descriptions des éléments tels que les variables et d'autres renseignements contextuels requis pour que d'autres chercheurs puissent utiliser les données. Parmi les autres éléments à documenter, le cas échéant, mentionnons la méthodologie de recherche utilisée, les définitions des variables, les vocabulaires, les systèmes de classification, les unités de mesure, les hypothèses formulées, le type de format et de fichier des données, une description des données recueillies et des méthodes de collecte, l'explication de l'analyse et de la codification des données réalisées (y compris les fichiers de syntaxe) et les renseignements sur les personnes ayant travaillé au projet et réalisé chacune des tâches, etc. </p>"},{"id":133,"question_id":198,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:12 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:12 UTC","text":"Comment vous assurerez-vous de documenter le projet de façon systématique tout au long du processus?","guidance":"<p>Examinez la façon dont vous saisirez ces renseignements et l'emplacement où ils seront enregistrés, idéalement avant de procéder à l'analyse et à la collecte de données, afin d'assurer l'exactitude, l'uniformité et l'exhaustivité des documents. Souvent, les ressources que vous avez déjà créées peuvent contribuer à cela (p. ex. publications, sites Web, rapports d'étape, etc.). Il est utile de consulter régulièrement les membres de l'équipe de recherche afin de connaître les changements possibles dans la collecte ou le traitement des données qui doivent être pris en considération dans les documents. La collecte des renseignements sur les données doit être une partie intégrante des responsabilités des membres de l'équipe et des opérations.</p>"},{"id":134,"question_id":199,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:12 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:12 UTC","text":"Si vous utilisez une norme de métadonnées ou des outils pour documenter et décrire vos données, veuillez les indiquer ici.","guidance":"<p>Il existe plusieurs normes de métadonnées générales et propres à un domaine. Les informations sur l'ensemble de données doivent être fournies dans un de ces formats standards, ouverts et lisibles par machine afin de permettre l'échange efficace d'information entre les utilisateurs et les systèmes. Ces normes s'appuient souvent sur des formats de données comme XML, RDF et JSON qui ne sont pas liés à un langage de programmation. Il y a plusieurs normes de métadonnées fondées sur ces formats, y compris des normes propres à une discipline.</p> Pour en savoir plus sur les normes de métadonnées, consultez le site suivant :  <a href=\"http://dcc.ac.uk/resources/metadata-standards\" target=\"_blank\">UK Digital Curation Centre's Disciplinary Metadata</a>. </p>"},{"id":135,"question_id":200,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:12 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:12 UTC","text":"Quelles sont les besoins de stockage anticipés pour votre projet en matière d'espace (en mégaoctets, gigaoctets, téraoctets, etc.) et de durée de stockage?","guidance":"<p>Les estimations concernant l'espace de stockage doivent prendre en considération les exigences pour le versionnage de fichiers, les sauvegardes et la croissance du nombre de fichiers au fil du temps. </p> Si vous recueillez des données sur une longue période (p. ex. plusieurs mois ou années), votre stratégie en matière de sauvegarde et de stockage des données doit tenir compte de la croissance des données. De même, un plan de stockage à long terme est nécessaire si vous avez l'intention de conserver vos données après le projet de recherche. </p>"},{"id":136,"question_id":201,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:12 UTC","updated_at":"2017-09-08 21:09:17 UTC","text":"Comment vos données seront-elles stockées et sauvegardées pendant votre projet de recherche et à quel endroit le seront-elles?","guidance":"<p>Le risque de perdre des donn&eacute;es en raison d'une erreur humaine, de catastrophes naturelles ou d'autres m&eacute;saventures peut &ecirc;tre att&eacute;nu&eacute; en respectant les <a href=\"http://dataabinitio.com/?p=501\" target=\"_blank\">3-2-1 r&egrave;gles de sauvegarde</a>:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Poss&eacute;der au moins trois&nbsp;copies de vos donn&eacute;es.</li>\r\n<li>Stocker les copies sur deux&nbsp;types de m&eacute;dias diff&eacute;rents.</li>\r\n<li>Conserver une copie de sauvegarde hors site</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Les donn&eacute;es peuvent &ecirc;tre stock&eacute;es au moyen d'un m&eacute;dia optique ou magn&eacute;tique qui peut &ecirc;tre amovible (p.&nbsp;ex. DVD et cl&eacute;s USB), fixe (p.&nbsp;ex. lecteurs de disque dur d'ordinateur de bureau ou d'ordinateur portatif) ou en r&eacute;seau (p. ex. lecteurs en r&eacute;seau ou serveurs bas&eacute;s sur l'infonuagique). Chaque m&eacute;thode de stockage comporte des avantages et des inconv&eacute;nients qui doivent &ecirc;tre pris en consid&eacute;ration au moment de d&eacute;terminer la solution la plus appropri&eacute;e. De plus amples renseignements sur les pratiques de stockage et de sauvegarde sont disponibles sur les sites suivants : <a href=\"https://www.sheffield.ac.uk/library/rdm/safedata\" target=\"_blank\">University of Sheffield Library</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.data-archive.ac.uk/create-manage/storage/back-up\" target=\"_blank\">UK Data Archive</a>.</p>"},{"id":137,"question_id":202,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:12 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:12 UTC","text":"Comment l'équipe de recherche et d'autres collaborateurs pourront-ils accéder aux données, modifier celles-ci ou en contribuer de nouvelles tout au long du projet?","guidance":"<p>Une solution idéale est une solution qui facilite la collaboration, assure la sécurité des données et qui peut être adoptée par les utilisateurs en suivant une formation minimale. La transmission de données entre les différents espaces de travail ou au sein d'équipes de recherche n'est pas toujours simple selon l'infrastructure de gestion des données. Se fier au courrier électronique pour le transfert de données n'est pas une solution robuste ou sécuritaire. Les services de partage de fichiers commerciaux de tiers (comme Google Drive et Dropbox) facilitent l'échange de fichiers, mais ne sont pas nécessairement permanents ou sécuritaires et sont souvent situés à l'extérieur du Canada. Communiquez avec votre bibliothèque pour mettre au point la meilleure solution pour votre projet de recherche.</p>"},{"id":138,"question_id":203,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:12 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:12 UTC","text":"Où déposerez-vous vos données en vue de l'accès et de la préservation à long terme à la fin de votre projet de recherche?","guidance":"<p>La question de la rétention des données doit être examinée tôt dans le cycle de vie de la recherche. Les décisions relatives à la rétention des données peuvent être dictées par des politiques externes (p. ex. organismes de financement, éditeurs de revues) ou par une compréhension de la valeur durable d'un ensemble de données déterminé. La nécessité de préserver les données à court terme (c.-à-d. à des fins de vérification par des pairs) ou à long terme (pour les données de valeur durable) influencera le choix de l'archive ou du dépôt de données. Une analogie utile consiste à penser à créer un « testament de vie » pour les données, c'est-à-dire un plan qui décrit la façon dont les futurs chercheurs continueront d'avoir accès aux données.</p>Si vous avez besoin d'aide pour trouver une archive ou un dépôt de données approprié, communiquez avec votre bibliothèque.</p> <a href=\"http://www.re3data.org/\" target=\"_blank\">re3data.org</a> est un répertoire de dépôts de données ouvertes. Vérifiez si le dépôt de données pourra vous fournir une confirmation que les termes du dépôt énoncés dans votre plan de gestion des données seront respectés.</p>"},{"id":139,"question_id":204,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:12 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:12 UTC","text":"Indiquez comment vous vous assurerez que vos données sont prêtes pour la conservation. À prendre en considération: formats de fichier appropriés pour la conservation mais qui préservent l'intégrité des données;  anonymisation et dépersonnalisation des fichiers, y compris les fichiers de documentation. ","guidance":"<p>Certains formats de données sont idéals pour la conservation à long terme des données. Par exemple, les formats de fichier non-propriétaires, comme le format texte (.txt) et les valeurs séparées par des virgules (.csv), sont considérés comme des formats conçus pour la conservation. Le UK Data Archive (dépôt de données du Royaume-Uni) fournit un tableau utile des formats de fichier pour divers types de données. Il faut se rappeler que les fichiers qui sont convertis d'un format à l'autre peuvent perdre des renseignements (p. ex. en convertissant un fichier TIFF non compressé à un fichier JPG compressé). Ainsi, les modifications apportées aux formats de fichier doivent être documentées. </p>Déterminez les étapes à suivre à la fin d'un projet pour s'assurer que les données que vous choisissez de préserver ou de partager sont anonymes, exemptes d'erreur et converties dans les formats recommandés en assurant un risque minimal de perte de données. </p> Pour en savoir plus sur l'anonymisation, consultez les sites suivants :<a href=\"http://researchdata.library.ubc.ca/plan/format-your-data/\" target=\"_blank\">UBC Library</a> ou <a href=\"http://data-archive.ac.uk/create-manage/consent-ethics/anonymisation\" target=\"_blank\">UK Data Archive</a>.</p>"},{"id":140,"question_id":205,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:12 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:12 UTC","text":"Quelles données partagerez-vous et sous quelle forme? (p. ex. données brutes, traitées, analysées, définitives)","guidance":"<p><b>Les données brutes</b> sont des données obtenues directement de l'instrument, de la simulation ou de l'enquête.</p><b>Les données traitées</b> découlent d'une certaine manipulation des données brutes afin d'éliminer les erreurs ou les valeurs aberrantes, de préparer les données en vue de l'analyse, d'obtenir de nouvelles variables ou d'anonymiser les participants humains. </p><b>Les données analysées</b> sont les résultats d'une analyse qualitative, statistique ou mathématique des données traitées.  Elles peuvent être présentées sous forme de graphiques, de diagrammes ou de tableaux statistiques.</p><b>Les données définitives</b> sont des données traitées qui ont été converties, au besoin, dans un format pouvant être préservé.</p>Examinez les données qui peuvent devoir être partagées afin de respecter les exigences institutionnelles ou de financement et les données qui peuvent faire l'objet de restrictions en raison de préoccupations relatives à la confidentialité, au respect de la vie privée et à la propriété intellectuelle.</p>"},{"id":141,"question_id":206,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:12 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:12 UTC","text":"Avez-vous examiné quel type de licence d'utilisation inclure avec vos données?","guidance":"<p>Les licences déterminent les utilisations permises de vos données. Les organismes de financement et les dépôts de données peuvent avoir des exigences relatives à la licence d'utilisation. Si ce n'est pas le cas, ils peuvent vous guider dans l'établissement d'une licence. Une fois la licence créée, veuillez envisager d'inclure une copie de votre licence d'utilisation avec votre plan de gestion des données. Il convient de noter que seuls les titulaires des droits de propriété intellectuelle peuvent émettre une licence, il est dont essentiel de préciser à qui appartient ces droits.</p> Il existe plusieurs types de licences standards mises à la disposition des chercheurs comme  les <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/choose/\" target=\"_blank\">licences Creative Commons</a> et les <a href=\"http://opendatacommons.org/licenses/\" target=\"_blank\">licences Open Data Commons</a>. En fait, pour la plupart des ensembles de données, il est plus facile d'utiliser une licence standard plutôt que de concevoir une licence personnalisée. Veuillez noter que même si vous choisissez de rendre vos données publiques, il est préférable de l'indiquer de manière explicite en utilisant une licence comme celle CC0 de Creative Commons. </p> Pour en savoir plus sur les licences d'exploitation des données, consultez le site suivant : <a href=\"http://www.dcc.ac.uk/resources/how-guides/license-research-data\" target=\"_blank\">UK Digital Curation Centre</a>. </p>"},{"id":142,"question_id":207,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:12 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:12 UTC","text":"Quelles mesures seront prises pour faire connaître l'existence de vos données au milieu de la recherche?","guidance":"<p>Les possibilités comprennent : registres de données, dépôts, index, bouche-à-oreille, publications.</p><p>Comment pourra-t-on accéder aux données (service Web, ftp, etc.)? &nbsp;Dans la mesure du possible, choisissez un dépôt qui attribuera un identifiant constant (comme un DOI) à votre ensemble de données. Cela permettra ainsi d'assurer un accès stable à l'ensemble de données et il pourra être accessible grâce à divers outils de recherche.</p><p>Une des meilleures façons d'orienter d'autres chercheurs vers vos ensembles de données déposés consiste à les citer de la même façon que d'autres types de publications (articles, livres, procédures). Le Digital Curation Centre fournit un <a href=\"http://www.dcc.ac.uk/resources/how-guides/cite-datasets\" target=\"_blank\">guide</a> détaillé sur la citation des données. Veuillez noter que certains dépôts de données établissent également des liens entre les ensembles de données et les articles connexes, ce qui accroît ainsi la visibilité des publications.<p>Communiquez avec votre bibliothèque pour obtenir de l'aide pour donner de la visibilité à votre ensemble de données et le rendre facilement accessible.&nbsp;</p><p>Réutilisé des NIH. (2009). <a href=\"https://grants.nih.gov/grants/sharing_key_elements_data_sharing_plan.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Key Elements to Consider in Preparing a Data Sharing Plan Under NIH Extramural Support (Principaux éléments à prendre en considération dans l'établissement d'un plan de partage des données en vertu du soutien extra-muros des NIH)</a>. National Institutes of Health.</p>"},{"id":143,"question_id":208,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:12 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:12 UTC","text":"Identifiez qui sera responsable de la gestion des données de ce projet pendant et après le projet ainsi que les principales tâches associées à ces responsabilités.","guidance":"<p>Votre plan de gestion des données a identifié les activités importantes relatives à la gestion des données dans le cadre de votre projet. Indiquez les responsables  -- des personnes ou des organisations -- de l'exécution de ces parties de votre plan de gestion des données. Cela pourrait également comprendre le calendrier associé à ces responsabilités et toute formation nécessaire afin de préparer le personnel à assumer ces fonctions. </p>"},{"id":144,"question_id":209,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:12 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:12 UTC","text":"De quelle façon les responsabilités relatives à la gestion des données seront-elles gérées si des changements importants surviennent au sein du personnel qui supervise les données du projet, y compris un changement de chercheur principal?","guidance":"<p>Indiquez une stratégie de planification de la relève pour ces données dans l'éventualité où une ou plusieurs personnes responsables des données quittent le projet (p. ex. un étudiant aux cycles supérieurs qui quitte après l'obtention de son diplôme). Décrivez le processus à suivre dans l'éventualité où le chercheur principal quitte le projet. Dans certains cas, un cochercheur, le département ou la division qui supervise cette recherche en assumera la responsabilité. </p>"},{"id":145,"question_id":210,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:12 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:12 UTC","text":"De quelles ressources aurez-vous besoin pour mettre en œuvre votre plan de gestion des données? À combien évaluez-vous le coût total de la gestion des données?","guidance":"<p>Cette évaluation doit comprendre les coûts de gestion des données encourus au cours du projet ainsi que les coûts requis pour le soutien à plus long terme des données après la fin du projet. Les points à considérer dans la dernière catégorie de dépenses comprennent les coûts d'entretien  et de prestation d'un accès à long terme aux données. Certains organismes de financement indiquent de façon explicite le soutien qu'ils fourniront afin de respecter les coûts relatifs à la préparation des données à déposer. Cela peut comprendre les aspects techniques de la gestion de données, les exigences en matière de formation, le stockage et la sauvegarde des fichiers et le travail du personnel ne faisant pas partie du projet.</p>"},{"id":146,"question_id":211,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:12 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:12 UTC","text":"Si votre projet comprend des données sensibles, comment vous assurerez-vous qu'il est géré de manière sécuritaire et que les données sont accessibles uniquement aux membres approuvés du projet?","guidance":"<p>Examinez où et comment les données sensibles ayant une valeur à long terme reconnue doivent être rendues disponibles et à qui, de même que pendant combien de temps elles doivent  être archivées. Ces décisions doivent respecter les exigences du comité d'éthique de la recherche. Les méthodes utilisées pour partager les données dépendront d'un certain nombre de facteurs comme le type, la taille, la complexité et le degré de sensibilité des données. Décrivez les problèmes prévus dans le partage des données, ainsi que les causes et les mesures possibles pour les atténuer. Les problèmes peuvent comprendre, entre autres, la confidentialité, l'absence de consentement ou les préoccupations au sujet des droits de propriété intellectuelle. Dans certains cas, une période d'embargo peut être justifiée; ces cas peuvent être définis dans la politique sur les données de recherche d'un organisme de financement.</p><p>Réutilisé de : DCC. (2013). <a href=\"http://www.dcc.ac.uk/resources/data-management-plans\" target=\"_blank\">Checklist for a Data Management Plan (Liste de vérification pour un plan de gestion des données)</a>. v.4.0. Edinburgh: Digital Curation Centre</p><p>Des restrictions peuvent être imposées en limitant l'accès physique aux dispositifs de stockage, en enregistrant les données sur des ordinateurs qui ne possèdent pas d'accès au réseau externe (c.-à-d. accès à Internet), grâce à une protection par mot de passe, et en codant les fichiers. Les données sensibles ne doivent jamais être partagées par courriel ou au moyen de services de stockage en nuage comme Dropbox.</p>"},{"id":147,"question_id":212,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:12 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:12 UTC","text":"Le cas échéant, quelles stratégies adopterez-vous pour traiter les utilisations secondaires des données sensibles?","guidance":"<p>L'obtention du consentement approprié des participants de recherche constitue une étape importante pour assurer au comité d'éthique de la recherche que les données de recherche peuvent être partagées avec des chercheurs ne faisant pas partie de votre projet. La déclaration de consentement peut indiquer certaines conditions précisant l'utilisation des données par d'autres chercheurs. Par exemple, elle peut stipuler que les données seront uniquement partagées à des fins de recherche sans but lucratif ou que les données ne seront pas croisées avec des données personnelles provenant d'autres sources. </p><p>Pour en savoir plus sur la sécurité des données, consultez le site suivant : <a href=\"http://data-archive.ac.uk/create-manage/storage/security\" target=\"_blank\">UK Data Archive</a></p>.</p>"},{"id":148,"question_id":213,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:12 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-19 17:40:12 UTC","text":"Comment traiterez-vous les questions d'ordre juridique, éthique et de propriété intellectuelle?","guidance":"<p>Le respect des règlements et des lois sur la protection de la vie privée qui peuvent imposer des restrictions de contenu dans les données devrait être discuté avec le bureau de la recherche ou le responsable de la protection de la vie privée de votre établissement. Le comité d'éthique de la recherche est aussi essentiel dans ce processus.</p><p>Décrivez ici ce qui en est de la propriété des données, de l'octroi de licences et de la propriété intellectuelle. Les conditions énoncées pour la réutilisation des données doivent être clairement mentionnés et respecter les exigences juridiques et éthiques pertinentes, le cas échéant (p. ex. consentement du sujet, permissions, restrictions, etc.).</p>"},{"id":149,"question_id":259,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-12-03 17:17:51 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-01 21:41:42 UTC","text":"What file formats will your data be collected? Will these formats allow for data re-use, sharing and long-term access to the data?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Proprietary file formats requiring specialized software or hardware to use are not recommended, but may be necessary for certain data collection or analysis methods. Using open file formats or industry-standard formats (e.g. those widely used by a given community) is preferred whenever possible.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Read more about file formats: </span><a href=\"http://researchdata.library.ubc.ca/plan/format-your-data/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">UBC Library Research Data Website</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> or </span><a href=\"https://www.ukdataservice.ac.uk/manage-data/format/file-formats.aspx\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">UK Data Archive</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">. </span><strong><br /><br /></strong></p>"},{"id":150,"question_id":260,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-12-03 17:21:47 UTC","updated_at":"2020-11-23 18:59:24 UTC","text":"What conventions and procedures will you use to structure, name and version-control your files to help you and others better understand how your data are organized?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">It is important to keep track of different copies or versions of files, files held in different formats or locations, and information cross-referenced between files. &nbsp;This process is called &lsquo;version control&rsquo;. &nbsp;Logical file structures, informative naming conventions, and clear indications of file versions all contribute to better use of your data during and after your research project. &nbsp;These practices will help ensure that you and your research team are using the appropriate version of your data, and minimize confusion regarding copies on different computers and/or on different media.</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> &nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Read more about file naming and version control: </span><a href=\"http://researchdata.library.ubc.ca/plan/organize-your-data/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">UBC Library Research Data Website</span></a> <span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">or </span><a href=\"https://www.ukdataservice.ac.uk/manage-data/format/versioning.aspx\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">UK Data Archive</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.<br /></span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><br /></span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><a href=\"https://dataverse.scholarsportal.info/dataverse/ubc\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">UBC Dataverse</a>&nbsp;@Scholars Portal&nbsp;software can help with version control of your files.</span></p>"},{"id":151,"question_id":266,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-12-03 17:35:22 UTC","updated_at":"2015-12-03 17:35:22 UTC","text":"What documentation will be needed for the data to be read and interpreted correctly in the future?  ","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Typically, good documentation includes information about the study, data-level descriptions, and any other contextual information required to make the data usable by other researchers. &nbsp;Other elements you should document, as applicable, include: research methodology used, variable definitions, vocabularies, classification systems, units of measurement, assumptions made, format and file type of the data, software versions, a description of the data capture and collection methods, explanation of data coding and analysis performed (including syntax files), and details of who has worked on the project and performed each task, etc. More information about metadata is available on the UBC Library</span><a href=\"http://researchdata.library.ubc.ca/plan/document-describe-your-data/\" target=\"_blank\"> <span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Research Data Website</span> </a></p>"},{"id":152,"question_id":265,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-12-03 17:37:14 UTC","updated_at":"2015-12-03 17:37:14 UTC","text":"How will you make sure that documentation is created or captured consistently throughout your project?\r\n","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Consider how you will capture this information and where it will be recorded. It is best to start preparing data documentation and metadata procedures well in advance of data collection and analysis in order to avoid inaccuracies, inconsistencies, or loss of information in the capture and processing of data, and especially after the study has been completed. Creating documentation takes time, so consider whether anything you&rsquo;ve already created can be used (e.g. publications, websites, progress reports, etc.). If documentation is to be captured during the data collection or data processing phase, consult with members of the research team to assess procedures in the collection and capture of data, and indicate the individual roles and workflows when possible (e.g. data collectors code data and upload to database with headers, etc.).</span></p>"},{"id":153,"question_id":264,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-12-03 17:39:05 UTC","updated_at":"2019-04-05 17:45:54 UTC","text":"If you are using a metadata standard and/or tools to document and describe your data, please list here.\r\n","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">There are many general and domain-specific metadata standards. &nbsp;Dataset documentation should be provided in one of these standard, machine readable, openly-accessible formats to enable the effective exchange of information between users and systems. &nbsp;These standards are often based on language-independent data formats such as XML, RDF, and JSON. For assistance with choosing a metadata standard, please contact us at </span><a href=\"mailto:research.data@ubc.ca\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">research.data@ubc.ca</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">. <br /><a href=\"https://dataverse.scholarsportal.info/dataverse/ubc\" target=\"_blank\">UBC Dataverse</a>&nbsp;@Scholars Portal&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">repository uses a popular metadata standard from the </span><a href=\"http://www.ddialliance.org/\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">DDI </span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">&nbsp;(Data Documentation Initiative).&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Read more about metadata standards: </span><a href=\"http://www.dcc.ac.uk/resources/metadata-standards\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">UK Digital Curation Centre&rsquo;s Disciplinary Metadata. </span></a></p>"},{"id":154,"question_id":268,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-12-03 17:44:33 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-01 21:44:23 UTC","text":"How and where will your data be stored and backed up during your research project?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The risk of losing data due to human error, natural disasters, or other mishaps can be mitigated by following the 3-2-1 backup rule: </span></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Have at least three copies of your data.</span></li>\r\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Store the copies on two different media.</span></li>\r\n<li>Keep one backup copy offsite</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Storing data on flash drives, laptops, computers, or external hard drives without a regular backup procedure is not recommended, because they are subject to hardware failure, viruses, file corruption, theft, loss, and human error. Likewise, multiple copies of data stored in the same physical location does little to mitigate risk.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp; Using software which automatically backs up your data and keeps it synchronized with a master copy is recommended. Copies of data should ideally be stored in separate physical locations to mitigate physical risks, e.g. fire.<br /><br />Learn more about <a href=\"https://it.ubc.ca/sites/it.ubc.ca/files/UBC%20Online%20Storage%20Solutions%20-%20Features%20Comparison%20Chart.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">UBC data storage solutions</a> from UBC IT at from the UBC Library<a href=\"http://researchdata.library.ubc.ca/plan/store-and-back-up-your-data/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"> Research Data Website </a>.<br /><br />UBC Library also offers <a href=\"https://dataverse.scholarsportal.info/dataverse/ubc\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">UBC Dataverse</a>&nbsp;@Scholars Portal&nbsp;for managing and sharing datasets. For assistance with Dataverse, please contact <a href=\"mailto:research.data@ubc.ca\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">research.data@ubc.ca</a></p>"},{"id":155,"question_id":267,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-12-03 17:46:31 UTC","updated_at":"2015-12-03 17:46:31 UTC","text":"What are the anticipated storage requirements for your project, in terms of storage space (in megabytes, gigabytes, terabytes, etc.) and the length of time you will be storing it?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Storage-space estimates should take into account requirements for file versioning, backups, and growth over time. If your data will be changing frequently, provide an estimate of how much extra storage will be required to store multiple versions. If you are collecting data over a long period of time (e.g. several months or years), describe your plan for adding additional storage to accommodate data growth. If you plan to retain your data after the research project, describe how long-term storage will be achieved. </span></p>"},{"id":156,"question_id":280,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-12-03 17:48:38 UTC","updated_at":"2015-12-03 17:48:38 UTC","text":"How will the research team and other collaborators access, modify, and contribute data throughout the project?\r\n","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The security measures you choose to implement will depend on the sensitivity of the data being stored. Data can be protected by limiting physical access to hard drives and file servers on which it is stored, by storing data on computers that do not have external network access (i.e. access to the Internet), through password protection, and by encrypting data files.</span></p>\r\n<p><span>Sharing sensitive data via email and cloud storage services such as Dropbox is not recommended, since the security of these services cannot be trusted. Read more about security at the UBC Library</span><a href=\"http://researchdata.library.ubc.ca/plan/protect-your-data/\" target=\"_blank\"> <span>Research Data Website</span></a></p>"},{"id":157,"question_id":271,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-12-03 17:51:46 UTC","updated_at":"2019-04-05 17:49:38 UTC","text":"Where will you deposit your data for long-term preservation and access at the end of your research project?\r\n","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The issue of data retention should be considered early in the research lifecycle. &nbsp;Data-retention decisions can be driven by external policies (e.g. funding agencies, journal publishers), or by an understanding of the enduring value of a given set of data. &nbsp;The need to preserve data in the short-term (i.e. for peer-verification purposes) or long-term (for data of lasting value), will influence the choice of data repository or archive. &nbsp;A helpful analogy is to think of creating a &lsquo;living will&rsquo; for the data, that is, a plan describing how future researchers will have continued access to the data.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">If you need assistance locating a suitable data repository or archive, please contact </span><a href=\"mailto:research.data@ubc.ca\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">research.data@ubc.ca</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> or your </span><a href=\"http://directory.library.ubc.ca/subjectlibrarians/\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">subject librarian</span></a></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">UBC researchers can deposit datasets in <a href=\"https://dataverse.scholarsportal.info/dataverse/ubc\" target=\"_blank\">UBC Dataverse</a>&nbsp;@Scholars Portal, including ones with complex formats such as those produced by SPSS, R or SAS. For help, please contact </span><a href=\"mailto:research.data@ubc.ca\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">research.data@ubc.ca</span></a></p>"},{"id":158,"question_id":270,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-12-03 17:54:15 UTC","updated_at":"2015-12-03 17:54:15 UTC","text":"Indicate how you will ensure your data is preservation ready. Consider preservation-friendly file formats, ensuring file integrity, anonymization and de-identification, and inclusion of supporting documentation.\t\r\n","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Some data formats are optimal for long-term preservation of data. For example, non-proprietary file formats such as text (&lsquo;.txt&rsquo;) and comma-separated (&lsquo;.csv&rsquo;), are considered preservation-friendly. &nbsp;The UK Data Archive provides a useful </span><a href=\"http://data-archive.ac.uk/create-manage/format/formats-table\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">table of file formats</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> for various types of data. &nbsp;Keep in mind that files converted from one format to another may lose information (e.g. </span><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">converting from an uncompressed TIFF file to a compressed JPG file</span></em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">), so changes to file formats should be documented. &nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Identify&nbsp;steps required following project completion in order to ensure the data you are choosing to preserve or share is anonymous, error-free, and converted to recommended formats with a minimal risk of data loss.</span></p>"},{"id":159,"question_id":272,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-12-03 17:56:58 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-01 21:45:49 UTC","text":"What data will you be sharing and in what form? (e.g. raw, processed, analyzed, final).  ","guidance":"<p><strong>Raw data</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> are the data directly obtained from the instrument, simulation or survey.</span></p>\r\n<p><strong>Processed data </strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">result from some manipulation of the raw data in order to eliminate errors or outliers, to prepare the data for analysis, to derive new variables, or to de-identify the human participants</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>\r\n<p><strong>Analyzed data</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> are the results of qualitative, statistical, or mathematical analysis of the processed data. They can be presented as &nbsp;graphs, charts or statistical tables.</span></p>\r\n<p><strong>Final data</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> are processed data that have, if needed, been converted into a preservation-friendly format.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Consider which data may need to be shared in order to meet institutional or funding requirements, and which data may be restricted because of confidentiality/privacy/intellectual property considerations.</span></p>"},{"id":160,"question_id":273,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-12-03 17:58:18 UTC","updated_at":"2015-12-03 17:58:18 UTC","text":"If the way you store and share data during your research project differs from how you will preserve your data long-term, include a brief description of any resources needed to share your data (equipment, systems, expertise, etc.).\r\n","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">It&rsquo;s possible that the data repository you've selected provides long-term preservation but does not meet your needs in terms of short- or medium-term data sharing and access. For instance, you may need exploration and analysis tools that the long-term archive does not provide.&nbsp; In addition, the long-term archive may not provide flexible authenticated-access options. Also consider if the repository supports metadata standards commonly used by researchers in your field.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">In some instances,&nbsp;you may want to use another (or additional)&nbsp;repository or platform to share your dataset. Please contact </span><a href=\"mailto:research.data@ubc.ca\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">research.data@ubc.ca</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> or your </span><a href=\"http://directory.library.ubc.ca/subjectlibrarians/\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">subject librarian</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> to discuss options for data sharing.</span></p>"},{"id":161,"question_id":274,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-12-03 17:59:55 UTC","updated_at":"2015-12-03 17:59:55 UTC","text":"Have you considered what type of end-user license to include with your data?\r\n","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Licenses determine what uses can be made of your data. Funding agencies and/or data repositories may have end-user license requirements in place; if not, they may still be able to guide you in the development of a license. Once created, do include a copy of your end-user license with your Data Management Plan. &nbsp;Note that only the intellectual property rights holder(s) can issue a license, so it is crucial to clarify who owns those rights.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">There are several types of standard licenses available to researchers, such as the </span><a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/choose/\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Creative Commons licenses</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> and the </span><a href=\"http://opendatacommons.org/licenses/\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Open Data Commons licenses.</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> In fact, for most datasets it is easier to use a standard license rather than to devise a custom-made one. Note that even if you choose to make your data part of the public domain, it is preferable to make this explicit by using a license such as </span><a href=\"https://creativecommons.org/choose/zero/\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Creative Commons&rsquo; CC0</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Read more about data licensing: UBC Library </span><a href=\"http://researchdata.library.ubc.ca/share/license-your-data/\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Research Data Management Website</span></a></p>"},{"id":162,"question_id":275,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-12-03 18:01:36 UTC","updated_at":"2019-04-05 17:51:27 UTC","text":"What steps will be taken to help the research community know that your data exists?\r\n","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Where you share your data depends on the complexity and size of your data. Smaller, low-risk datasets can be shared via institutional or disciplinary repositories and project websites. Larger datasets or datasets with more stringent security requirements cannot be easily transferred over the Internet. Read more about sharing data at the UBC Library</span><a href=\"http://researchdata.library.ubc.ca/share/\" target=\"_blank\"> <span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Research Data Website</span></a></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Researchers at UBC can deposit datasets in&nbsp;<a href=\"https://dataverse.scholarsportal.info/dataverse/ubc\" target=\"_blank\">UBC Dataverse</a>&nbsp;@Scholars Portal&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">(and get a DOI) for complex data formats such as those produced by SPSS, R or SAS, or</span> <span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">even for basic data formats such as Excel. For large datasets, please contact </span><a href=\"mailto:research.data@ubc.ca\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">research.data@ubc.ca</span></a></p>"},{"id":163,"question_id":276,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-12-03 18:03:54 UTC","updated_at":"2015-12-03 18:03:54 UTC","text":"Identify who will be responsible for managing this project’s data during and after the project and the major data management tasks for which they will be responsible.\t","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Your data management plan has identified important data activities in your project. Identify who will be responsible -- individuals or organizations -- for carrying out these parts of your data management plan. This could also include the time frame associated with these staff responsibilities and any training needed to prepare staff for these duties.</span></p>"},{"id":164,"question_id":277,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-12-03 18:05:13 UTC","updated_at":"2015-12-03 18:05:13 UTC","text":"How will responsibilities for managing data activities be handled if substantive changes happen in the personnel overseeing the project's data, including a change of Principal Investigator?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Indicate a succession strategy for these data in the event that one or more people responsible for the data leaves (e.g. a Graduate student leaving after graduation). Describe the process to be followed in the event that the Principal Investigator leaves the project. In some instances, a co-investigator or the department or division overseeing this research will assume responsibility. </span></p>"},{"id":165,"question_id":278,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-12-03 18:06:19 UTC","updated_at":"2015-12-03 18:06:19 UTC","text":"What resources will you require to implement your data management plan? What do you estimate the overall cost for data management to be?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">This estimate should incorporate data management costs incurred during the project as well as those required for the longer-term support for the data after the project is finished. Items to consider in the latter category of expenses include the costs of curating and providing long-term access to the data. Some funding agencies state explicitly the support that they will provide to meet the </span><a href=\"http://www.data-archive.ac.uk/media/247429/costingtool.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">cost of preparing data for deposit</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">. This might include technical aspects of data management, training requirements, file storage &amp; backup, and contributions of non-project staff.</span></p>"},{"id":166,"question_id":281,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-12-03 18:09:27 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-01 21:46:47 UTC","text":"If your research project includes sensitive data, how will you ensure that it is securely managed and accessible only to approved members of the project?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Consider where, how, and to whom sensitive data with acknowledged long-term value should be made available, and how long it should be archived. These decisions should align with Research Ethics Board requirements. The methods used to share data will be dependent on a number of factors such as the type, size, complexity and degree of sensitivity of data. Outline problems anticipated in sharing data, along with causes and possible measures to mitigate these. Problems may include confidentiality, lack of consent agreements, or concerns about Intellectual Property Rights, among others. In some instances, an embargo period may be justified; these may be defined by a funding agency&rsquo;s policy on research data.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Sharing sensitive data via email and cloud storage services such as Dropbox is not recommended, since the security of these services cannot be trusted. Read more about security at the UBC Library</span><a href=\"http://researchdata.library.ubc.ca/plan/protect-your-data/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"> <span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Research Data Website</span></a></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Restrictions can be imposed by limiting physical access to storage devices, by placing data on computers that do not have external network access (i.e. access to the Internet), through password protection, and by </span><a href=\"https://it.ubc.ca/services/security/encryption-services\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">encrypting </span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">files. </span></p>"},{"id":167,"question_id":282,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-12-03 18:11:05 UTC","updated_at":"2015-12-03 18:11:05 UTC","text":"If applicable, what strategies will you undertake to address secondary uses of sensitive data?\r\n","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Obtaining the appropriate consent from research participants is an important step in assuring Research Ethics Boards that the data may be shared with researchers outside your project. The consent statement may identify certain conditions clarifying the uses of the data by other researchers. For example, it may stipulate that the data will only be shared for non-profit research purposes or that the data will not be linked with personally identified data from other sources. &nbsp;Read more about security at the UBC Library</span><a href=\"http://researchdata.library.ubc.ca/plan/protect-your-data/\" target=\"_blank\"> <span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Research Data Website </span></a></p>"},{"id":168,"question_id":283,"locale":"en","created_at":"2015-12-03 18:11:52 UTC","updated_at":"2015-12-03 18:11:52 UTC","text":"How will you manage legal, ethical, and intellectual property issues?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Compliance with privacy legislation and laws that may impose content restrictions in the data should be discussed with your institution&rsquo;s privacy officer or research services office. UBC </span><a href=\"http://ethics.research.ubc.ca/\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Research Ethics Boards</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> are central to the research process.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Include here a description concerning ownership, licensing, and intellectual property rights of the data. Terms of reuse must be clearly stated, in line with the relevant legal and ethical requirements where applicable (e.g., subject consent, permissions, restrictions, etc.).</span></p>"},{"id":169,"question_id":284,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-01-08 17:48:13 UTC","updated_at":"2016-01-08 17:48:13 UTC","text":"test question 1","guidance":""},{"id":170,"question_id":285,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-02-18 21:16:37 UTC","updated_at":"2016-02-18 21:16:37 UTC","text":"Question1?","guidance":""},{"id":171,"question_id":286,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-02-18 21:17:35 UTC","updated_at":"2016-02-18 21:18:39 UTC","text":"Question2?","guidance":""},{"id":172,"question_id":287,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-03-07 17:30:40 UTC","updated_at":"2016-03-07 17:30:40 UTC","text":"What type of data will you collect?","guidance":""},{"id":173,"question_id":288,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-03-07 17:33:12 UTC","updated_at":"2016-03-07 17:33:12 UTC","text":"Will you use a consent form?","guidance":"<p>Think of what type of data access/sharing you want to provide. This will impcat the wording of your consent form.</p>"},{"id":174,"question_id":289,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-06-03 16:39:39 UTC","updated_at":"2016-06-03 16:39:39 UTC","text":"Think about what kind of data your project will generate: list all types in point form","guidance":"<p>It's unlikely you will generate only one type of data. Log your data as you go to ensure you have contintuity.</p>"},{"id":175,"question_id":290,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-08-25 21:43:50 UTC","updated_at":"2016-08-25 21:43:50 UTC","text":"What types of data will you collect, create, link to, acquire, and/or record?","guidance":""},{"id":176,"question_id":291,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-08-25 21:45:01 UTC","updated_at":"2016-08-25 21:45:01 UTC","text":"What file formats will you use for your data? Keep in mind the need to allow for data re-use, sharing, and long-term access. ","guidance":""},{"id":177,"question_id":292,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-08-25 21:45:43 UTC","updated_at":"2016-08-25 21:45:43 UTC","text":"What conventions and procedures will you use to structure, name, and version-control your files to help you and others better understand how your data are organized?","guidance":""},{"id":178,"question_id":293,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-08-25 21:46:04 UTC","updated_at":"2016-08-25 21:46:04 UTC","text":"What would you and/or other researchers need to interpret the data? How will you create, manage, and update the documentation?","guidance":""},{"id":179,"question_id":294,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-08-25 21:46:23 UTC","updated_at":"2016-08-25 21:46:23 UTC","text":"Which metadata standard and/or tools, if any, will you use to document and describe your data?","guidance":""},{"id":180,"question_id":295,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-08-25 21:47:18 UTC","updated_at":"2016-08-25 21:47:18 UTC","text":"What are the anticipated storage requirements for your project, in terms of storage space (in megabytes, gigabytes, terabytes, etc.) and the length of time you will be storing it?","guidance":""},{"id":181,"question_id":296,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-08-25 21:48:06 UTC","updated_at":"2016-08-25 21:48:06 UTC","text":"How and where will your data be stored and backed up during your research project? ","guidance":""},{"id":182,"question_id":297,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-08-25 21:48:26 UTC","updated_at":"2016-08-25 21:48:26 UTC","text":"How will the research team and other collaborators access, modify, and contribute data throughout the project?","guidance":""},{"id":183,"question_id":298,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-08-25 21:49:01 UTC","updated_at":"2016-08-25 21:49:01 UTC","text":"What form of the data will you be sharing?","guidance":""},{"id":184,"question_id":299,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-08-25 21:49:25 UTC","updated_at":"2016-08-25 21:49:25 UTC","text":"What type of end-user license will you include with your data?","guidance":""},{"id":185,"question_id":300,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-08-25 21:49:43 UTC","updated_at":"2016-08-25 21:49:43 UTC","text":"How will you make it possible for the research community to find your data?","guidance":""},{"id":186,"question_id":301,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-08-25 21:50:18 UTC","updated_at":"2016-08-25 21:50:18 UTC","text":"Where will you deposit your data for long-term preservation and access (if appropriate) at the end of your research project?","guidance":""},{"id":187,"question_id":302,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-08-25 21:50:37 UTC","updated_at":"2016-08-25 21:50:37 UTC","text":"How will you ensure your data are preservation ready? ","guidance":""},{"id":188,"question_id":303,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-08-25 21:51:19 UTC","updated_at":"2016-08-25 21:51:19 UTC","text":"Who will be responsible for managing the data during and after the project?","guidance":""},{"id":189,"question_id":304,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-08-25 21:51:38 UTC","updated_at":"2016-08-25 21:51:38 UTC","text":"How will responsibilities for managing data activities be handled if substantive changes happen in the personnel overseeing the data management?","guidance":""},{"id":190,"question_id":305,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-08-25 21:51:56 UTC","updated_at":"2016-08-25 21:51:56 UTC","text":"What resources will you require to implement your data management plan? What is your estimate for the overall cost for data management?","guidance":""},{"id":191,"question_id":306,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-08-25 21:52:31 UTC","updated_at":"2016-08-25 21:52:31 UTC","text":"If your research project includes sensitive data, how will you ensure that it is securely managed and accessible only to approved members of the project?","guidance":""},{"id":192,"question_id":307,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-08-25 21:52:56 UTC","updated_at":"2016-08-25 21:52:56 UTC","text":"If applicable, what strategies will you undertake to address secondary uses of sensitive data?","guidance":""},{"id":193,"question_id":308,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-08-25 21:53:15 UTC","updated_at":"2016-08-25 21:53:15 UTC","text":"How will you manage legal, ethical, and intellectual property issues?","guidance":""},{"id":194,"question_id":309,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-09-23 22:20:48 UTC","updated_at":"2016-09-23 22:20:48 UTC","text":"Describe what types of data you anticipate the project will generate and/or collection. ","guidance":"<p>Describe the types of data that will be generated during this research project (eg. column delimited ASCII, NetCDF, GIF, JPEG, etc)</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Are formats open (do not need proprietary software to interpret)</li>\r\n<li>Describe the volume of data to be generated in MG, GB, TB</li>\r\n</ul>"},{"id":195,"question_id":310,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-09-23 22:23:52 UTC","updated_at":"2016-09-26 23:00:25 UTC","text":"How will the data be collected or created?","guidance":"<p>What conventions/procedures will you use to organize, name, and version-control your data files</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>List file naming conventions (e.g. cruise_year_instrument_data-type_version.txt, instrument_data-type_begindate_enddate)</li>\r\n<li>List file codes, labelling, and/or identifiers practice</li>\r\n<li>Develop protocols. These can include information about: Parameters, Flags &amp;&nbsp;Codes</li>\r\n<li>Procedures used to check and verify data (including remarks, controlled vocabulary, versioning control)</li>\r\n</ul>"},{"id":196,"question_id":311,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-09-26 23:18:33 UTC","updated_at":"2016-09-26 23:18:33 UTC","text":"Data Access, Sharing and Re-use: Who is the data author/data contact that is responsible for the data and documentation during the project?","guidance":"<p>How will the research team and other collaborators access, modify, and contribute data throughout the project? (e.g. CanWIN, FTP site). Who will organize distribution and update metadata/datasets?</p>"},{"id":197,"question_id":312,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-09-26 23:19:39 UTC","updated_at":"2016-09-26 23:19:39 UTC","text":"Data Access, Sharing and Re-use: Who is the data maintainer that is responsible for the data and documentation at completion of project. ","guidance":"<p>How will the research team and other collaborators access, modify, and contribute data throughout the project? (e.g. CanWIN, FTP site). Who will organize distribution and update metadata/datasets?</p>"},{"id":198,"question_id":313,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-09-26 23:21:29 UTC","updated_at":"2016-09-26 23:21:29 UTC","text":"Data Access, Sharing and Re-use: What is the data access policy?","guidance":"<p>How will the research team and other collaborators access, modify, and contribute data throughout the project? (e.g. CanWIN, ftp site). Who will organize distribution and update metadata/datasets?</p>"},{"id":199,"question_id":314,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-09-26 23:22:07 UTC","updated_at":"2016-09-26 23:22:07 UTC","text":"Are there user restrictions to data? Will data sharing be postponed / restricted e.g. embargo period. Dataset has privacy restrictions (has consent to disclose data has been obtained)?","guidance":""},{"id":200,"question_id":315,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-09-27 16:20:52 UTC","updated_at":"2016-09-27 18:15:07 UTC","text":"What documentation and metadata will accompany the data? (ex. Protocols, metadata file, controlled vocabulary)","guidance":"<p>Information from section 3 should be packaged as a protocol document and supplemental information &amp; &nbsp;should be stored in the same location as the data. Information may include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Data, Metadata, and minimum information standards that will be used;</li>\r\n<li>Protocol for data and record filing (digital folder, directory structures, physical filing systems etc.);</li>\r\n<li>The manner in which master version and/or copy of data will be identified; and</li>\r\n<li>Version control measures</li>\r\n</ul>"},{"id":201,"question_id":316,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-09-27 19:34:04 UTC","updated_at":"2016-09-27 19:34:04 UTC","text":"Time periods during which the data will be collected?","guidance":""},{"id":202,"question_id":317,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-09-27 19:36:30 UTC","updated_at":"2016-09-27 19:36:30 UTC","text":"Planned update frequency of dataset:","guidance":""},{"id":203,"question_id":318,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-09-27 19:44:05 UTC","updated_at":"2016-09-27 19:44:05 UTC","text":"Study site description:","guidance":"<p>Please provide the study site with either:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"https://www.nrcan.gc.ca/earth-sciences/geography/place-names/search/9170\" target=\"_blank\">Canadian Geographical Names Data Base Name</a>: Projection, with latitude and longtitude, or</li>\r\n<li>Bounding box coordinates (degrees)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>"},{"id":204,"question_id":319,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-09-27 19:48:48 UTC","updated_at":"2016-09-27 19:48:48 UTC","text":"Intellectual Property, Copyright and Ownership","guidance":"<p>Please find out more information about:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Open Government Licence - Canada:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://open.canada.ca/en/open-government-licence-canada\" target=\"_blank\">http://open.canada.ca/en/open-government-licence-canada</a></li>\r\n<li>Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International Licence: <a href=\"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/\" target=\"_blank\">https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/</a></li>\r\n</ul>"},{"id":205,"question_id":320,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-09-27 19:50:40 UTC","updated_at":"2016-09-27 19:50:40 UTC","text":"Ethics, Privacy, and Confidentiality Requirements","guidance":""},{"id":206,"question_id":321,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-09-27 19:52:41 UTC","updated_at":"2016-09-27 19:52:41 UTC","text":"Is there any privacy restriction in place? What safeguards are in place to prevent disclosure?","guidance":"<p>e.g.:&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Will data be anonymized, de-identified, encrypted?</li>\r\n<li>What are the confidentiality/FIPPA agreements?</li>\r\n</ul>"},{"id":207,"question_id":322,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-09-27 21:35:15 UTC","updated_at":"2016-09-27 21:35:15 UTC","text":"What are the storage plans for the digital data?","guidance":"<p>Describe the media type, location and amount of time you are storing your main (actively using) data and backup files for. Do you have sufficient storage or will you need to include charges for additional services? Who will be responsible for backup and recovery?How will the data be recovered in the event of an incident?</p>"},{"id":208,"question_id":323,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-09-27 21:36:35 UTC","updated_at":"2016-09-27 21:36:35 UTC","text":"Which data should be retained, shared, and/or archived?","guidance":""},{"id":209,"question_id":324,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-09-27 21:40:24 UTC","updated_at":"2016-09-27 21:40:24 UTC","text":"What resources will you require to delivery your plan?\r\n\r\n","guidance":""},{"id":210,"question_id":325,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-10-14 15:42:06 UTC","updated_at":"2016-10-14 15:42:06 UTC","text":"Question 1","guidance":"<p>test</p>"},{"id":211,"question_id":326,"locale":"en","created_at":"2016-10-14 15:42:50 UTC","updated_at":"2016-10-14 15:42:50 UTC","text":"File Format","guidance":""},{"id":212,"question_id":327,"locale":"en","created_at":"2017-06-15 12:38:42 UTC","updated_at":"2017-06-15 13:45:58 UTC","text":"What types of data will you collect, create, acquire and/or record?","guidance":"<p>Examples: numeric, images, audio, video, text, tabular data, modeling data, spatial data, instrumentation data.</p>"},{"id":213,"question_id":328,"locale":"en","created_at":"2017-06-15 12:39:29 UTC","updated_at":"2017-06-15 13:46:40 UTC","text":"What file formats will your data be collected in? Do these formats allow for data re-use, sharing and long-term access? E.g., are file formats proprietary or open source?","guidance":"<p>Proprietary file formats requiring specialized software or hardware to use are not recommended, but may be necessary for certain data collection or analysis methods. Using open file formats or industry-standard formats (e.g. those widely used by a given community) is preferred whenever possible.</p>\r\n<p>Read more about file formats: <a href=\"http://researchdata.library.ubc.ca/plan/format-your-data/\" target=\"_blank\">UBC Library</a> or <a href=\"http://data-archive.ac.uk/create-manage/format/formats\" target=\"_blank\">UK Data Archive</a>.</p>"},{"id":214,"question_id":329,"locale":"en","created_at":"2017-06-15 12:40:34 UTC","updated_at":"2017-06-15 13:47:47 UTC","text":"What are the anticipated storage requirements of your project?","guidance":"<p>Storage-space estimates should take into account requirements for file versioning, backups, and growth over time.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>If you are collecting data over a long period (e.g. several months or years), your data storage and backup strategy should accommodate data growth. Similarly, a long-term storage plan is necessary if you intend to retain your data after the research project.</p>"},{"id":215,"question_id":330,"locale":"en","created_at":"2017-06-15 12:44:47 UTC","updated_at":"2017-06-17 17:44:19 UTC","text":"How will data quality be assured and controlled? ","guidance":"<p>It is important to keep track of different copies or versions of files, files held in different formats or locations, and information cross-referenced between files. This process is called 'version control'.</p>\r\n<p>Logical file structures, informative naming conventions, and clear indications of file versions, all contribute to better use of your data during and after your research project. &nbsp;These practices will help ensure that you and your research team are using the appropriate version of your data, and minimize confusion regarding copies on different computers and/or on different media.</p>\r\n<p>Read more about file naming and version control: <a href=\"http://researchdata.library.ubc.ca/plan/organize-your-data/\" target=\"_blank\">UBC Library</a> or <a href=\"http://data-archive.ac.uk/create-manage/format/versions\" target=\"_blank\">UK Data Archive</a>.</p>"},{"id":216,"question_id":331,"locale":"en","created_at":"2017-06-15 12:48:24 UTC","updated_at":"2017-06-15 14:07:22 UTC","text":"What provisions are in place for data security including data recovery, backup, secure storage, transfer of data, and version control? ","guidance":"<p>The risk of losing data due to human error, natural disasters, or other mishaps can be mitigated by following the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://dataabinitio.com/?p=501\" target=\"_blank\">3-2-1 backup rule</a>:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Have at least three copies of your data.</li>\r\n<li>Store the copies on two different media.</li>\r\n<li>Keep one backup copy offsite</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Data may be stored using optical or magnetic media, which can be removable (e.g. DVD and USB drives), fixed (e.g. desktop or laptop hard drives), or networked (e.g. networked drives or cloud-based servers). Each storage method has benefits and drawbacks that should be considered when determining the most appropriate solution.</p>\r\n<p>Further information on storage and backup practices is available from the <a href=\"https://www.sheffield.ac.uk/library/rdm/storage\" target=\"_blank\">University of Sheffield Library</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.data-archive.ac.uk/create-manage/storage/back-up\" target=\"_blank\">UK Data Archive</a>.</p>"},{"id":217,"question_id":332,"locale":"en","created_at":"2017-06-15 12:50:38 UTC","updated_at":"2017-06-15 13:55:57 UTC","text":"What elements in the metadata and other supporting documentation are needed to ensure that data is read and interpreted correctly in the future? ","guidance":"<p>Typically, good documentation includes information about the study, data-level descriptions, and any other contextual information required to make the data usable by other researchers. &nbsp;Other elements you should document, as applicable, include: research methodology used, variable definitions, vocabularies, classification systems, units of measurement, assumptions made, format and file type of the data, a description of the data capture and collection methods, explanation of data coding and analysis performed (including syntax files), and details of who has worked on the project and performed each task, etc.</p>"},{"id":218,"question_id":333,"locale":"en","created_at":"2017-06-15 12:52:12 UTC","updated_at":"2017-06-15 13:58:10 UTC","text":"What specific standard(s) are being used for metadata? ","guidance":"<p>There are many general and domain-specific metadata standards. &nbsp;Dataset documentation should be provided in one of these standard, machine readable, openly-accessible formats to enable the effective exchange of information between users and systems. &nbsp;These standards are often based on language-independent data formats such as XML, RDF, and JSON. There are many metadata standards based on these formats, including discipline-specific standards.</p>\r\n<p>Read more about metadata standards: <a href=\"http://dcc.ac.uk/resources/metadata-standards\" target=\"_blank\">UK Digital Curation Centre's Disciplinary Metadata</a>.&nbsp;</p>"},{"id":220,"question_id":335,"locale":"en","created_at":"2017-06-15 13:05:07 UTC","updated_at":"2017-06-17 17:47:51 UTC","text":"What data will you be publicly sharing and in what form?","guidance":"<p><strong>Raw data</strong> are the data directly obtained from the instrument, simulation or survey.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Processed data</strong> result from some manipulation of the raw data in order to eliminate errors or outliers, to prepare the data for analysis, to derive new variables, or to de-identify the human participants.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Analyzed data</strong> are the the results of qualitative, statistical, or mathematical analysis of the processed data. They can be presented as graphs, charts or statistical tables.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Final data</strong> are processed data that have, if needed, been converted into a preservation-friendly format.</p>\r\n<p>Consider which data may need to be shared in order to meet institutional or funding requirements, and which data may be restricted because of confidentiality/privacy/intellectual property considerations.</p>"},{"id":221,"question_id":336,"locale":"en","created_at":"2017-06-15 13:06:14 UTC","updated_at":"2017-06-15 13:06:14 UTC","text":"When will the data be made available for re-use? If an embargo period is requested specify why and how long this will apply, bearing in mind that data should be made available as soon as possible.","guidance":""},{"id":222,"question_id":337,"locale":"en","created_at":"2017-06-15 13:07:21 UTC","updated_at":"2017-06-17 17:48:48 UTC","text":"What type of end-user license to include with your data? E.g., CC-BY ","guidance":"<p>Licenses determine what uses can be made of your data. Funding agencies and/or data repositories may have end-user license requirements in place; if not, they may still be able to guide you in the development of a license. Once created, please consider including a copy of your end-user license with your Data Management Plan. Note that only the intellectual property rights holder(s) can issue a license, so it is crucial to clarify who owns those rights.</p>\r\n<p>There are several types of standard licenses available to researchers, such as the <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/choose/\" target=\"_blank\">Creative Commons licenses</a> and the <a href=\"http://opendatacommons.org/licenses/\" target=\"_blank\">Open Data Commons licenses</a>. In fact, for most datasets it is easier to use a standard license rather than to devise a custom-made one. Note that even if you choose to make your data part of the public domain, it is preferable to make this explicit by using a license such as Creative Commons' CC0.</p>\r\n<p>Read more about data licensing: <a href=\"http://www.dcc.ac.uk/resources/how-guides/license-research-data\" target=\"_blank\">UK Digital Curation Centre</a>.</p>"},{"id":223,"question_id":338,"locale":"en","created_at":"2017-06-15 13:08:58 UTC","updated_at":"2017-06-17 17:46:35 UTC","text":"Where will you deposit data for long term preservation and access? E.g., Dryad, Zenodo, Figshare, University-specific repository, etc.","guidance":"<p>The issue of data retention should be considered early in the research lifecycle. Data-retention decisions can be driven by external policies (e.g. funding agencies, journal publishers), or by an understanding of the enduring value of a given set of data. The need to preserve data in the short-term (i.e. for peer-verification purposes) or long-term (for data of lasting value), will influence the choice of data repository or archive. A helpful analogy is to think of creating a 'living will' for the data, that is, a plan describing how future researchers will have continued access to the data.</p>\r\n<p>If you need assistance locating a suitable data repository or archive, please contact your Library.</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.re3data.org/\" target=\"_blank\">re3data.org</a> is a directory of potential open data repositories. Verify whether or not the data repository will provide a statement agreeing to the terms of deposit outlined in your Data Management Plan.</p>"},{"id":224,"question_id":339,"locale":"en","created_at":"2017-06-15 13:09:42 UTC","updated_at":"2017-06-17 17:48:27 UTC","text":"What steps will be taken to help the research community know that your data exists? E.g., what metadata catalog will you use to increase discoverability?","guidance":"<p>Possibilities include: data registries, repositories, indexes, word-of-mouth, publications.</p>\r\n<p>How will the data be accessed (Web service, ftp, etc.)? If possible, choose a repository that will assign a persistent identifier (such as a DOI) to your dataset. This will ensure a stable access to the dataset and make it retrievable by various discovery tools.</p>\r\n<p>One of the best ways to refer other researchers to your deposited datasets is to cite them the same way you cite other types of publications (articles, books, proceedings). The Digital Curation Centre provides a detailed <a href=\"http://www.dcc.ac.uk/resources/how-guides/cite-datasets\" target=\"_blank\">guide</a> on data citation.Note that some data repositories also create links from datasets to their associated papers, thus increasing the visibility of the publications.</p>\r\n<p>Contact your Library for assistance in making your dataset visible and easily accessible.</p>\r\n<p>Reused from NIH. (2009). <a href=\"https://grants.nih.gov/grants/sharing_key_elements_data_sharing_plan.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Key Elements to Consider in Preparing a Data Sharing Plan Under NIH Extramural Support</a>. National Institutes of Health.</p>"},{"id":225,"question_id":340,"locale":"en","created_at":"2017-06-15 13:12:46 UTC","updated_at":"2017-06-15 13:18:53 UTC","text":"Will approval from your University’s research ethics board be required? If you are unsure, please review <a href=\"http://www.pre.ethics.gc.ca/pdf/eng/tcps2-2014/TCPS_2_FINAL_Web.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"> the Tri-Council Policy Statement on Ethical Conduct for Research Involving Humans</a>.","guidance":""},{"id":226,"question_id":341,"locale":"en","created_at":"2017-06-15 13:20:12 UTC","updated_at":"2017-06-17 17:54:01 UTC","text":"Are there any legal, ethical or intellectual property issues with sharing data? Please describe","guidance":""},{"id":227,"question_id":342,"locale":"en","created_at":"2017-06-15 13:20:42 UTC","updated_at":"2017-06-15 13:20:42 UTC","text":"If applicable, how will sensitive data be securely managed and accessible only to project members? Does ethics alone address this, or are non-disclosure agreements required?","guidance":""},{"id":228,"question_id":343,"locale":"en","created_at":"2017-06-15 13:21:03 UTC","updated_at":"2017-06-15 13:21:03 UTC","text":"If applicable, what steps need to be taken before publicly releasing data? E.g., anonymization/de-personalization of data.","guidance":""},{"id":229,"question_id":344,"locale":"en","created_at":"2017-06-15 13:25:54 UTC","updated_at":"2017-06-17 17:51:09 UTC","text":"Identify who will be responsible for managing the project’s data and the major data management tasks for which they will be responsible.","guidance":"<p>Your data management plan has identified important data activities in your project. Identify who will be responsible -- individuals or organizations -- for carrying out these parts of your data management plan. This could also include the timeframe associated with these staff responsibilities and any training needed to prepare staff for these duties.</p>\r\n<p>Indicate a succession strategy for these data in the event that one or more people responsible for the data leaves&nbsp;(e.g. a graduate student leaving after graduation). Describe the process to be followed in the event that the Principal Investigator leaves the project. In some instances, a co-investigator or the department or division overseeing this research will assume responsibility.</p>"},{"id":230,"question_id":345,"locale":"en","created_at":"2017-06-15 13:27:35 UTC","updated_at":"2017-06-17 17:51:33 UTC","text":"What resources will you require to implement your data management plan? (E.g., training, storage space, and large data transfer capabilities). If applicable, try to estimate the costs associated with data management and build these into your project’s budget.","guidance":"<p>This estimate should incorporate data management costs incurred during the project as well as those required for the longer-term support for the data after the project is finished. Items to consider in the latter category of expenses include the costs of curating and providing long-term access to the data. Some funding agencies state&nbsp;explicitly the support that they will provide to meet the cost of preparing data for deposit. This might include technical aspects of data management, training requirements, file storage &amp; backup, and contributions of non-project staff.</p>"},{"id":231,"question_id":346,"locale":"en","created_at":"2017-06-18 22:20:12 UTC","updated_at":"2017-06-18 22:20:12 UTC","text":"What standards or applications (e.g., notebooks) are you using to help to structure, name and version control your files? ","guidance":""},{"id":232,"question_id":347,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2017-11-01 20:16:41 UTC","updated_at":"2017-11-01 20:16:41 UTC","text":"De quelle couleur sont vos données?","guidance":"<p>Mettre la couleur pr&eacute;dominante des donn&eacute;es</p>"},{"id":233,"question_id":348,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2017-11-01 20:23:10 UTC","updated_at":"2017-11-01 20:23:10 UTC","text":"Qui est responsable d'attribuer une couleur aux données","guidance":"<p>mettre ici qui est le boss!</p>"},{"id":234,"question_id":349,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-23 22:13:14 UTC","updated_at":"2018-02-23 22:13:14 UTC","text":"What types of data will you collect, create, acquire and/or record?","guidance":"<p>Examples: images, audio, video, text, tabular data, modeling data, spatial data, instrumentation data</p>"},{"id":235,"question_id":350,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-23 22:32:45 UTC","updated_at":"2018-02-23 22:32:45 UTC","text":"What file formats will your data be collected in? Will these formats allow for data re-use, sharing and long-term access to the data?","guidance":"<p>During your research you may utilize or generate data in proprietary file formats from specialized software or hardware. Identify what, if any, those may be. Consider how that data may be exported or saved in open or industry-standard file formats. It is best practice to use open/industry-standard formats whenever possible.</p>\r\n<p>Read more about file formats: <a href=\"https://www.ukdataservice.ac.uk/manage-data/format/file-formats\" target=\"_blank\">UK Data Service</a></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>"},{"id":236,"question_id":351,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-23 22:51:17 UTC","updated_at":"2018-02-23 22:51:17 UTC","text":"What conventions and procedures will you use to structure, name and version-control your files to help you and others better understand how your data are organized?","guidance":"<p>Version control is to keep track of different copies or versions of files, files held in different formats or locations, and information cross-referenced between files. Establishing a logical file structure, using an informative naming convention and clear indications of file versions, contributes to more efficient, timely access to data at all points in your research project. It also minimizes error and confusion regarding copies held on different devices/equipment or media. The use of <a href=\"http://libguides.lib.umanitoba.ca/facultyhelp/dataverse\" target=\"_blank\">UM Library's Dataverse</a> can help with version control of your files.</p>\r\n<p>Read more about <a href=\"https://www.ukdataservice.ac.uk/manage-data/format/organising\" target=\"_blank\">file naming</a> and <a href=\"https://www.ukdataservice.ac.uk/manage-data/format/versioning\" target=\"_blank\">version control</a>.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>"},{"id":237,"question_id":352,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-26 17:38:08 UTC","updated_at":"2018-02-26 17:38:08 UTC","text":"What documentation will be needed for the data to be read and interpreted correctly in the future?","guidance":"<p>Best practice for describing data include: information about the study; data-level descriptions; and any other contextual information required to make the data usable by other researchers. Other elements that should be included, as applicable:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>research methodology used</li>\r\n<li>variable definitions</li>\r\n<li>vocabularies</li>\r\n<li>classification systems</li>\r\n<li>units of measurement</li>\r\n<li>assumptions made</li>\r\n<li>format and file type of the data</li>\r\n<li>software versions</li>\r\n<li>description of data capture and collection methods</li>\r\n<li>explanation of data coding and analysis performed (including syntax files)</li>\r\n<li>details/list of who has worked on the project, role/task assignment, contact information, etc.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Read about metadata: <a href=\"https://www.ukdataservice.ac.uk/manage-data/document\" target=\"_blank\">Document Your Data - UK Data Service</a></p>"},{"id":238,"question_id":353,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-26 17:58:20 UTC","updated_at":"2018-02-26 17:59:26 UTC","text":"How will you make sure that documentation is created or captured consistently throughout your project?","guidance":"<p>Consider how and where you will record this information. The preparation of data documentation and metadata is best done well in advance of data collection and analysis. Guidance for data quality may be determined, in part, on the policies of the REB submission criteria, the grant funder and/or the regulatory body governing your area of research. Efforts on data quality considerations will avoid inaccuracies, inconsistencies, or data loss in the capture and processing of data, especially after the study has been completed. Creating documentation takes time, so consider whether anything you have already created can be used, for example publications, websites, progress reports etc. Consult your research team as part of your documentation considerations to assess procedures in the data collection process; record roles, workflows when possible.</p>"},{"id":239,"question_id":354,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-26 18:46:41 UTC","updated_at":"2018-02-26 18:48:17 UTC","text":"If you are using a metadata standard and/or tools to document and describe your data, please list here.","guidance":"<p>There are many general and discipline-specific metadata standards. Dataset documentation should be provided in one of these standard, machine readable, openly-accessible formats to enable the ease of information exchange between users, systems. These standards are often based on language-dependent data formats like XML, RDF, and JSON.</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"https://dataverse.lib.umanitoba.ca/dataverse/um\" target=\"_blank\">University of Manitoba Dataverse</a> data repository offers several metadata schema optons for various disciplines including Astronomy &amp; Astrophysics, and Life Sciences.</p>\r\n<p>Read more about metadata standards: <a href=\"http://www.dcc.ac.uk/resources/metadata-standards\" target=\"_blank\">Disciplinary Metadata - DCC</a></p>"},{"id":240,"question_id":355,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-26 21:46:18 UTC","updated_at":"2018-02-26 21:46:18 UTC","text":"How and where will your data be stored and backed up during your research project?","guidance":"<p>Risk management data loss mitigation is summarized with the 3-2-1 rule:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Have at least 3 copies of your data</li>\r\n<li>Store the copies on 2 different media</li>\r\n<li>Keep 1 backup copy offsite</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Storing data on flash drives, laptops, computers, or external hard drives without a regular backup procedure is not recommended. These methods are subject to hardware failure, viruses, file corruption, theft, loss or human error. Similarly, multiple copies kept in the same physical location does little to migate risk.</p>\r\n<p>Using software which automatically backs up your data and keeps it synchronized with a master copy is recommended.</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"https://dataverse.lib.umanitoba.ca/dataverse/um\" target=\"_blank\">University of Manitoba Dataverse</a> for managing and sharing datasets.</p>"},{"id":241,"question_id":356,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-26 22:04:35 UTC","updated_at":"2018-02-26 22:04:35 UTC","text":"What are the anticipated storage requirements for your project, in terms of storage space (in megabytes, gigabytes, terabytes etc.) and the length of time you will be storing it?","guidance":"<p>In estimating your storage-space requirements, there are several factors you should take account:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>consider file versioning, backups, and growth over time</li>\r\n<li>if data changes frequently, extra storage will be needed to store multiple versions</li>\r\n<li>if data collection occurs over a long period of time (months, years), include a plan for adding additional storage to accommodate data growth</li>\r\n<li>if data retention is required long after the project, describe the nature of that storage</li>\r\n</ul>"},{"id":242,"question_id":357,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-26 22:26:53 UTC","updated_at":"2018-02-26 22:26:53 UTC","text":"How will the research team and other collaborators access, modify, and contribute data  throughout the project?","guidance":"<p>The nature of the data and/or regulatory bodies for your research will determine the security measures you need to implement. Data can be protected by limiting physial access to hard drives and file servers on which it is stored, by storing data on computers that do not have external network access (i.e. access to the Internet), through password protection and data encryption.</p>\r\n<p>Sharing sensitive data via email and third-party cloud storage services such as Dropbox is not recommended, since the security of these services cannot be trusted.&nbsp;</p>"},{"id":243,"question_id":358,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-27 16:04:44 UTC","updated_at":"2018-02-27 16:18:48 UTC","text":"Name of project or sub-project and project number (if applicable).","guidance":"<p>Example: Oil Sands Monitoring</p>"},{"id":245,"question_id":360,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-27 16:05:55 UTC","updated_at":"2018-02-27 16:19:50 UTC","text":"Please provide an outline description of the research project and the intended products of the research.","guidance":"<p>Scope of project or sub-project. Describe the types of data and products that will be generated in the research, such as images of astronomical objects, spectra, data tables, time series, theoretical formalisms, computational strategies, software, and curriculum materials.</p>"},{"id":246,"question_id":361,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-27 16:06:16 UTC","updated_at":"2018-02-27 16:06:16 UTC","text":"Please provide details of the project timelines.","guidance":"<p>Duration in Years; Months</p>"},{"id":247,"question_id":362,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-27 16:06:47 UTC","updated_at":"2018-02-27 16:06:47 UTC","text":"Principal Investigator(s)","guidance":"<p>Who is the project lead?</p>"},{"id":248,"question_id":363,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-27 16:07:10 UTC","updated_at":"2018-03-05 14:54:03 UTC","text":"Identify collaborating Agencies/Organizations.","guidance":"<p>List any collaborating agencies and organizations, if applicable.</p>"},{"id":249,"question_id":364,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-27 16:07:27 UTC","updated_at":"2018-02-27 16:07:27 UTC","text":"Identify who will be responsible for managing this project’s data during and after the project.\t","guidance":"<p>Your data management plan identifies important data activities in your project. Identify who will be responsible -- this could be the project lead or other individual(s) and service units -- for carrying out the responsibilities association with data acquisition, processing, quality control, documentation, and preservation.</p>"},{"id":250,"question_id":365,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-27 16:10:32 UTC","updated_at":"2018-02-27 16:20:25 UTC","text":"If applicable, identify the data sharing agreement, Memorandum of Understanding, or Memorandum of Agreement that defines roles and responsibilities for data collection and/or sharing.","guidance":"<p>Before research is initiated, it is important to determine who owns the data. Collaborators entering into arrangements, particularly regarding publication, should be aware of expectations, obligations, rights and roles of all parties with respect to data release. A clear understanding of how the data will be distributed and shared should be established in the early stages of collaboration.&nbsp;</p>"},{"id":251,"question_id":366,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-27 16:21:56 UTC","updated_at":"2018-02-27 16:21:56 UTC","text":"What types of data will you collect, create, acquire and/or record?","guidance":"<p>Examples: Images, audio, video, text, tabular data, modeling data, spatial data, instrumentation data</p>"},{"id":252,"question_id":367,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-27 16:22:22 UTC","updated_at":"2018-02-27 16:22:22 UTC","text":"Will this project use existing data? ","guidance":"<p>Considering answering the following questions: Where did the existing dataset(s) from from? Is that data published or publicly available? Will the project use contracted datasets (data from external sources?)&nbsp; If yes, will you be able to store a local copy of the contracted data?</p>"},{"id":253,"question_id":368,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-27 16:23:31 UTC","updated_at":"2018-02-27 16:31:36 UTC","text":"What systems are to be used to collect the data? What file formats will your electronic data be collected in? Will these formats allow for data re-use, sharing and long-term access to the data?","guidance":"<p>Proprietary file formats requiring specialized software or hardware to use are not recommended, but may be necessary for certain data collection or analysis methods. Using open file formats or industry-standard formats (e.g. those widely used by a given community) is preferred whenever possible.</p>\r\n<p>Read more about file formats: <a href=\"http://open.canada.ca/en/open-data-principles\" target=\"_blank\">Open Data 101&nbsp;</a>&amp;<br /><a href=\"https://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/services/government-information-resources/guidelines/Pages/guidelines-file-formats-transferring-information-resources-enduring-value.aspx#v\" target=\"_blank\">Guidelines on File Formats for Transferring Information Resources of Enduring Value</a>.</p>"},{"id":254,"question_id":369,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-27 16:24:32 UTC","updated_at":"2018-02-27 16:24:32 UTC","text":"Will the project need to buy any new software, licenses, or IT equipment to collect or process the data?","guidance":"<p>Any IT related items not listed on the \"Restricted IT Product List\" can be procured directly by the CBI, to a maximum of up to $500.<br />Items on the \"Restricted IT Product List\" must be ordered through the IT Hardware and Software order Application page. <br />If you have questions about your IT requirements, contact the Client Service Centre.</p>"},{"id":255,"question_id":370,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-27 16:25:20 UTC","updated_at":"2018-02-27 16:25:20 UTC","text":"How is the data in the research project categorized?","guidance":"<p>For example, data may be categorized as follows: Confidentiality is Protected B</p>"},{"id":256,"question_id":371,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-27 16:25:40 UTC","updated_at":"2018-02-27 16:25:40 UTC","text":"Has a statement of sensivity (SOS) been conducted? Is the research project responsible for controlled Goods data and/or ITAR Data?","guidance":"<p>NRC is mandated to maintain positive control of its sensitive inventory, including all controlled goods and ITAR goods and technologies, including data, held by NRC.&nbsp; The controlled Goods/ITAR default sensitivity level is Protected B, unless related to a classified project.</p>"},{"id":257,"question_id":372,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-27 16:26:31 UTC","updated_at":"2018-02-27 16:26:31 UTC","text":"Are you collecting personal information?","guidance":"<p>A Privacy Impact Assessment (PIA) document is required when collecting personal information.&nbsp; The Privacy Impact Assessment (PIA) is the component of risk management that focuses on ensuring compliance with the legal and policy requirements related to the administration of the Privacy Act. The PIA process also confirms that personal information under the control of NRC is complete, accurate and up to date, and reported in the annual Info Source publication.</p>\r\n<p>See also <a href=\"https://intranet.nrc-cnrc.gc.ca/en/policies-procedures/32303\" target=\"_blank\">Guidelines on Privacy Breaches </a>on Myzone.</p>"},{"id":258,"question_id":373,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-27 16:30:21 UTC","updated_at":"2018-02-27 16:30:21 UTC","text":"Is ethics approval required and has it been obtained?","guidance":"<p>NRC employees are committed to pursuing excellence in research by meeting the highest standards for ethics and integrity.</p>\r\n<p>All research involving human participants with which NRC is involved should comply with the NRC Policy for <a href=\"http://www.nrc-cnrc.gc.ca/eng/about/ethics_integrity/policy_human_subjects.html\" target=\"_blank\">research involving human participants </a>and, as required by the Policy, shall be carried out with the approval of <a href=\"http://www.nrc-cnrc.gc.ca/eng/about/ethics_integrity/research_ethics_board.html\" target=\"_blank\">NRC&rsquo;s Research Ethics Board</a>.</p>\r\n<p>For more information, consult the <a href=\"http://www.nrc-cnrc.gc.ca/eng/about/ethics_integrity/human_subjects.html\" target=\"_blank\">Research involving human participants </a>webpage.</p>\r\n<p>NRC is committed to high ethical standards in research involving animals. This commitment is based on the understanding that using animals in research is acceptable only if results can reasonably be expected to contribute to the understanding of fundamental biological principles, or develop knowledge that benefits humans or animals.</p>\r\n<p>To maintain its high standards, NRC has created local Animal Care Committees (ACCs) to review and approve research protocols in each portfolio, branch or program which conducts <a href=\"https://www.nrc-cnrc.gc.ca/eng/about/ethics_integrity/animals.html\" target=\"_blank\">research involving animals</a>.</p>"},{"id":259,"question_id":374,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-27 16:34:25 UTC","updated_at":"2018-02-27 16:34:25 UTC","text":"What conventions and procedures will you use to structure, name and version-control your files to help you and others better understand how your data are organized?  ","guidance":"<p>It is important to keep track of different copies or versions of files, files held in different formats or locations, and information cross-referenced between files.&nbsp; This process is called &lsquo;version control&rsquo;.&nbsp; Logical file structures, informative naming conventions, and clear indications of file versions all contribute to better use of your data during and after your research project.&nbsp; These practices will help ensure that you and your research team are using the appropriate version of your data, and minimize confusion regarding copies on different computers and/or on different media.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Read more about file naming and version control: <a href=\"https://intranet.nrc-cnrc.gc.ca/en/policies-procedures/35888\" target=\"_blank\">Using naming conventions to organize your information</a>.&nbsp;<a href=\"https://intranet.nrc-cnrc.gc.ca/en/policies-procedures/31340\" target=\"_blank\">Organizing your information resources</a>.</p>"},{"id":260,"question_id":375,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-27 16:34:55 UTC","updated_at":"2018-02-27 16:34:55 UTC","text":"How will the data (derived, raw and unpublished data files) be documented for future usefulness?","guidance":"<p>Will the raw data be accompagnied by supporting documents (i.e. fieldbooks), standardized logs, and/or standardize operating procedures. Typically, good documentation includes information about the project, data-level descriptions, and any other contextual information required to make the data usable by other researchers. Consider how you will capture this information and where it will be recorded. It is best to start preparing data documentation and metadata procedures well in advance of data collection and analysis in order to avoid inaccuracies, inconsistencies, or loss of information in the capture and processing of data, and especially after the project has been completed (e.g. data collectors code data and upload to database with headers, etc.).</p>"},{"id":261,"question_id":376,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-27 16:35:29 UTC","updated_at":"2018-02-27 16:35:29 UTC","text":"If you are using a metadata standard and/or tools to document and describe your data, please list here.","guidance":"<p>Quality metadata are essential for making research data findable, and for the systems that use or mine the data. Standards are diverse and vary across disciplines, but metadata generally state who created the data and when, and include information on how the data were created, their quality, accuracy and precision, as well as other features necessary to enable understanding and reuse. <br />These standards are often based on language-independent data formats such as XML, RDF, and JSON.&nbsp; (e.g. ISO 15836-1:2017, the Dublin Core metadata element set establishes 15 core metadata elements for cross-domain resource description).</p>"},{"id":262,"question_id":377,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-27 16:59:31 UTC","updated_at":"2018-02-27 16:59:31 UTC","text":"How and where will your data be stored and backed up during your research project (e.g. laboratory server, HPC site, Cloud services, Specialized Research Equipment (SRE))?","guidance":"<p>Storing data on flash drives, laptops, computers, or external hard drives without a regular backup procedure is not recommended, because they are subject to hardware failure, viruses, file corruption, theft, loss, and human error. <br />Using software which automatically backs up your data and keeps it synchronized with a master copy is recommended.</p>\r\n<p>See more about <a href=\"https://intranet.nrc-cnrc.gc.ca/en/policies-procedures/35854\" target=\"_blank\">where to store your information </a>on MyZone.</p>"},{"id":263,"question_id":378,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-27 17:00:24 UTC","updated_at":"2018-02-27 17:00:24 UTC","text":"If applicable, where are hardcopy notebooks and physical samples going to be physically stored?","guidance":""},{"id":264,"question_id":379,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-27 17:01:22 UTC","updated_at":"2018-02-27 17:01:22 UTC","text":"If your data is not on a network server, how often will backups be performed?","guidance":"<p>Who will be responsible for backups and how long are they going to be kept?</p>"},{"id":265,"question_id":380,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-27 17:02:25 UTC","updated_at":"2018-02-27 17:02:25 UTC","text":"What are the anticipated storage requirements for your project, in terms of storage space (in megabytes, gigabytes, terabytes, etc.) and the length of time you will be storing it?","guidance":"<p>Storage-space estimates should take into account requirements for file versioning, backups, and growth over time. If your data will be changing frequently, provide an estimate of how much extra storage will be required to store multiple versions. If you are collecting data over a long period of time (e.g. several months or years), describe your plan for adding additional storage to accommodate data growth. If you plan to retain your data after the research project, describe how long-term storage will be achieved.</p>\r\n<p>Contact <a href=\"mailto:NRC.ClientServiceCentre-Centredeservicesalaclientele.CNRC@nrc-cnrc.gc.ca\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"color: #0066cc;\">Client Service Centre</span></a>&nbsp;for more information about storage solutions.</p>"},{"id":266,"question_id":381,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-27 17:09:40 UTC","updated_at":"2018-03-05 16:48:24 UTC","text":"If applicable, how will you ensure that sensitive data is stored securely and only accessible to the research team and other collaborators throughout the project?","guidance":"<p>All NRC employees are responsible for protecting sensitive NRC information (personal data, commercially confidential information, intellectual property, classified information, etc.) in accordance with the requirements of the NRC Information Security Guide.&nbsp; The security measures implemented will depend on the sensitivity of the data being stored. Data can be protected by limiting physical access to hard drives and file servers on which it is stored, by storing data on computers that do not have external network access (i.e. access to the Internet), through password protection, and by encrypting data files.</p>\r\n<p>For more information, see the <a href=\"https://intranet.nrc-cnrc.gc.ca/en/policies-procedures/37949\" target=\"_blank\">Information security guide on</a> MyZone.&nbsp;</p>"},{"id":267,"question_id":382,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-27 17:10:29 UTC","updated_at":"2018-02-27 17:10:29 UTC","text":"Indicate how you will ensure your data is preservation ready. Consider preservation-friendly file formats, ensuring file integrity, anonymization and de-identification, and inclusion of supporting documentation.\t","guidance":"<p>Identify steps required following project completion in order to ensure the data you are choosing to preserve or share is anonymous, error-free, and converted to recommended formats with a minimal risk of data loss.</p>"},{"id":268,"question_id":383,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-27 17:11:07 UTC","updated_at":"2018-02-27 17:11:07 UTC","text":"Where will you deposit your data for long-term preservation and access at the end of your research project?","guidance":"<p>&nbsp;The need to preserve data in the short-term (i.e. for peer-verification purposes) or long-term (for data of lasting value), will influence the choice of data repository or archive.&nbsp;&nbsp; NRC researchers can deposit datasets in NRC's Digital Repository, for more information please contact IM-GI@nrc-cnrc.gc.ca.</p>"},{"id":269,"question_id":384,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-27 17:18:38 UTC","updated_at":"2018-02-27 17:33:46 UTC","text":"Where will you deposit your data for long-term preservation and access at the end of your research project?","guidance":"<p>Data retention, like data storage, should be considered early in the research lifecycle. Data-retention decisions can be dictated by external policies (e.g. funding agencies, journal publishers), or by an understanding of the enduring value of a given set of data. Whether you need to preserve data in the short-term (i.e. for peer-verification) or long-term will influence the choice of data repository or archive.&nbsp;In summary, a data retention plan describes how future researchers can have continued access to your data.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;UM researchers can deposit datasets in <a href=\"https://dataverse.lib.umanitoba.ca/dataverse/um\" target=\"_blank\">University of Manitoba's Dataverse</a>.</p>"},{"id":270,"question_id":385,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-27 17:52:38 UTC","updated_at":"2018-02-27 17:52:38 UTC","text":"What data will you be sharing and in what form? (e.g. raw, processed, analyzed, final).  ","guidance":"<p>Consider which data may need to be shared in order to meet partner or policy requirements, and which data may be restricted because of confidentiality/privacy issue.&nbsp;</p>"},{"id":271,"question_id":386,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-27 17:54:49 UTC","updated_at":"2018-02-27 17:54:49 UTC","text":"How will you ensure your data is preservation ready? Factors in this consideration include open file formats, file integrity, anonymization and de-identification, and inclusion of supporting documentation.","guidance":"<p>Preservation-friendly formats are those that are open (non-proprietary), and/or internationally recognized. For example, text (.txt) and comma-separated (.csv) are considered preservation-friendly. Consult this <a href=\"https://www.ukdataservice.ac.uk/manage-data/format/recommended-formats\" target=\"_blank\">table of file formats&nbsp;</a>&nbsp;by the UK Data Service for data type options. Remember that file conversion (one file type to another) may result is data loss (e.g. moving from an uncompressed TIFF image file to a compressed JPG file). Record this changes in file formats and its implications.</p>\r\n<p>As part of your post-project data preservation and access plan, discuss proceedures for anonymization/de-identification, data quality, and file conversion to recommended file formats, minimizing the risk of data loss.</p>"},{"id":272,"question_id":387,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-27 17:55:03 UTC","updated_at":"2018-02-27 17:55:03 UTC","text":"How will you be sharing your data? (e.g. a specialized data archive, project website, informal/on-request sharing etc). ","guidance":"<p>KITS is responsible for establishing NRC information and data release criteria, in partnership with business leads across the organization. As an employee of NRC, when you create, edit, receive or plan to send any data, document, record or information to a colleague, client or other recipient, you must ensure that you securely transmit and store that information. Please include a brief description of any resources needed to share your data (e.g. equipment, systems)<br />For more information, see <a href=\"https://intranet.nrc-cnrc.gc.ca/en/policies-procedures/32182\" target=\"_blank\">Sharing information guidelines </a>on MyZone.</p>"},{"id":273,"question_id":388,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-27 17:56:14 UTC","updated_at":"2018-02-27 17:56:14 UTC","text":"Please describe whether there will be any restrictions placed on your data when they are made available and who may access them. If data are not openly available, describe the process for gaining access, if applicable","guidance":"<p>&ldquo;Open&rdquo; principles are applied where appropriate and to the greatest extent possible.&nbsp; To facilitate knowledge-sharing and re-use of information assets within the NRC organization, business units should only restrict access to their information where there are risks associated with internal sharing.&nbsp; In accordance with Government of Canada open government/open science requirements, NRC applies release criteria to identify information and data sets that can be made publicly available for access and re-use.&nbsp; Where there are restrictions on the use of the data, the reasons for these restrictions must be explained in the metadata. Information must describe how to gain controlled access to the data if possible (e.g., contact information, access terms, access agreement templates, data request forms, etc.)</p>"},{"id":274,"question_id":389,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-27 17:58:54 UTC","updated_at":"2018-02-27 17:58:54 UTC","text":"What type of end-user license will you include with your data, if applicable? Please include a copy of this license with your Data Management Plan. ","guidance":"<p>&nbsp;In accordance with Government of Canada open government/open science requirements, NRC applies release criteria to identify information and data sets that can be made publicly available for access and re-use.&nbsp; Where there are restrictions on the use of the data, employees should endeavour to use standard agreements wherever possible.</p>"},{"id":276,"question_id":391,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-27 18:40:14 UTC","updated_at":"2018-02-27 18:40:14 UTC","text":"What data will you be sharing/providing access to and in what form? (e.g. raw, processed, analyzed, final)","guidance":"<p>In considering which data may be shared/made accessible to meet institutional or funding requirements, remember there are levels of access that can be granted per data item. For example, one dataset could be completely open and accessible to everyone; another one could be 'locked' and only available upon request. Reasons for those&nbsp;'locked' data items should be documented (i.e. restricted access due to confidentiality/privacy/intellectual property concerns).</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Raw data</strong> is data directly obtained by the instrument, simulation, survery</li>\r\n<li><strong>Processed data</strong> is data resulting from some manipulation of the raw data to remove errors or outliers, prepare the data for analysis, derive new variables, or to de-identify human subjects</li>\r\n<li><strong>Analyzed data</strong> is data resulting from qualitative, statistical or mathematical analysis of the processed data (e.g. graphs, charts, tables)</li>\r\n<li><strong>Final data</strong> is processed data that have, if needed, been converted into a preservation-friendly format</li>\r\n</ul>"},{"id":277,"question_id":392,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-27 19:42:33 UTC","updated_at":"2018-02-27 19:42:33 UTC","text":"If the way you store and access data during your research project (i.e. active storage) differs from how you will preserve your data long-term, describe any resources needed to share/provide access your data (equipment, systems, expertise etc.)","guidance":"<p>The storage you are using during the short- to medium-term phase of your research may not be suitable for your long-term preservation needs or vice versa. For example, during the active phase of your project, you may need exploration and analysis tools, or access graularity that is not provided with an long-term archive. Perhaps&nbsp;you wish to deposit your data in an additional repository tangential to your disciplne to improve your data's audience reach. Whatever your data sharing/access needs, contact your <a href=\"http://libguides.lib.umanitoba.ca/staff/bysubject\" target=\"_blank\">subject librarian</a> for options for data sharing/access.</p>"},{"id":278,"question_id":393,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-27 21:00:15 UTC","updated_at":"2018-02-27 21:00:15 UTC","text":"Have you considered what type of end-user license to include with your data?","guidance":"<p>End-user licenses determine what uses can be made of your data. Funding agencies and/or data repositories may have license requirements; if not, they may still be able to guide you in the development of a license. It is not necessary to include a copy of the end-user license in your Data Management Plan; however, only intellectual property rights' holder(s) can issue a license, so you MUST clarify who owns those rights and should document that ownership.</p>\r\n<p>There are several types of standard licenses available to researchers, including <a href=\"https://creativecommons.org/choose/\" target=\"_blank\">Creative Commons licenses</a>, and <a href=\"https://opendatacommons.org/\" target=\"_blank\">Open Data Commons</a> licenses. For most datasets it is easier to use a standard license; it may not be necessary to design a custom license. It is recommended that if you choose to make your data part of the public domain, you should stipulate user-rights of that data via a license such as <a href=\"https://creativecommons.org/share-your-work/public-domain/cc0/\" target=\"_blank\">Creative Commons' CC0</a>.</p>\r\n<p>Related Information: <a href=\"http://umanitoba.ca/admin/governance/governing_documents/community/235.html\" target=\"_blank\">UM's Intellectual Property Policy</a></p>"},{"id":279,"question_id":394,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-27 21:43:47 UTC","updated_at":"2018-02-27 21:43:47 UTC","text":"What steps will you take to disseminate and/or assist the discovery of your research?","guidance":"<p>The type, complexity and size of the data determines where/how you can share your data. Smaller, low-risk datasets or manuscripts can be shared via institutional or disciplinary repositories and project websites. Larger datasets or datasets with more stringent security requirements cannot be easily transferred over the internet.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>UM researchers can deposit datasets in <a href=\"https://dataverse.lib.umanitoba.ca/dataverse/um\" target=\"_blank\">University of Manitoba Dataverse</a>&nbsp;(and get a DOI) for complex data formats such as those produced by SPSS, R, or SAS or even for basic data formats such as Excel.&nbsp;</p>"},{"id":280,"question_id":395,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-27 22:32:47 UTC","updated_at":"2018-02-27 22:32:47 UTC","text":"Identify who will be responsible for managing the research data during and after the project and the major data management tasks for which they will be responsible.","guidance":"<p>Your data managment plan&nbsp;(DMP) has identified important data activities in your research. List all the individuals or organizations for carrying out these parts of your DMP; for each, include the time frame associated and the responsibilities and training needed to perform these responsibilities.</p>"},{"id":281,"question_id":396,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-27 22:43:27 UTC","updated_at":"2018-02-27 22:43:27 UTC","text":"How will responsibilities for managing data activities be handled if substantive changes happen in the personnel overseeing the research data, including a change in Principle Investigator?","guidance":"<p>Describe a succession strategy for the research data in the event that one or more people with data responsibilities is unavailable or unable for a long period of time, or vacates their position (e.g. a graduate student leaves upon graduation). This succession strategy should include the process to be followed in the case&nbsp;that it is the&nbsp;Principle Investigator who is&nbsp;unavailable or unable for&nbsp;a long period of time, or vacates their position. For example, a co-investigator or the department/division of the research will assume responsibility.</p>"},{"id":282,"question_id":397,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-28 16:26:15 UTC","updated_at":"2018-02-28 16:29:33 UTC","text":"What resources will you require to implement your data management plan? What do you estimate the overall cost for data management to be?","guidance":"<p>Cost projections here should include those during the project as well as after the research is completed (i.e. include data preservation equipment/service costs, data curation).&nbsp;Consult your funding agency policy: some explicitly state what cost they will support to meet the <a href=\"https://www.ukdataservice.ac.uk/manage-data/plan/costing\" target=\"_blank\">costs of preparing data for deposit</a>. These costs&nbsp;could include technical aspects of data management; training requirements; file storage and backup; and contributions of external personnel and consultant support.</p>\r\n<p>See Also: <a href=\"http://www.nserc-crsng.gc.ca/Professors-Professeurs/FinancialAdminGuide-GuideAdminFinancier/index_eng.asp\" target=\"_blank\">Tri-Agency Financial Administration Guide</a></p>"},{"id":283,"question_id":398,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-28 18:09:18 UTC","updated_at":"2018-02-28 18:09:18 UTC","text":"If your research project includes sensitive data, how will you ensure that is securely managed and accessible only to approved members of the project?","guidance":"<p>Identify the sensitive data in your research with known long-term value and consider where, how and to whom is should be made available and how long it should be archived. The stipulations from your Research Ethics Board should align with your answers here.&nbsp;Factors such as type, size and complexity and degree of sensitivity of data will determine the method chosen to share data. List the issues/challenges of sharing your data together with causes and possible measures to mitigate this issues. Such issues may include confidentiality, lack of consent agreements, or concens about intellectual property rights, for example. Limitation or restriction to access the data over a period of time, or embargo, may provide a solution in certain situations; embargo as an option and its duration may be defined by a funding agency's policy on research data.</p>\r\n<p>Cloud file sharing options for active storage such as Dropbox, Google Drive or iCloud is not recommended as security of these services cannot be guaranteed.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"https://www.ukdataservice.ac.uk/manage-data/store/security\" target=\"_blank\">Data security</a> for active data storage measures could include, not limited to, physical access to storage devices; by placing data on computers that do not have external network access (i.e. access to the internet);&nbsp;password protection; <a href=\"https://www.ukdataservice.ac.uk/manage-data/store/encryption\" target=\"_blank\">data&nbsp;encryption</a>.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>"},{"id":284,"question_id":399,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-28 18:22:10 UTC","updated_at":"2018-02-28 18:26:49 UTC","text":"If applicable, what strategies will you undertake to address secondary uses of sensitive data?","guidance":"<p>For human subject data, obtaining the appropriate consent is a key step in assuring research ethics boards that the data will be used according to ethical standards and policies. The consent statement must reflect not only the&nbsp;expected&nbsp;use of the data but anticipate the necessary sharing or access to some form of that data beyond the research project. The statement may identify certain conditions clarifying the uses of the data by other researchers or applications. For example, it may stipulate that the data will only be shared for non-profit research purposes; the data will not be linked with personally identified data from other sources.&nbsp;</p>"},{"id":285,"question_id":400,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-02-28 18:53:41 UTC","updated_at":"2018-02-28 18:53:41 UTC","text":"How will you manage legal, ethical, and intellectual property issues?","guidance":"<p>Describe ownership, licensing, and intellectual property rights of the data. Terms of reuse must be clearly stated, in line with the relevant legal and ethical requirements where applicable (e.g. human subject consent, permissions, restrictions etc.).</p>\r\n<p>Direct your questions or concerns about compliance with privacy legislation and laws and the content restrictions in the data that may be imposed to the <a href=\"http://umanitoba.ca/research/orec/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">Office of Research Ethics and Compliance</a>.&nbsp;</p>"},{"id":286,"question_id":401,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-03-05 14:11:21 UTC","updated_at":"2018-03-05 14:11:21 UTC","text":"How will the research team and other collaborators access, modify, and contribute data throughout the project?","guidance":""},{"id":287,"question_id":402,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-03-05 14:13:47 UTC","updated_at":"2018-03-05 14:13:47 UTC","text":"What resources will you require to implement your data management plan? ","guidance":"<p>&nbsp;What do you estimate the overall cost for data management to be?</p>"},{"id":288,"question_id":403,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-06-12 14:22:33 UTC","updated_at":"2019-01-28 13:35:55 UTC","text":"What types of data will you collect, create, link to, acquire and/or record as part of this project?","guidance":"<p>Example of data types: numeric, images, audio, video, text, tabular data, modeling data, spatial data, instrumentation data. (see <a href=\"https://dictionary.casrai.org/Data\" target=\"_blank\">CASRAI</a> definition of data)</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"color: #3e3c3c; font-family: 'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; background-color: #ffffff; text-decoration-style: initial; text-decoration-color: initial; display: inline !important; float: none;\">&nbsp;</span></p>"},{"id":289,"question_id":404,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-06-12 14:25:15 UTC","updated_at":"2018-06-12 14:48:30 UTC","text":"Where will you deposit your data for long-term preservation and access at the end of your research project?","guidance":"<p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 10px; font-size: 14px; font-family: 'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; color: #3e3c3c; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration-style: initial; text-decoration-color: initial;\">The issue of data retention should be considered early in the research lifecycle. Data-retention decisions can be driven by external policies (e.g. funding agencies, journal publishers), or by an understanding of the enduring value of a given set of data. The need to preserve data in the short-term (i.e. for peer-verification purposes) or long-term (for data of lasting value), will influence the choice of data repository or archive. A helpful analogy is to think of creating a 'living will' for the data, that is, a plan describing how future researchers will have continued access to the data.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 10px; font-size: 14px; font-family: 'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; color: #3e3c3c; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration-style: initial; text-decoration-color: initial;\">If you need assistance locating a suitable data repository or archive, please contact your Library.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 10px; font-size: 14px; font-family: 'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; color: #3e3c3c; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration-style: initial; text-decoration-color: initial;\"><a href=\"http://www.re3data.org/\" target=\"_blank\">re3data.org</a>&nbsp;is a directory of potential open data repositories. Verify whether or not the data repository will provide a statement agreeing to the terms of deposit outlined in your Data Management Plan.</p>"},{"id":290,"question_id":405,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-06-12 14:25:30 UTC","updated_at":"2018-06-12 14:49:32 UTC","text":"Indicate how you will ensure your data is preservation ready. Consider preservation-friendly file formats, ensuring file integrity, anonymization and de-identification, inclusion of supporting documentation.","guidance":"<p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 10px; font-size: 14px; font-family: 'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; color: #3e3c3c; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration-style: initial; text-decoration-color: initial;\">Some data formats are optimal for long-term preservation of data. For example, non-proprietary file formats, such as text ('.txt') and comma-separated ('.csv'), are considered preservation-friendly. The UK Data Archive provides a useful table of file formats for various types of data. Keep in mind that preservation-friendly files converted from one format to another may lose information (e.g. converting from an uncompressed TIFF file to a compressed JPG file), so changes to file formats should be documented.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 10px; font-size: 14px; font-family: 'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; color: #3e3c3c; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration-style: initial; text-decoration-color: initial;\">Identify steps required following project completion in order to ensure the data you are choosing to preserve or share is anonymous, error-free, and converted to recommended formats with a minimal risk of data loss.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 10px; font-size: 14px; font-family: 'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; color: #3e3c3c; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration-style: initial; text-decoration-color: initial;\">Read more about anonymization:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://researchdata.library.ubc.ca/plan/format-your-data/\" target=\"_blank\">UBC Library</a>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<a href=\"http://data-archive.ac.uk/create-manage/consent-ethics/anonymisation\" target=\"_blank\">UK Data Archive</a>.</p>"},{"id":292,"question_id":407,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-06-12 14:26:42 UTC","updated_at":"2018-06-12 14:50:12 UTC","text":"What data will you be sharing and in what form? (e.g. raw, processed, analyzed, final).","guidance":"<p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 10px; font-size: 14px; font-family: 'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; color: #3e3c3c; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration-style: initial; text-decoration-color: initial;\"><strong style=\"margin: 0px;\">Raw data</strong>&nbsp;are the data directly obtained from the instrument, simulation or survey.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 10px; font-size: 14px; font-family: 'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; color: #3e3c3c; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration-style: initial; text-decoration-color: initial;\"><strong style=\"margin: 0px;\">Processed data</strong>&nbsp;result from some manipulation of the raw data in order to eliminate errors or outliers, to prepare the data for analysis, to derive new variables, or to de-identify the human participants.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 10px; font-size: 14px; font-family: 'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; color: #3e3c3c; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration-style: initial; text-decoration-color: initial;\"><strong style=\"margin: 0px;\">Analyzed data</strong>&nbsp;are the the results of qualitative, statistical, or mathematical analysis of the processed data. They can be presented as graphs, charts or statistical tables.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 10px; font-size: 14px; font-family: 'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; color: #3e3c3c; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration-style: initial; text-decoration-color: initial;\"><strong style=\"margin: 0px;\">Final data</strong>&nbsp;are processed data that have, if needed, been converted into a preservation-friendly format.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 10px; font-size: 14px; font-family: 'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; color: #3e3c3c; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration-style: initial; text-decoration-color: initial;\">Consider which data may need to be shared in order to meet institutional or funding requirements, and which data may be restricted because of confidentiality/privacy/intellectual property considerations.</p>"},{"id":293,"question_id":408,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-06-12 14:26:52 UTC","updated_at":"2018-06-12 14:50:56 UTC","text":"What steps will be taken to help the research community know that your data exists?","guidance":"<p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 10px; font-size: 14px; font-family: 'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; color: #3e3c3c; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration-style: initial; text-decoration-color: initial;\">Possibilities include: data registries, repositories, indexes, word-of-mouth, publications.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 10px; font-size: 14px; font-family: 'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; color: #3e3c3c; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration-style: initial; text-decoration-color: initial;\">How will the data be accessed (Web service, ftp, etc.)? If possible, choose a repository that will assign a persistent identifier (such as a DOI) to your dataset. This will ensure a stable access to the dataset and make it retrievable by various discovery tools.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 10px; font-size: 14px; font-family: 'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; color: #3e3c3c; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration-style: initial; text-decoration-color: initial;\">One of the best ways to refer other researchers to your deposited datasets is to cite them the same way you cite other types of publications (articles, books, proceedings). The Digital Curation Centre provides a detailed&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.dcc.ac.uk/resources/how-guides/cite-datasets\" target=\"_blank\">guide</a>&nbsp;on data citation.Note that some data repositories also create links from datasets to their associated papers, thus increasing the visibility of the publications.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 10px; font-size: 14px; font-family: 'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; color: #3e3c3c; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration-style: initial; text-decoration-color: initial;\">Contact your Library for assistance in making your dataset visible and easily accessible.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 10px; font-size: 14px; font-family: 'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; color: #3e3c3c; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration-style: initial; text-decoration-color: initial;\">Reused from NIH. (2009).&nbsp;<a href=\"https://grants.nih.gov/grants/sharing_key_elements_data_sharing_plan.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Key Elements to Consider in Preparing a Data Sharing Plan Under NIH Extramural Support</a>. National Institutes of Health.</p>"},{"id":295,"question_id":410,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-06-13 15:05:04 UTC","updated_at":"2018-06-13 15:05:04 UTC","text":"Outline any restrictions on data sharing due to the need to protect proprietary or patentable data or sensitive data.","guidance":""},{"id":296,"question_id":411,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-06-13 15:05:20 UTC","updated_at":"2018-06-13 15:05:33 UTC","text":"Outline any legal or ethical constraints on data release (obligations from funders, etc.)","guidance":""},{"id":297,"question_id":412,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-06-13 15:09:52 UTC","updated_at":"2018-06-13 15:09:52 UTC","text":"Outline measures you will undertake to ensure data is handled and maintained safely and securely throughout the research project.","guidance":""},{"id":298,"question_id":413,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2018-07-31 19:44:56 UTC","updated_at":"2018-07-31 20:16:28 UTC","text":"Quels types de données allez-vous recueillir, créer, lier, acquérir ou enregistrer?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Pour plus d&rsquo;information sur la gestion des donn&eacute;es de recherche (GDR) en g&eacute;n&eacute;ral, consultez le </span><a href=\"http://guides.bib.umontreal.ca/disciplines/500-Gestion-des-donnees-de-recherche?tab=2299\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">guide sur la GDR des Biblioth&egrave;ques de l&rsquo;Universit&eacute; de Montr&eacute;al</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">N&rsquo;h&eacute;sitez pas &agrave; contacter un biblioth&eacute;caire &agrave; </span><a href=\"mailto:gdr@bib.umontreal.ca\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">gdr@bib.umontreal.ca</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>"},{"id":299,"question_id":414,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2018-07-31 19:45:31 UTC","updated_at":"2018-07-31 20:19:23 UTC","text":"Dans quels formats de fichier vos données seront-elles recueillies? Ces formats permettront-ils la réutilisation des données, le partage et l'accès à long terme aux données?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Des informations sur </span><strong>le format des fichiers</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> se trouvent dans le </span><a href=\"http://guides.bib.umontreal.ca/disciplines/500-Gestion-des-donnees-de-recherche?tab=2301\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">guide sur la GDR</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>"},{"id":300,"question_id":415,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2018-07-31 19:45:47 UTC","updated_at":"2018-07-31 19:45:47 UTC","text":"Quelles conventions et procédures utiliserez-vous pour structurer et nommer vos fichiers et en contrôler les versions afin de vous aider, ainsi que les utilisateurs potentiels, à mieux comprendre la façon dont vos données sont organisées?","guidance":""},{"id":301,"question_id":416,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2018-07-31 19:47:47 UTC","updated_at":"2018-07-31 19:47:47 UTC","text":"Quels documents seront nécessaires pour que les données soient lues et interprétées correctement dans le futur?","guidance":""},{"id":302,"question_id":417,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2018-07-31 19:48:12 UTC","updated_at":"2018-07-31 19:48:12 UTC","text":"Comment vous assurerez-vous de documenter le projet de façon systématique tout au long du processus?","guidance":""},{"id":303,"question_id":418,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2018-07-31 19:48:46 UTC","updated_at":"2018-07-31 19:48:46 UTC","text":"Si vous utilisez une norme de métadonnées ou des outils pour documenter et décrire vos données, veuillez les indiquer ici.","guidance":""},{"id":304,"question_id":419,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2018-07-31 19:49:22 UTC","updated_at":"2018-07-31 19:49:22 UTC","text":"Quels sont les besoins de stockage anticipés pour votre projet en matière d'espace (en mégaoctets, gigaoctets, téraoctets, etc.) et de durée de stockage?","guidance":""},{"id":305,"question_id":420,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2018-07-31 19:49:45 UTC","updated_at":"2018-07-31 19:49:45 UTC","text":"Comment vos données seront-elles stockées et sauvegardées pendant votre projet de recherche et à quel endroit le seront-elles?","guidance":""},{"id":306,"question_id":421,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2018-07-31 19:50:08 UTC","updated_at":"2018-07-31 19:59:57 UTC","text":"Comment l'équipe de recherche et d'autres collaborateurs pourront-ils accéder aux données, modifier celles-ci ou en ajouter de nouvelles tout au long du projet?","guidance":""},{"id":307,"question_id":422,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2018-07-31 20:02:21 UTC","updated_at":"2018-07-31 20:02:21 UTC","text":"Où déposerez-vous vos données en vue de l'accès et de la préservation à long terme à la fin de votre projet de recherche?","guidance":""},{"id":308,"question_id":423,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2018-07-31 20:02:48 UTC","updated_at":"2018-07-31 20:02:48 UTC","text":"Indiquez comment vous assurerez que vos données sont prêtes pour la conservation. À prendre en considération: formats de fichier appropriés pour la conservation mais qui préservent l'intégrité des données; anonymisation et dépersonnalisation des fichiers, y compris les fichiers de documentation. ","guidance":""},{"id":309,"question_id":424,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2018-07-31 20:03:27 UTC","updated_at":"2018-07-31 20:03:27 UTC","text":"Quelles données partagerez-vous et sous quelle forme? (p. ex. données brutes, traitées, analysées, définitives)","guidance":""},{"id":310,"question_id":425,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2018-07-31 20:03:58 UTC","updated_at":"2018-07-31 20:03:58 UTC","text":"Avez-vous examiné quel type de licence d'utilisation inclure avec vos données?","guidance":""},{"id":311,"question_id":426,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2018-07-31 20:04:19 UTC","updated_at":"2018-07-31 20:04:19 UTC","text":"Quelles mesures seront prises pour faire connaître l'existence de vos données au milieu de la recherche?","guidance":""},{"id":312,"question_id":427,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2018-07-31 20:05:02 UTC","updated_at":"2018-07-31 20:05:02 UTC","text":"Identifiez qui sera responsable de la gestion des données de ce projet pendant et après le projet ainsi que les principales tâches associées à ces responsabilités.","guidance":""},{"id":313,"question_id":428,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2018-07-31 20:05:32 UTC","updated_at":"2018-07-31 20:05:32 UTC","text":"De quelle façon les responsabilités relatives à la gestion des données seront-elles gérées si des changements importants surviennent au sein du personnel qui supervise les données du projet, y compris un changement de chercheur principal?","guidance":""},{"id":314,"question_id":429,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2018-07-31 20:05:52 UTC","updated_at":"2018-07-31 20:05:52 UTC","text":"De quelles ressources aurez-vous besoin pour mettre en œuvre votre plan de gestion des données? À combien évaluez-vous le coût total de la gestion des données?","guidance":""},{"id":315,"question_id":430,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2018-07-31 20:06:35 UTC","updated_at":"2018-07-31 20:06:35 UTC","text":"Si votre projet comprend des données sensibles, comment vous assurerez-vous qu'il est géré de manière sécuritaire et que les données sont accessibles uniquement aux membres approuvés du projet?","guidance":""},{"id":316,"question_id":431,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2018-07-31 20:06:56 UTC","updated_at":"2018-07-31 20:06:56 UTC","text":"Le cas échéant, quelles stratégies adopterez-vous pour traiter les utilisations secondaires des données sensibles?","guidance":""},{"id":317,"question_id":432,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2018-07-31 20:07:17 UTC","updated_at":"2018-07-31 20:07:17 UTC","text":"Comment traiterez-vous les questions d'ordre juridique, éthique et de propriété intellectuelle?","guidance":""},{"id":318,"question_id":473,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2018-08-01 15:01:23 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-01 15:01:23 UTC","text":"Quels types de données allez-vous recueillir, créer, lier, acquérir ou enregistrer?","guidance":"<table>\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Pour plus d&rsquo;information sur la gestion des donn&eacute;es de recherche (GDR) en g&eacute;n&eacute;ral, consultez le </span><a href=\"http://guides.bib.umontreal.ca/disciplines/500-Gestion-des-donnees-de-recherche?tab=2299\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">guide sur la GDR des Biblioth&egrave;ques de l&rsquo;Universit&eacute; de Montr&eacute;al</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">N&rsquo;h&eacute;sitez pas &agrave; contacter un biblioth&eacute;caire &agrave; </span><a href=\"mailto:gdr@bib.umontreal.ca\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">gdr@bib.umontreal.ca</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>"},{"id":319,"question_id":474,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2018-08-01 15:01:56 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-01 15:01:56 UTC","text":"Dans quels formats de fichier vos données seront-elles recueillies? Ces formats permettront-ils la réutilisation des données, le partage et l'accès à long terme aux données?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Des informations sur </span><strong>le format des fichiers</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> se trouvent dans le </span><a href=\"http://guides.bib.umontreal.ca/disciplines/500-Gestion-des-donnees-de-recherche?tab=2301\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">guide sur la GDR</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>"},{"id":320,"question_id":475,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2018-08-01 15:02:29 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-01 15:02:29 UTC","text":"Quelles conventions et procédures utiliserez-vous pour structurer et nommer vos fichiers et en contrôler les versions afin de vous aider, ainsi que les utilisateurs potentiels, à mieux comprendre la façon dont vos données sont organisées?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Le </span><a href=\"http://recherche.umontreal.ca/services-aux-chercheurs/expertise-numerique/\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Centre d&rsquo;expertise num&eacute;rique pour la recherche</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> (CEN-R) peut vous aider &agrave; structurer et &agrave; nommer vos fichiers. Pour contacter le centre&nbsp;: </span><a href=\"mailto:info@cen.umontreal.ca\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">info@cen.umontreal.ca</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Des informations sur </span><strong>le nommage de fichiers et la gestion des versions</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> se trouvent dans le </span><a href=\"http://guides.bib.umontreal.ca/disciplines/500-Gestion-des-donnees-de-recherche?tab=2301\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">guide sur la GDR</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>"},{"id":321,"question_id":476,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2018-08-01 15:03:52 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-01 15:03:52 UTC","text":"Quels documents seront nécessaires pour que les données soient lues et interprétées correctement dans le futur?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Des informations de base se trouvent dans le </span><a href=\"http://guides.bib.umontreal.ca/disciplines/500-Gestion-des-donnees-de-recherche?tab=2301\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">guide sur la GDR</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>"},{"id":322,"question_id":477,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2018-08-01 15:04:20 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-01 15:04:20 UTC","text":"Comment vous assurerez-vous de documenter le projet de façon systématique tout au long du processus?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Concernant les</span><strong> cahiers de laboratoires </strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">dans certaines disciplines, des informations se trouvent dans le </span><a href=\"http://guides.bib.umontreal.ca/disciplines/500-Gestion-des-donnees-de-recherche?tab=2301\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">guide sur la GDR</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>"},{"id":323,"question_id":478,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2018-08-01 15:04:48 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-01 15:04:48 UTC","text":"Si vous utilisez une norme de métadonnées ou des outils pour documenter et décrire vos données, veuillez les indiquer ici.","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Des informations sur </span><strong>les m&eacute;tadonn&eacute;es</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> se trouvent dans le </span><a href=\"http://guides.bib.umontreal.ca/disciplines/500-Gestion-des-donnees-de-recherche?tab=2301\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">guide sur la GDR</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>"},{"id":324,"question_id":479,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2018-08-01 15:05:34 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-01 15:16:17 UTC","text":"Quels sont les besoins de stockage anticipés pour votre projet en matière d'espace (en mégaoctets, gigaoctets, téraoctets, etc.) et de durée de stockage?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Le CEN-R et les </span><a href=\"http://ti.umontreal.ca/\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Technologies de l'information</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> (TI) peuvent vous aider &agrave; &eacute;tablir vos besoins en termes de stockage.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Pour contacter le CEN-R&nbsp;: </span><a href=\"mailto:info@cen.umontreal.ca\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">info@cen.umontreal.ca</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Pour contacter les TI, utilisez </span><a href=\"http://ti.umontreal.ca/formulaires/formulaire_aide.html\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">ce formulaire</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>"},{"id":325,"question_id":480,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2018-08-01 15:06:06 UTC","updated_at":"2019-12-12 17:00:53 UTC","text":"Comment vos données seront-elles stockées et sauvegardées pendant votre projet de recherche et à quel endroit le seront-elles?","guidance":"<p><a href=\"http://www.calculquebec.ca/services-aux-chercheurs/procedures/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Calcul Qu&eacute;bec</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> offre un service de stockage de donn&eacute;es &agrave; tout chercheur admissible aux subventions des conseils de recherche canadiens. Pour les besoins de quelques To ou moins, vous pouvez passer par le <a href=\"https://www.computecanada.ca/page-daccueil-du-portail-de-recherche/acces-aux-ressources/acces-rapide/?lang=fr\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">service d'acc&egrave;s rapide</a>. Pour les besoin plus importants, vous devrez passer par le <a href=\"https://www.computecanada.ca/page-daccueil-du-portail-de-recherche/acces-aux-ressources/concours-dallocation-des-ressources/?lang=fr\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">concours d'allocation de ressources</a>.<br /></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Comme membre de la communaut&eacute; universitaire UdeM, vous disposez d&rsquo;un espace de stockage d&rsquo;un t&eacute;raoctet sur </span><a href=\"https://wiki.umontreal.ca/display/SIE/OneDrive+Entreprise\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">OneDrive Entreprise</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Les TI offrent &eacute;galement un service payant d&rsquo;h&eacute;bergement de serveur, virtuel ou non, de m&ecirc;me que des conseils pour l&rsquo;acquisition d&rsquo;un serveur et pour mettre en place une strat&eacute;gie de cryptage (utiliser </span><a href=\"http://ti.umontreal.ca/formulaires/formulaire_aide.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">ce formulaire</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> pour les contacter).</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Des informations sur </span><strong>le stockage et la sauvegarde des donn&eacute;es</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> se trouvent dans le </span><a href=\"http://guides.bib.umontreal.ca/disciplines/500-Gestion-des-donnees-de-recherche?tab=2301\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">guide sur la GDR</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>"},{"id":326,"question_id":481,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2018-08-01 15:06:35 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-03 16:08:28 UTC","text":"Comment l'équipe de recherche et d'autres collaborateurs pourront-ils accéder aux données, modifier celles-ci ou en ajouter de nouvelles tout au long du projet?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Le CEN-R peut vous aider &agrave; mettre en place une strat&eacute;gie de collaboration et de s&eacute;curit&eacute;. Pour contacter le centre: </span><a href=\"mailto:info@cen.umontreal.ca\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">info@cen.umontreal.ca</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Pour des conseils sur les donn&eacute;es sensibles, contactez un conseiller en &eacute;thique au </span><a href=\"https://recherche.umontreal.ca/qui-fait-quoi/#c16700\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Bureau de la conduite responsable en recherche</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> (BCRR).</span></p>"},{"id":327,"question_id":482,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2018-08-01 15:07:21 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-01 15:07:21 UTC","text":"Où déposerez-vous vos données en vue de l'accès et de la préservation à long terme à la fin de votre projet de recherche?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Des informations sur </span><strong>les d&eacute;p&ocirc;ts de donn&eacute;es</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> se trouvent dans le </span><a href=\"http://guides.bib.umontreal.ca/disciplines/500-Gestion-des-donnees-de-recherche?tab=2305\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">guide sur la GDR</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Pour des donn&eacute;es de recherche en format imprim&eacute; ou sur autre support analogique, contactez la </span><a href=\"http://www.archiv.umontreal.ca/joindre/index.html\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Division de la gestion de documents et des archives</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> (DGDA) de l&rsquo;UdeM pour discuter des possibilit&eacute;s. &nbsp;</span></p>"},{"id":328,"question_id":483,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2018-08-01 15:07:53 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-03 16:09:15 UTC","text":"Indiquez comment vous assurerez que vos données sont prêtes pour la conservation. À prendre en considération: formats de fichier appropriés pour la conservation mais qui préservent l'intégrité des données; anonymisation et dépersonnalisation des fichiers, y compris les fichiers de documentation. ","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Des informations sur </span><strong>le format des fichiers</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> se trouvent dans le </span><a href=\"http://guides.bib.umontreal.ca/disciplines/500-Gestion-des-donnees-de-recherche?tab=2301\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">guide sur la GDR</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Pour des conseils sur les donn&eacute;es sensibles, contactez un conseiller en &eacute;thique au </span><a href=\"https://recherche.umontreal.ca/qui-fait-quoi/#c16700\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">BCRR</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>"},{"id":329,"question_id":484,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2018-08-01 15:08:38 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-03 16:10:08 UTC","text":"Quelles données partagerez-vous et sous quelle forme? (p. ex. données brutes, traitées, analysées, définitives)?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Des informations sur </span><strong>le partage des donn&eacute;es</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> se trouvent dans le </span><a href=\"http://guides.bib.umontreal.ca/disciplines/500-Gestion-des-donnees-de-recherche?tab=2304\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">guide sur la GDR</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Pour des conseils sur les donn&eacute;es sensibles, contactez un conseiller en &eacute;thique au </span><a href=\"https://recherche.umontreal.ca/qui-fait-quoi/#c16700\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">BCRR</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>"},{"id":330,"question_id":485,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2018-08-01 15:09:09 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-01 15:09:09 UTC","text":"Avez-vous examiné quel type de licence d'utilisation inclure avec vos données?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Des informations sur </span><strong>les licences de diffusion</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> se trouvent dans le </span><a href=\"http://guides.bib.umontreal.ca/disciplines/500-Gestion-des-donnees-de-recherche?tab=2304\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">guide sur la GDR</span></a>.</p>"},{"id":331,"question_id":486,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2018-08-01 15:09:29 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-01 15:09:29 UTC","text":"Quelles mesures seront prises pour faire connaître l'existence de vos données au milieu de la recherche?","guidance":""},{"id":332,"question_id":487,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2018-08-01 15:10:35 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-01 15:10:35 UTC","text":"Identifiez qui sera responsable de la gestion des données de ce projet pendant et après le projet ainsi que les principales tâches associées à ces responsabilités.","guidance":""},{"id":333,"question_id":488,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2018-08-01 15:10:53 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-01 15:10:53 UTC","text":"De quelle façon les responsabilités relatives à la gestion des données seront-elles gérées si des changements importants surviennent au sein du personnel qui supervise les données du projet, y compris un changement de chercheur principal?","guidance":""},{"id":334,"question_id":489,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2018-08-01 15:11:20 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-01 15:11:20 UTC","text":"De quelles ressources aurez-vous besoin pour mettre en œuvre votre plan de gestion des données? À combien évaluez-vous le coût total de la gestion des données?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Le CEN-R peut vous aider &agrave; d&eacute;terminer les co&ucirc;ts d&rsquo;infrastructure n&eacute;cessaires &agrave; votre recherche. &nbsp;Pour contacter le centre&nbsp;: </span><a href=\"mailto:info@cen.umontreal.ca\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">info@cen.umontreal.ca</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>"},{"id":335,"question_id":490,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2018-08-01 15:12:18 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-01 15:12:18 UTC","text":"Si votre projet comprend des données sensibles, comment vous assurerez-vous qu'il est géré de manière sécuritaire et que les données sont accessibles uniquement aux membres approuvés du projet?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Pour des conseils, contactez un conseiller en &eacute;thique au </span><a href=\"https://recherche.umontreal.ca/qui-fait-quoi/#c16700\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">BCRR</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>"},{"id":336,"question_id":491,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2018-08-01 15:12:54 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-01 15:12:54 UTC","text":"Le cas échéant, quelles stratégies adopterez-vous pour traiter les utilisations secondaires des données sensibles?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Des informations sur </span><strong>les donn&eacute;es sensibles</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> se trouvent dans le </span><a href=\"http://guides.bib.umontreal.ca/disciplines/500-Gestion-des-donnees-de-recherche?tab=2301\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">guide sur la GDR</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>"},{"id":337,"question_id":492,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2018-08-01 15:13:28 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-01 15:13:28 UTC","text":"Comment traiterez-vous les questions d'ordre juridique, éthique et de propriété intellectuelle?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Vous pouvez consulter les </span><a href=\"https://secretariatgeneral.umontreal.ca/documents-officiels/reglements-et-politiques/#c48399\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">politiques de l&rsquo;UdeM en mati&egrave;re de recherche</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Vous trouverez aussi quelques pistes concernant </span><strong>la propri&eacute;t&eacute; intellectuelle des donn&eacute;es</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> dans le </span><a href=\"http://guides.bib.umontreal.ca/disciplines/500-Gestion-des-donnees-de-recherche?tab=2304\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">guide sur la GDR</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Pour des conseils, contactez un conseiller en &eacute;thique au </span><a href=\"https://recherche.umontreal.ca/qui-fait-quoi/#c16700\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">BCRR</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Puis n&rsquo;h&eacute;sitez pas &agrave; contacter un biblioth&eacute;caire &agrave; </span><a href=\"mailto:gdr@bib.umontreal.ca\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">gdr@bib.umontreal.ca</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> pour toute autre question sur la GDR.</span></p>"},{"id":338,"question_id":473,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-08-28 20:04:11 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-28 20:04:11 UTC","text":"Quels types de données allez-vous recueillir, créer, lier, acquérir ou enregistrer?","guidance":"<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<table>\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Pour plus d&rsquo;information sur la gestion des donn&eacute;es de recherche (GDR) en g&eacute;n&eacute;ral, consultez le </span><a href=\"http://guides.bib.umontreal.ca/disciplines/500-Gestion-des-donnees-de-recherche?tab=2299\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">guide sur la GDR des Biblioth&egrave;ques de l&rsquo;Universit&eacute; de Montr&eacute;al</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">N&rsquo;h&eacute;sitez pas &agrave; contacter un biblioth&eacute;caire &agrave; </span><a href=\"mailto:gdr@bib.umontreal.ca\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">gdr@bib.umontreal.ca</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>"},{"id":339,"question_id":474,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-08-28 20:05:04 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-28 20:05:04 UTC","text":"Dans quels formats de fichier vos données seront-elles recueillies? Ces formats permettront-ils la réutilisation des données, le partage et l'accès à long terme aux données?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Des informations sur </span><strong>le format des fichiers</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> se trouvent dans le </span><a href=\"http://guides.bib.umontreal.ca/disciplines/500-Gestion-des-donnees-de-recherche?tab=2301\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">guide sur la GDR</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>"},{"id":340,"question_id":475,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-08-28 20:07:02 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-28 20:07:02 UTC","text":"Quelles conventions et procédures utiliserez-vous pour structurer et nommer vos fichiers et en contrôler les versions afin de vous aider, ainsi que les utilisateurs potentiels, à mieux comprendre la façon dont vos données sont organisées?\r\n","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Le </span><a href=\"http://recherche.umontreal.ca/services-aux-chercheurs/expertise-numerique/\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Centre d&rsquo;expertise num&eacute;rique pour la recherche</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> (CEN-R) peut vous aider &agrave; structurer et &agrave; nommer vos fichiers. Pour contacter le centre&nbsp;: </span><a href=\"mailto:info@cen.umontreal.ca\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">info@cen.umontreal.ca</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Des informations sur </span><strong>le nommage de fichiers et la gestion des versions</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> se trouvent dans le </span><a href=\"http://guides.bib.umontreal.ca/disciplines/500-Gestion-des-donnees-de-recherche?tab=2301\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">guide sur la GDR</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>"},{"id":341,"question_id":476,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-08-28 20:07:59 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-28 20:07:59 UTC","text":"Quels documents seront nécessaires pour que les données soient lues et interprétées correctement dans le futur?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Des informations de base se trouvent dans le </span><a href=\"http://guides.bib.umontreal.ca/disciplines/500-Gestion-des-donnees-de-recherche?tab=2301\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">guide sur la GDR</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>"},{"id":342,"question_id":479,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-08-28 22:11:25 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-28 22:11:25 UTC","text":"Quels sont les besoins de stockage anticipés pour votre projet en matière d'espace (en mégaoctets, gigaoctets, téraoctets, etc.) et de durée de stockage?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Le CEN-R et les </span><a href=\"http://ti.umontreal.ca/\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Technologies de l'information</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> (TI) peuvent vous aider &agrave; &eacute;tablir vos besoins en termes de stockage.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Pour contacter le CEN-R&nbsp;: </span><a href=\"mailto:info@cen.umontreal.ca\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">info@cen.umontreal.ca</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Pour contacter les TI, utilisez </span><a href=\"http://ti.umontreal.ca/formulaires/formulaire_aide.html\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">ce formulaire</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>"},{"id":343,"question_id":480,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-08-28 22:11:56 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-28 22:11:56 UTC","text":"Comment vos données seront-elles stockées et sauvegardées pendant votre projet de recherche et à quel endroit le seront-elles?","guidance":"<p><a href=\"http://www.calculquebec.ca/services-aux-chercheurs/procedures/\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Calcul Qu&eacute;bec</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> offre un service de stockage de donn&eacute;es &agrave; tout chercheur admissible aux subventions des conseils de recherche canadiens. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Comme membre de la communaut&eacute; universitaire UdeM, vous disposez d&rsquo;un espace de stockage d&rsquo;un t&eacute;raoctet sur </span><a href=\"https://wiki.umontreal.ca/display/SIE/OneDrive+Entreprise\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">OneDrive Entreprise</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Les TI offrent &eacute;galement un service payant d&rsquo;h&eacute;bergement de serveur, virtuel ou non, de m&ecirc;me que des conseils pour l&rsquo;acquisition d&rsquo;un serveur et pour mettre en place une strat&eacute;gie de cryptage (utiliser </span><a href=\"http://ti.umontreal.ca/formulaires/formulaire_aide.html\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">ce formulaire</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> pour les contacter).</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Des informations sur </span><strong>le stockage et la sauvegarde des donn&eacute;es</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> se trouvent dans le </span><a href=\"http://guides.bib.umontreal.ca/disciplines/500-Gestion-des-donnees-de-recherche?tab=2301\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">guide sur la GDR</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>"},{"id":344,"question_id":481,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-08-28 22:26:29 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-28 22:26:29 UTC","text":" Comment l'équipe de recherche et d'autres collaborateurs pourront-ils accéder aux données, modifier celles-ci ou en ajouter de nouvelles tout au long du projet?","guidance":"<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<table>\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Le CEN-R peut vous aider &agrave; mettre en place une strat&eacute;gie de collaboration et de s&eacute;curit&eacute;. Pour contacter le centre: </span><a href=\"mailto:info@cen.umontreal.ca\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">info@cen.umontreal.ca</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Pour des conseils sur les donn&eacute;es sensibles, contactez un conseiller en &eacute;thique au </span><a href=\"https://recherche.umontreal.ca/qui-fait-quoi/#c16700\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Bureau de la conduite responsable en recherche</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> (BCRR).</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>"},{"id":345,"question_id":482,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-08-28 22:27:12 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-28 22:27:12 UTC","text":"Où déposerez-vous vos données en vue de l'accès et de la préservation à long terme à la fin de votre projet de recherche?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Des informations sur </span><strong>les d&eacute;p&ocirc;ts de donn&eacute;es</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> se trouvent dans le </span><a href=\"http://guides.bib.umontreal.ca/disciplines/500-Gestion-des-donnees-de-recherche?tab=2305\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">guide sur la GDR</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Pour des donn&eacute;es de recherche en format imprim&eacute; ou sur autre support analogique, contactez la </span><a href=\"http://www.archiv.umontreal.ca/joindre/index.html\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Division de la gestion de documents et des archives</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> (DGDA) de l&rsquo;UdeM pour discuter des possibilit&eacute;s. &nbsp;</span></p>"},{"id":346,"question_id":483,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-08-28 22:27:39 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-28 22:27:39 UTC","text":"Indiquez comment vous assurerez que vos données sont prêtes pour la conservation. À prendre en considération: formats de fichier appropriés pour la conservation mais qui préservent l'intégrité des données; anonymisation et dépersonnalisation des fichiers, y compris les fichiers de documentation. ","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Des informations sur </span><strong>le format des fichiers</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> se trouvent dans le </span><a href=\"http://guides.bib.umontreal.ca/disciplines/500-Gestion-des-donnees-de-recherche?tab=2301\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">guide sur la GDR</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Pour des conseils sur les donn&eacute;es sensibles, contactez un conseiller en &eacute;thique au </span><a href=\"https://recherche.umontreal.ca/qui-fait-quoi/#c16700\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">BCRR</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>"},{"id":347,"question_id":484,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-08-28 22:28:18 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-28 22:28:18 UTC","text":" Quelles données partagerez-vous et sous quelle forme? (p. ex. données brutes, traitées, analysées, définitives)","guidance":"<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<table>\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Des informations sur </span><strong>le partage des donn&eacute;es</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> se trouvent dans le </span><a href=\"http://guides.bib.umontreal.ca/disciplines/500-Gestion-des-donnees-de-recherche?tab=2304\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">guide sur la GDR</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Pour des conseils sur les donn&eacute;es sensibles, contactez un conseiller en &eacute;thique au </span><a href=\"https://recherche.umontreal.ca/qui-fait-quoi/#c16700\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">BCRR</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>"},{"id":348,"question_id":485,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-08-28 22:28:36 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-28 22:28:36 UTC","text":"Avez-vous examiné quel type de licence d'utilisation inclure avec vos données?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Des informations sur </span><strong>les licences de diffusion</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> se trouvent dans le </span><a href=\"http://guides.bib.umontreal.ca/disciplines/500-Gestion-des-donnees-de-recherche?tab=2304\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">guide sur la GDR</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>"},{"id":349,"question_id":486,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-08-28 22:28:51 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-28 22:28:51 UTC","text":"Quelles mesures seront prises pour faire connaître l'existence de vos données au milieu de la recherche?","guidance":""},{"id":350,"question_id":487,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-08-28 22:29:20 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-28 22:29:20 UTC","text":"Identifiez qui sera responsable de la gestion des données de ce projet pendant et après le projet ainsi que les principales tâches associées à ces responsabilités.","guidance":""},{"id":351,"question_id":488,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-08-28 22:29:33 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-28 22:29:33 UTC","text":"De quelle façon les responsabilités relatives à la gestion des données seront-elles gérées si des changements importants surviennent au sein du personnel qui supervise les données du projet, y compris un changement de chercheur principal?","guidance":""},{"id":352,"question_id":489,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-08-28 22:29:44 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-28 22:30:07 UTC","text":"De quelles ressources aurez-vous besoin pour mettre en œuvre votre plan de gestion des données? À combien évaluez-vous le coût total de la gestion des données?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Le CEN-R peut vous aider &agrave; d&eacute;terminer les co&ucirc;ts d&rsquo;infrastructure n&eacute;cessaires &agrave; votre recherche. &nbsp;Pour contacter le centre&nbsp;: </span><a href=\"mailto:info@cen.umontreal.ca\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">info@cen.umontreal.ca</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>"},{"id":353,"question_id":490,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-08-28 22:30:42 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-28 22:30:42 UTC","text":"Si votre projet comprend des données sensibles, comment vous assurerez-vous qu'il est géré de manière sécuritaire et que les données sont accessibles uniquement aux membres approuvés du projet?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Pour des conseils, contactez un conseiller en &eacute;thique au </span><a href=\"https://recherche.umontreal.ca/qui-fait-quoi/#c16700\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">BCRR</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>"},{"id":354,"question_id":491,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-08-28 22:30:56 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-28 22:31:30 UTC","text":" Le cas échéant, quelles stratégies adopterez-vous pour traiter les utilisations secondaires des données sensibles?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Des informations sur </span><strong>les donn&eacute;es sensibles</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> se trouvent dans le </span><a href=\"http://guides.bib.umontreal.ca/disciplines/500-Gestion-des-donnees-de-recherche?tab=2301\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">guide sur la GDR</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>"},{"id":355,"question_id":492,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-08-28 22:31:17 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-28 22:31:17 UTC","text":"Comment traiterez-vous les questions d'ordre juridique, éthique et de propriété intellectuelle?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Vous pouvez consulter les </span><a href=\"https://secretariatgeneral.umontreal.ca/documents-officiels/reglements-et-politiques/#c48399\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">politiques de l&rsquo;UdeM en mati&egrave;re de recherche</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Vous trouverez aussi quelques pistes concernant </span><strong>la propri&eacute;t&eacute; intellectuelle des donn&eacute;es</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> dans le </span><a href=\"http://guides.bib.umontreal.ca/disciplines/500-Gestion-des-donnees-de-recherche?tab=2304\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">guide sur la GDR</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Pour des conseils, contactez un conseiller en &eacute;thique au </span><a href=\"https://recherche.umontreal.ca/qui-fait-quoi/#c16700\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">BCRR</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Puis n&rsquo;h&eacute;sitez pas &agrave; contacter un biblioth&eacute;caire &agrave; </span><a href=\"mailto:gdr@bib.umontreal.ca\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">gdr@bib.umontreal.ca</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> pour toute autre question sur la GDR.</span></p>"},{"id":357,"question_id":514,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-08-30 16:52:39 UTC","updated_at":"2020-10-13 17:40:31 UTC","text":"What types of data will you collect, create, link to, acquire and/or record?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Research data are used as primary sources to support technical or scientific enquiry, research, scholarship, or artistic activity, and are used as evidence in the research process and/or are commonly accepted in the research community as necessary to validate research findings and results. Research data may be experimental data, observational data, operational data, third party data, public sector data, monitoring data, processed data, or repurposed data.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Examples: numeric, images, audio, video, text, tabular data, modeling data, spatial data, instrumentation data.</span></p>"},{"id":358,"question_id":515,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-08-30 16:54:43 UTC","updated_at":"2018-10-16 18:22:51 UTC","text":"What file formats will your data be collected in? \r\n\r\nConsider whether these formats will allow for data re-use, sharing and long-term access to the data. If they do not, will it be possible to convert your data to a more accessible format after collecting the data?\r\n","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Proprietary file formats requiring specialized software or hardware to use are not recommended, but may be necessary for certain data collection or analysis methods. Using open file formats or industry-standard formats (e.g. those widely used by a given community) is preferred whenever possible.</span><br /><a href=\"https://libguides.uvic.ca/researchdata/planning/formatting\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Read more about file formats</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>"},{"id":359,"question_id":516,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-08-30 16:55:39 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-30 16:56:27 UTC","text":"What conventions and procedures will you use to structure, name and version-control your files to help you and others better understand how your data are organized?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">It is important to keep track of different copies or versions of files, files held in different formats or locations, and information cross-referenced between files. This process is called 'version control'.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Logical file structures, informative naming conventions, and clear indications of file versions, all contribute to better use of your data during and after your research project. &nbsp;These practices will help ensure that you and your research team are using the appropriate version of your data, and minimize confusion regarding copies on different computers and/or on different media.</span><br /><a href=\"https://libguides.uvic.ca/researchdata/planning/organization\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Read more about file naming and version control</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>"},{"id":360,"question_id":517,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-08-30 16:58:30 UTC","updated_at":"2018-10-16 18:24:06 UTC","text":"What documentation will be needed for the data to be read and interpreted correctly in the future?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Typically, good documentation includes information about the study, data-level descriptions, and any other contextual information required to make the data usable by other researchers. Other elements you should document, as applicable, include: research methodology used, variable definitions, vocabularies, classification systems, units of measurement, assumptions made in collecting or analyzing the data, format and file type of the data, a description of the data capture and collection methods, explanation of data coding and analysis performed (including syntax files), and details of who has worked on the project and performed each task.</span></p>\r\n<p><a href=\"https://libguides.uvic.ca/researchdata/planning/documentation\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Read more about documentation</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>"},{"id":361,"question_id":518,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-08-30 16:59:23 UTC","updated_at":"2018-10-16 18:25:13 UTC","text":"How will you make sure that documentation is created or captured consistently throughout your project?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Consider how you will capture this information and where it will be recorded, ideally in advance of data collection and analysis, to ensure accuracy, consistency, and completeness of the documentation. Often, resources you've already created can contribute to this (e.g. publications, websites, progress reports, etc.). It is useful to consult regularly with members of the research team to capture potential changes in data collection/processing that need to be reflected in the documentation. Individual roles and workflows should include gathering data documentation as a key element.</span></p>"},{"id":362,"question_id":519,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-08-30 17:00:39 UTC","updated_at":"2018-10-16 18:25:43 UTC","text":"Do you plan to use a metadata standard and/or tools to document and describe your data? If so, please list here.","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">There are many general and domain-specific metadata standards. Datasets should be described with one of these standard, machine readable, openly-accessible formats to enable the effective exchange of information between users and systems. These standards are often based on language-independent data formats such as XML, RDF, and JSON. </span></p>\r\n<p><a href=\"https://libguides.uvic.ca/researchdata/planning/documentation\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Read more about metadata standards</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>"},{"id":363,"question_id":520,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-08-30 17:03:45 UTC","updated_at":"2018-10-16 18:19:48 UTC","text":"What are the anticipated storage requirements for your project, in terms of storage space (in megabytes, gigabytes, terabytes, etc.) and the length of time you will be storing it?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Storage-space estimates should take into account requirements for file versioning, backups, and growth over time. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">If you are collecting data over a long period (e.g. several months or years), your data storage and backup strategy should accommodate data growth. Similarly, a long-term storage plan is necessary if you intend to retain your data after the research project.</span></p>\r\n<p><a href=\"https://libguides.uvic.ca/researchdata/planning/storagesecurity\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Read more about data storage and security</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>"},{"id":364,"question_id":521,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-08-30 17:04:22 UTC","updated_at":"2018-10-16 18:19:20 UTC","text":"How and where will your data be stored and backed up during your research project?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The risk of losing data due to human error, natural disasters, or other mishaps can be mitigated by following the </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">3-2-1 backup rule</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">:</span></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Have at least three copies of your data</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Store the copies on two different media</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Keep one backup copy off-site</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Data may be stored using optical or magnetic media, which can be removable (e.g. DVD and USB drives), fixed (e.g. desktop or laptop hard drives), or networked (e.g. networked drives or cloud-based servers). Each storage method has benefits and drawbacks that should be considered when determining the most appropriate solution.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">At the University of Victoria, University Systems offers a range of services for research computing and data storage. <a href=\"https://www.uvic.ca/systems/services/index.php\" target=\"_blank\">Consult their service catalogue </a></span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><a href=\"https://www.uvic.ca/systems/services/index.php\" target=\"_blank\"> for their complete range of services</a>.</span></p>"},{"id":365,"question_id":522,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-08-30 17:08:35 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-30 17:08:35 UTC","text":"How will the research team and other collaborators access, modify, and contribute data throughout the project?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">An ideal solution is one that facilitates </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">cooperation</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> and ensures data security, yet is able to be adopted by users with minimal training. Transmitting data between locations or within research teams can be challenging for data management infrastructure. Relying on email for data transfer is not a robust or secure solution. Third-party commercial file sharing services (such as Google Drive and Dropbox) facilitate file exchange, but they are not necessarily permanent or secure, and are often located outside Canada.</span></p>"},{"id":366,"question_id":523,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-08-30 17:14:19 UTC","updated_at":"2018-10-16 18:30:23 UTC","text":"If your research project includes sensitive data, how will you ensure that it is securely managed and accessible only to approved members of the project?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Consider where, how, and to whom sensitive data with acknowledged long-term value should be made available, and how long it should be archived. For research projects involving human participants and human biological materials, these decisions should align with </span><a href=\"https://www.uvic.ca/research/conduct/home/regapproval/humanethics/index.php\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">UVic's Human Research Ethics Board</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> requirements.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The methods used to share data will be dependent on a number of factors such as the type, size, complexity and degree of sensitivity of data. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Outline problems anticipated in sharing data, along with causes and possible measures to mitigate these. Problems may include confidentiality, lack of consent agreements, or concerns about iIntellectual pProperty rRights, among others. In some instances, an embargo period may be justified; these may be defined by a funding agency's policy on research data.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Restrictions can be imposed by limiting physical access to storage devices, by placing data on computers that do not have external network access (i.e. access to the Internet), through password protection, and by encrypting files. Sensitive data should never be shared via email or cloud storage services such as Dropbox.</span></p>"},{"id":367,"question_id":524,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-08-30 17:15:12 UTC","updated_at":"2018-10-16 18:38:16 UTC","text":"If applicable, what strategies will you undertake to address secondary uses of sensitive data?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">For research involving human participants, obtaining the appropriate consent from research participants is an important step in assuring <a href=\"https://www.uvic.ca/research/conduct/home/regapproval/humanethics/index.php\" target=\"_blank\">Human Research Ethics Boards</a> that the data may be shared with researchers outside your project. The consent statement may identify certain conditions clarifying the uses of the data by other researchers. For example, it may stipulate that the data will only be shared for non-profit research purposes or that the data will not be linked with personally identified data from other sources.</span></p>"},{"id":368,"question_id":525,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-08-30 17:16:01 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-30 17:16:01 UTC","text":"How will you manage legal, ethical, and intellectual property issues?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Compliance with privacy legislation and laws that may impose content restrictions in the data should be discussed with your institution's privacy officer or research services office. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Include here a description concerning ownership, licensing, and intellectual property rights of the data. Terms of reuse must be clearly stated, in line with the relevant legal and ethical requirements where applicable (e.g., subject consent, permissions, restrictions, etc.).</span></p>"},{"id":369,"question_id":526,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-08-30 17:19:27 UTC","updated_at":"2018-10-16 18:50:18 UTC","text":"Where will you deposit your data for long-term storage at the end of your research project?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The issue of data retention and storage should be considered early in the research lifecycle. These decisions can be driven by institutional or external policies (e.g. funding agencies, journal publishers), or by an understanding of the enduring value of a given set of data, which may influence the choice of data repository. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">UVic Libraries provides access to two institutional repositories, </span><a href=\"https://libguides.uvic.ca/researchdata/share/dataverse\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Dataverse</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> and </span><a href=\"https://dspace.library.uvic.ca/\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">UVicSpace</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, either of which may be suitable depending on your type of data.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Various domain-</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">specific</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> repositories also exist for depositing research data, which may be preferable.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">For assistance locating a suitable data repository or archive, please contact </span><a href=\"mailto:skhair@uvic.ca\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">UVic Libraries</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>"},{"id":370,"question_id":527,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-08-30 17:21:06 UTC","updated_at":"2020-10-13 17:41:46 UTC","text":"Indicate how you will ensure your data is preservation friendly. Consider non-proprietary file formats, ensuring file integrity, and inclusion of supporting documentation.","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Some data formats are optimal for long-term preservation of data. For example, non-proprietary file formats, such as text ('.txt') and comma-separated ('.csv'), are considered preservation-friendly. Keep in mind that preservation-friendly files converted from one format to another may lose information (e.g. converting from an uncompressed TIFF file to a compressed JPG file), so changes to file formats should be documented. </span></p>\r\n<p><a href=\"https://libguides.uvic.ca/researchdata/planning/formatting\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Read more about file formats</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>"},{"id":371,"question_id":528,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-08-30 17:24:02 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-30 17:24:02 UTC","text":"What data will you be sharing and in what form? (e.g. raw, processed, analyzed, final).","guidance":"<p><strong>Raw data</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> are the data directly obtained from the instrument, simulation or survey.</span></p>\r\n<p><strong>Processed data</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> result from some manipulation of the raw data in order to eliminate errors or outliers, to prepare the data for analysis, to derive new variables, or to de-identify the human participants.</span></p>\r\n<p><strong>Analyzed data</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> are the the results of qualitative, statistical, or mathematical analysis of the processed data. They can be presented as graphs, charts or statistical tables.</span></p>\r\n<p><strong>Final data</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> are processed data that have, if needed, been converted into a preservation-friendly format. Consider which data may need to be shared in order to meet institutional or funding requirements, and which data may be restricted because of confidentiality/ privacy/ intellectual property considerations.</span></p>"},{"id":372,"question_id":529,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-08-30 17:24:57 UTC","updated_at":"2018-10-16 18:28:58 UTC","text":"Have you considered what type of end-user license to include with your data?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Licenses determine what uses can be made of your data. Funding agencies and/or data repositories may have end-user license requirements in place; if not, they may still be able to guide you in the development of a license. Once created, please consider including a copy of your end-user license with your Data Management Plan. Note that only the intellectual property rights holder(s) can issue a license, so it is crucial to clarify who owns those rights.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">There are several types of standard licenses available to researchers, such as the </span><a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/choose/\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Creative Commons licenses</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> and the </span><a href=\"http://opendatacommons.org/licenses/\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Open Data Commons licenses</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">. In fact, for most datasets it is easier to use a standard license rather than to devise a custom-made one. Note that even if you choose to make your data part of the public domain, it is preferable to make this explicit by using a license such as Creative Commons' CC0.</span><br /><a href=\"https://libguides.uvic.ca/researchdata/share\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Read more about data licensing</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>"},{"id":373,"question_id":530,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-08-30 17:25:52 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-30 17:25:52 UTC","text":"What steps will be taken to help the research community know that your data exists?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Possibilities include: data registries, repositories, indexes, word-of-mouth, publications.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">How will the data be accessed (Web service, ftp, etc.)? If possible, choose a repository that will assign a persistent identifier (such as a DOI) to your dataset. This will ensure a stable access to the dataset and make it retrievable by various discovery tools.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">One of the best ways to refer other researchers to your deposited datasets is to cite them the same way you cite other types of publications (articles, books, proceedings).</span><br /><a href=\"https://libguides.uvic.ca/researchdata/share\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Read more about data citation and attribution</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>"},{"id":374,"question_id":531,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-08-30 17:26:56 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-30 17:26:56 UTC","text":"Identify who will be responsible for managing this project's data during and after the project and the major data management tasks for which they will be responsible.","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Your data management plan has identified important data activities in your project. Identify who will be responsible -- individuals or organizations -- for carrying out these parts of your data management plan. This could also include the time frame associated with these staff responsibilities and any training needed to prepare staff for these duties.</span></p>"},{"id":375,"question_id":532,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-08-30 17:27:36 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-30 17:27:36 UTC","text":"How will responsibilities for managing data activities be handled if substantive changes happen in the personnel overseeing the project's data, including a change of Principal Investigator?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Indicate a succession strategy for these data in the event that one or more people responsible for the data leaves (e.g. a graduate student leaving after graduation).</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Describe the process to be followed in the event that the Principal Investigator leaves the project. In some instances, a co-investigator or the department or division overseeing this research will assume responsibility.</span></p>"},{"id":376,"question_id":533,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-08-30 17:28:07 UTC","updated_at":"2018-08-30 17:28:07 UTC","text":"What resources will you require to implement your data management plan? What do you estimate the overall cost for data management to be?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">This estimate should incorporate data management costs incurred during the project as well as those required for the longer-term support for the data after the project is finished. Items to consider in the latter category of expenses include the costs of curating and providing long-term access to the data. Some funding agencies state explicitly the support that they will provide to meet the cost of preparing data for deposit. This might include technical aspects of data management, training requirements, file storage &amp; backup, and contributions of non-project staff.</span></p>"},{"id":377,"question_id":477,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-09-11 05:23:54 UTC","updated_at":"2018-09-11 05:23:54 UTC","text":"Comment vous assurerez-vous de documenter le projet de façon systématique tout au long du processus?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Concernant les</span><strong> cahiers de laboratoires </strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">dans certaines disciplines, des informations se trouvent dans le </span><a href=\"http://guides.bib.umontreal.ca/disciplines/500-Gestion-des-donnees-de-recherche?tab=2301\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">guide sur la GDR</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>"},{"id":378,"question_id":478,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-09-11 05:26:47 UTC","updated_at":"2018-09-11 05:26:47 UTC","text":"Si vous utilisez une norme de métadonnées ou des outils pour documenter et décrire vos données, veuillez les indiquer ici.\r\n","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Des informations sur </span><strong>les m&eacute;tadonn&eacute;es</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> se trouvent dans le </span><a href=\"http://guides.bib.umontreal.ca/disciplines/500-Gestion-des-donnees-de-recherche?tab=2301\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">guide sur la GDR</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>"},{"id":380,"question_id":535,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-09-12 12:24:34 UTC","updated_at":"2019-01-31 16:17:02 UTC","text":"Where will you deposit your data for long-term preservation and access at the end of your research project?","guidance":"<p>The issue of data retention should be considered early in the research lifecycle. The need to preserve data in the short-term (i.e. for peer-verification purposes) or long-term (for data of lasting value), will influence the choice of data repository or archive.</p>"},{"id":381,"question_id":536,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-09-12 12:24:52 UTC","updated_at":"2019-01-28 13:53:18 UTC","text":"Indicate how you will ensure your data is preservation ready. Consider preservation-friendly file formats, ensuring file integrity, anonymization and de-identification, inclusion of supporting documentation.","guidance":"<p style=\"margin: 0in 0in 7.5pt 0in;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: 'Helvetica',sans-serif; color: #3e3c3c;\">Some data formats are optimal for long-term preservation of data. For example, non-proprietary file formats, such as text ('.txt') and comma-separated ('.csv'), are considered preservation-friendly. When converting files from one format to another check to ensure no information has been lost during the transition.</span></p>"},{"id":382,"question_id":537,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-09-12 12:25:28 UTC","updated_at":"2018-09-12 12:25:28 UTC","text":"Are you aware of any current or future restrictions on the data used in and/or generated during this project?","guidance":""},{"id":383,"question_id":538,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-09-12 12:25:58 UTC","updated_at":"2019-01-28 13:27:38 UTC","text":"If so, what data will you be sharing and in what form? (e.g. raw, processed, analyzed, final)","guidance":"<p style=\"margin: 0in; margin-bottom: .0001pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: 'Helvetica',sans-serif; color: #3e3c3c;\">Raw data</span></strong><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: 'Helvetica',sans-serif; color: #3e3c3c;\">&nbsp;are the data directly obtained from the instrument, simulation or survey.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0in; margin-bottom: .0001pt; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; widows: 2; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration-style: initial; text-decoration-color: initial; word-spacing: 0px;\"><strong><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: 'Helvetica',sans-serif; color: #3e3c3c;\">Processed data</span></strong><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: 'Helvetica',sans-serif; color: #3e3c3c;\">&nbsp;result from some manipulation of the raw data in order to eliminate errors or outliers, to prepare the data for analysis, to derive new variables, or to de-identify the human participants.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0in; margin-bottom: .0001pt; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; widows: 2; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration-style: initial; text-decoration-color: initial; word-spacing: 0px;\"><strong><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: 'Helvetica',sans-serif; color: #3e3c3c;\">Analyzed data</span></strong><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: 'Helvetica',sans-serif; color: #3e3c3c;\">&nbsp;are the the results of qualitative, statistical, or mathematical analysis of the processed data. They can be presented as graphs, charts or statistical tables.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0in; margin-bottom: .0001pt; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; widows: 2; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration-style: initial; text-decoration-color: initial; word-spacing: 0px;\"><strong><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: 'Helvetica',sans-serif; color: #3e3c3c;\">Final data</span></strong><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: 'Helvetica',sans-serif; color: #3e3c3c;\">&nbsp;are processed data that have, if needed, been converted into a preservation-friendly format.</span></p>"},{"id":384,"question_id":539,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-09-12 12:26:19 UTC","updated_at":"2018-10-05 19:50:06 UTC","text":"Will you make data from this project available for sharing?","guidance":"<p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 10px; font-size: 14px; font-family: 'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; color: #3e3c3c; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration-style: initial; text-decoration-color: initial;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 10px; font-size: 14px; font-family: 'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; color: #3e3c3c; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration-style: initial; text-decoration-color: initial;\">&nbsp;</p>"},{"id":385,"question_id":540,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-11-13 16:19:50 UTC","updated_at":"2018-11-13 16:19:50 UTC","text":"1.1 Name of project or sub-project and project number (if applicable).\r\n","guidance":""},{"id":386,"question_id":541,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-11-13 16:21:40 UTC","updated_at":"2018-11-13 16:33:41 UTC","text":"1.2  Please provide an outline description of the research project and the intended products of the research.","guidance":"<p>Scope of project or sub-project. Describe the types of data and products that will be generated in the research, such as images of astronomical objects, spectra, data tables, time series, theoretical formalisms, computational strategies, software, and curriculum materials.</p>"},{"id":387,"question_id":542,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-11-13 16:23:38 UTC","updated_at":"2018-11-13 16:35:13 UTC","text":"1.3  Please provide details of the project timelines.","guidance":"<p>Start date, end date, and duration of major tasks of the project.</p>"},{"id":388,"question_id":543,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-11-13 16:24:37 UTC","updated_at":"2018-11-13 16:36:09 UTC","text":"1.4 Principal Investigator(s)","guidance":"<p>Name(s) and affiliation(s) of Principal Investigator(s).</p>"},{"id":389,"question_id":544,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-11-13 16:25:38 UTC","updated_at":"2018-11-13 16:35:44 UTC","text":"1.5 Identify collaborating Agencies/Organizations.","guidance":"<p>List any collaborating agencies and organizations, if applicable.</p>"},{"id":390,"question_id":545,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-11-13 16:27:41 UTC","updated_at":"2018-11-13 16:38:11 UTC","text":"2.1 What types of data will you collect, create, link to, acquire and/or record?","guidance":"<p>Examples: numeric, images, audio, video, text, tabular data, modeling data, spatial data, instrumentation data.</p>"},{"id":391,"question_id":546,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-11-13 16:32:21 UTC","updated_at":"2018-11-13 16:32:21 UTC","text":"2.2 What file formats will your data be collected in? Will these formats allow for data re-use, sharing and long-term access to the data?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Use open (non-proprietary) file formats whenever possible. Proprietary file formats that require specialized software or hardware are not recommended but may be necessary for certain types of data collection or analysis. Using open file formats or industry-standard formats, especially those widely used by a given community, is preferred whenever possible. Changes to file formats should be documented and original files saved with preservation-friendly versions.</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><br /></span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><br /></span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Read more about </span><a href=\"http://www.dcc.ac.uk/resources/curation-reference-manual/completed-chapters/file-formats\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">file formats</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> and a list of </span><a href=\"https://www.ukdataservice.ac.uk/manage-data/format/recommended-formats\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">recommended formats</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> from UK Data Archive.</span></p>"},{"id":392,"question_id":547,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-11-13 16:40:05 UTC","updated_at":"2018-11-13 16:40:05 UTC","text":"2.3 How much data do you anticipate collecting? Include an estimate of how much storage space you will require (in megabytes, gigabytes, terabytes). This estimate should also take into account storage space required for file versioning, backups, and the growth rate over time.","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The type of data you collect will impact your storage requirements. Textual and tabular data files are usually very small (a few megabytes) unless you have a lot of data. Video files are usually very large (hundreds of megabytes up to several gigabytes). If you have a large amount of data (gigabytes or terabytes), it will be more challenging to share and transfer it. You may need to consider networked storage options or more sophisticated backup methods.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">If your data will be changing frequently, please estimate how much extra storage will be required to store multiple versions. If you are collecting data over a long period of time (e.g. several months or years), please describe your plan for adding additional storage to accommodate the growth of your data.</span></p>"},{"id":393,"question_id":548,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-11-13 16:42:02 UTC","updated_at":"2018-11-13 16:42:02 UTC","text":"2.4 Are there are any existing data that you can re-use? If so, please explain how you will obtain that data and integrate it into your research project.","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Considering answering the following questions: Where did the existing dataset(s) come from? Is that data published or publicly available? Will the project use contracted datasets (data from external sources?) &nbsp;If yes, will you be able to store a local copy of the contracted data?</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Contact York University Libraries&rsquo; </span><a href=\"http://scottlibrary.apps01.yorku.ca/machform/view.php?id=31546\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Open Scholarship Department</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> for help with finding existing data.</span></p>"},{"id":394,"question_id":549,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-11-13 16:44:07 UTC","updated_at":"2018-11-13 16:44:07 UTC","text":"2.5 What conventions and procedures will you use to structure, name and version-control your files to help you and others better understand how your data are organized?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Logical file structures, informative naming conventions, and clear indications of file versions, all contribute to better use of your data during and after your research project. These practices will help ensure that you and your research team are using the appropriate version of your data, and minimize confusion regarding copies on different computers and/or on different media.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Read more about </span><a href=\"https://www.ukdataservice.ac.uk/manage-data/format/organising\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">file organizing</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> and </span><a href=\"https://www.ukdataservice.ac.uk/manage-data/format/versioning\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">version control</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> from UK Data Archive.</span></p>"},{"id":395,"question_id":550,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-11-13 16:46:32 UTC","updated_at":"2019-10-28 12:57:51 UTC","text":"3.1 What documentation will be needed for the data to be read and interpreted correctly in the future? This includes study-level documentation, data-level description, and any other contextual information required to make the data usable by other researchers.","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Your documentation may include study-level information about:</span></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">who created/collected the data</span></li>\r\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">when it was created</span></li>\r\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">any relevant study documents</span></li>\r\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">conditions of use</span></li>\r\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">contextual details about data collection methods and procedural documentation about how data files are stored, structured, and modified.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">A complete description of the data files may include:</span></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">naming and labelling conventions</span></li>\r\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">explanations of codes and variables</span></li>\r\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">any information or files require to reproduce derived data.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">More information about data documentation is available at the </span><a href=\"https://www.ukdataservice.ac.uk/manage-data/document.aspx\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">UK Data Archive</span></a></p>"},{"id":396,"question_id":551,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-11-13 16:47:35 UTC","updated_at":"2018-11-13 16:47:35 UTC","text":"3.2 How will you make sure that documentation is created or captured consistently throughout your project?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Consider how you will capture this information and where it will be recorded, ideally in advance of data collection and analysis, to ensure accuracy, consistency, and completeness of the documentation. &nbsp;Often, resources you've already created can contribute to this (e.g. publications, websites, progress reports, etc.). It is useful to consult regularly with members of the research team to capture potential changes in data collection/processing that need to be reflected in the documentation. &nbsp;Individual roles and workflows should include gathering data documentation as a key element.</span></p>"},{"id":397,"question_id":552,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-11-13 16:49:14 UTC","updated_at":"2019-04-24 10:46:48 UTC","text":"3.3 If you are using a metadata standard and/or tools to document and describe your data, please list here.","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Metadata is a description of the contents and context of data files. Using a metadata standard (a set of required fields to fill out) helps ensure that your documentation is consistent, structured, and machine-readable, which is essential for depositing data in repositories and making it easily discoverable by search engines.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">There are general and discipline-specific </span><a href=\"http://www.dcc.ac.uk/resources/metadata-standards\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">metadata standards and tools</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> for research data. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">For assistance with choosing and using a metadata standard, please contact York University Libraries at yul_rdm@yorku.ca</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">. </span></p>"},{"id":398,"question_id":553,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-11-13 16:52:14 UTC","updated_at":"2018-11-13 16:52:14 UTC","text":"4.1 What are the anticipated storage requirements for your project, in terms of storage space (in megabytes, gigabytes, terabytes, etc.) and the length of time you will be storing it? \r\n\r\nIf applicable, where are hardcopy notebooks and physical samples going to be physically stored?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Storage-space estimates should take into account requirements for file versioning, backups, and growth over time. They should also take into account whether the data will be preserved for a set number of years, or whether it needs to be preserved in perpetuity.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">If you are collecting data over a long period (e.g. several months or years), your data storage and backup strategy should accommodate data growth. Similarly, a long-term storage plan is necessary if you intend to retain your data after the research project.</span></p>"},{"id":399,"question_id":554,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-11-13 16:53:37 UTC","updated_at":"2018-11-13 16:54:29 UTC","text":"4.2 How and where will your data be stored and backed up during your research project?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The risk of losing data due to human error, natural disasters, or other mishaps can be mitigated by following the 3-2-1 backup rule:</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><br /></span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">1. Have at least three copies of your data.</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><br /></span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">2. Store the copies on two different media.</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><br /></span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">3. Keep one backup copy offsite</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><br /></span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Data may be stored using optical or magnetic media, which can be removable (e.g. DVD and USB drives), fixed (e.g. desktop or laptop hard drives), or networked (e.g. networked drives or cloud-based servers). Each storage method has benefits and drawbacks that should be considered when determining the most appropriate solution.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Using software which automatically backs up your data and keeps it synchronized with a master copy is recommended. Copies of data should ideally be stored in separate physical locations to mitigate physical risks, e.g. fire. More about data storage from </span><a href=\"https://www.ukdataservice.ac.uk/manage-data/store\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">UK Data Archive</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">For York University researchers, UIT provides </span><a href=\"https://staff.computing.yorku.ca/support-services/server-data-storage/\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">secure storage solutions</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> that meet and exceed the 3-2-1 backup rule. Each file saved to UIT storage is copied three times, resulting in four separate copies. These copies reside in two separate data centres on campus, with the fourth copy stored at the University of Guelph. Find more information about </span><a href=\"https://staff.computing.yorku.ca/support-services/server-data-storage/\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Server Data Storage offered by UIT</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">. </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">It is important that a conversation is had with UIT prior to submitting your grant as there may be costs associated with data storage that will need to be represented in your budget.</span></p>"},{"id":400,"question_id":555,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-11-13 16:53:37 UTC","updated_at":"2018-11-13 16:58:20 UTC","text":"4.3 How will the research team and other collaborators access, modify, and contribute data throughout the project?\r\n\r\nIf applicable, how will you ensure that sensitive data is stored securely and only accessible to the research team and other collaborators throughout the project?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">An ideal solution is one that facilitates co-operation and ensures data security. The security measures you choose to implement will depend on the sensitivity of the data being stored. Data can be protected by limiting physical access to hard drives and file servers on which it is stored, by storing data on computers that do not have external network access (i.e. access to the Internet), through password protection, and by encrypting data files. Sharing sensitive data via email and cloud storage services such as Dropbox is not recommended, since the security of these services cannot be trusted. </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">&nbsp;Check out the York University&rsquo;s </span><a href=\"https://research.info.yorku.ca/data-security-guideline-research-involving-human-participants/\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Data Security Guideline for Research Involving Human Participants</span></a></p>"},{"id":401,"question_id":556,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-11-13 17:00:52 UTC","updated_at":"2018-11-13 17:00:52 UTC","text":"5.1 Which data are selected for preservation and access? ","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Which data are selected for preservation and access will depend on potential reuse value, whether there are obligations to either retain or destroy data, and the resources required to properly curate the data and ensure that it remains usable in the future. In some circumstances, it may be feasible to preserve all versions of the data (e.g. raw, processed, analyzed, final), but in others, it may be preferable to only keep only selected data (e.g. transcripts instead of audio interviews).</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">It is important that the cost of longer term storage for larger data sets be considered and factored into the grant budget. See Section 4.2: </span><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">How and where will your data be stored and backed up during your research project?</span></em></p>"},{"id":402,"question_id":557,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-11-13 17:00:52 UTC","updated_at":"2019-04-24 10:48:45 UTC","text":"5.2 Where will you deposit your data for long-term preservation and access at the end of your research project? Is there specific software needed in order to use or interpret your research data collection?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Please describe how you will identify a data repository or data center for your data.</span></p>\r\n<p><a href=\"https://www.library.yorku.ca/web/open/rdm/depositdata/\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Scholars Portal Dataverse</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> is available to York researchers and can serve preservation needs where file sizes are less than 2 GB. Scholars Portal Dataverse allows researchers to restrict access to datasets in compliance with research ethics guidelines.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Another option is the </span><a href=\"https://www.frdr.ca/repo/\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Federated Research Data Repository (FRDR)</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> which also allows for data deposit. FRDR allows researchers to set an embargo period for their data.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Larger projects will need to </span><a href=\"http://staff.computing.yorku.ca/support-services/server-data-storage/#squelch-taas-toggle-shortcode-content-0\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">contact UIT</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> to discuss the ongoing cost of long-term preservation. It is prudent that these costs be written into the grant budget.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">For other data deposit options, including discipline specific repositories, see the </span><a href=\"http://www.re3data.org/\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">re3data.org</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> directory.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">There are many ways in which you can release your software. These include: a binary executable that can be run directly; bundled in an installer program; an archive (.zip or .tar.gz) of binary executables or libraries, or as Python or R packages; an archive of source code; via a download link on a web site; via e-mail from you; via access to a source code repository hosted at your institution or on a third-party site such as GitHub (<a href=\"http://github.com\" target=\"_blank\">http://github.com</a></span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">), GitLab (<a href=\"http://www.gitlab.com\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.gitlab.com</a></span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">), BitBucket (</span><a href=\"http://bitbucket.org\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">http://bitbucket.org</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><a href=\"http://bitbucket.org\" target=\"_blank\">)</a>, LaunchPad (<a href=\"https://launchpad.net\" target=\"_blank\">https://launchpad.net</a></span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">) or Assembla (</span><a href=\"https://www.assembla.com\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">https://www.assembla.com</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">). (The Software Sustainability Institute. (2016). Checklist for a Software Management Plan. v0.1. doi: </span><a href=\"https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.1422657\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">10.5281/zenodo.1422657</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">. Available online: https://www.software.ac.uk/software-management-plans.)</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">If you need assistance locating a suitable data repository or archive, please contact York University Libraries at yul_rdm@yorku.ca</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">. </span></p>"},{"id":403,"question_id":558,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-11-13 17:07:47 UTC","updated_at":"2019-10-28 12:58:47 UTC","text":"5.3 Indicate how you will ensure your data is preservation ready. Consider preservation-friendly file formats, ensuring file integrity, anonymization and de-identification, inclusion of supporting documentation.","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">It is likely that you will have multiple versions of your data (raw, processed, analyzed, final), and your data may be stored in different file formats depending on how they were collected and analyzed. Some data formats are optimal for long-term preservation of data. The UK Data Archive provides a list of </span><a href=\"https://www.ukdataservice.ac.uk/manage-data/format/recommended-formats\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">recommended formats</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> for various types of data. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Digital information may be lost while converting files from one format to another (e.g. converting an image from a non-compressed &lsquo;lossless&rsquo; TIFF file to a compressed &lsquo;lossy&rsquo; JPG file), so changes to file formats should be clearly documented.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Identify what steps are needed after your project is completed in order to ensure the data you are choosing to preserve or share is anonymous, error-free, and converted to recommended formats with a minimal risk of data loss. Read more about </span><a href=\"https://www.ukdataservice.ac.uk/manage-data/legal-ethical/anonymisation.aspx\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">anonymization</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> on the UK Data Archive Website.</span></p>"},{"id":404,"question_id":559,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-11-13 17:10:11 UTC","updated_at":"2018-11-13 17:10:11 UTC","text":"6.1 What data will you be sharing and in what form? (e.g. raw, processed, analyzed, final). ","guidance":"<p><strong>Raw data</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> are the data directly obtained from the instrument, simulation or survey.</span></p>\r\n<p><strong>Processed data</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> result from some manipulation of the raw data in order to eliminate errors or outliers, to prepare the data for analysis, to derive new variables, or to de-identify the human participants.</span></p>\r\n<p><strong>Analyzed data</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> are the the results of qualitative, statistical, or mathematical analysis of the processed data. They can be presented as graphs, charts or statistical tables.</span></p>\r\n<p><strong>Final data</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> are processed data that have, if needed, been converted into a preservation-friendly format.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Consider which data may need to be shared in order to meet institutional or funding requirements, and which data may be restricted because of confidentiality/privacy/intellectual property considerations.</span></p>"},{"id":405,"question_id":560,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-11-13 17:12:09 UTC","updated_at":"2018-11-13 17:12:09 UTC","text":"6.2 If the way you store and share data during your research project differs from how you will preserve your data long-term, include a brief description of any resources needed to share your data (equipment, systems, expertise, etc.).","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">It&rsquo;s possible that the data repository you've selected provides long-term preservation but does not meet your needs in terms of short- or medium-term data sharing and access. For instance, you may need exploration and analysis tools that the long-term archive does not provide. &nbsp;In addition, the long-term archive may not provide flexible authenticated-access options. Also consider if the repository supports metadata standards commonly used by researchers in your field.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">In some instances, you may want to use another (or additional) repository or platform to share your dataset. </span></p>"},{"id":406,"question_id":561,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-11-13 17:14:32 UTC","updated_at":"2019-10-28 12:59:37 UTC","text":"6.3 How will you be sharing your data? (e.g. institutional repository, a specialized data archive, informal/on-request \r\nsharing). Include a brief description of any resources needed to share your data (equipment, systems, expertise, etc.).","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Where you share your data depends on the complexity and size of your data. Smaller, low-risk datasets can be shared via institutional or disciplinary repositories. Larger datasets or datasets with more stringent security requirements cannot be easily transferred over the Internet. Read more about sharing data at the </span><a href=\"https://www.ukdataservice.ac.uk/manage-data/plan/how-share.aspx\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">UK Data Archive</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">See section 5.2: </span><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Where will you deposit your data for long-term preservation and access at the end of your research project?</span></em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> This section suggests repositories that allow for both sharing and preservation</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">For help, please contact York University Libraries at yul_rdm@yorku.ca</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">. </span></p>"},{"id":407,"question_id":562,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-11-13 17:15:51 UTC","updated_at":"2019-04-24 10:50:17 UTC","text":"6.4 Please describe whether there will be any restrictions placed on your data when they are made available and who may access them. If data are not openly available, describe the process for gaining access.","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">It may be necessary or desirable to restrict access to your data for a limited time or to a limited number of people, for:</span></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">ethical reasons (privacy and confidentiality)</span></li>\r\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">economic reasons (patents and commercialization)</span></li>\r\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">intellectual property reasons (e.g. ownership of the original dataset on which yours is based)</span></li>\r\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">or to comply with a journal publishing policy.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Strategies to mitigate these issues may include:</span></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><a href=\"https://www.ukdataservice.ac.uk/manage-data/legal-ethical/anonymisation.aspx\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">anonymising or aggregating data</span></a></li>\r\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><a href=\"https://www.ukdataservice.ac.uk/manage-data/legal-ethical/consent-data-sharing\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">gaining participant consent for data sharing</span></a></li>\r\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">gaining permissions to share adapted or modified data</span></li>\r\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">and agreeing to a limited embargo period.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><a href=\"https://dataverse.scholarsportal.info/\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Scholars Portal Dataverse</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> is available to York researchers and can serve preservation needs where file sizes are less than 2 GB. Scholars Portal Dataverse allows researchers to restrict access to datasets in compliance with research ethics guidelines.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">For help, please contact York University Libraries at yul_rdm@yorku.ca</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>"},{"id":408,"question_id":563,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-11-13 17:17:22 UTC","updated_at":"2019-04-24 10:50:45 UTC","text":"6.5 Have you considered what type of end-user license to include with your data?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Licenses determine what uses can be made of your data. Funding agencies and/or data repositories may have end-user license requirements in place; if not, they may still be able to guide you in the development of a license. Once created, please consider including a copy of your end-user license with your Data Management Plan. Note that only the intellectual property rights holder(s) can issue a license, so it is crucial to clarify who owns those rights.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">There are several types of standard licenses available to researchers, such as the </span><a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/choose/\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Creative Commons licenses</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> and the </span><a href=\"http://opendatacommons.org/licenses/\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Open Data Commons licenses</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">. In fact, for most datasets it is easier to use a standard license rather than to devise a custom-made one. Note that even if you choose to make your data part of the public domain, it is preferable to make this explicit by using a license such as Creative Commons' CC0.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Read more about </span><a href=\"https://www.library.yorku.ca/web/open/overview/data-licensing/\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">data licensing</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">For help, please contact York University Libraries at yul_rdm@yorku.ca</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>"},{"id":409,"question_id":564,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-11-13 17:18:40 UTC","updated_at":"2019-04-24 10:51:34 UTC","text":"6.6 What steps will be taken to help the research community know that your data exists?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Possibilities include: data registries, repositories, indexes, word-of-mouth, publications.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">How will the data be accessed (Web service, ftp, etc.)? If possible, choose a repository that will assign a persistent identifier (such as a DOI) to your dataset. This will ensure a stable access to the dataset and make it retrievable by various discovery tools.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">One of the best ways to refer other researchers to your deposited datasets is to cite them the same way you cite other types of publications (articles, books, proceedings). The Digital Curation Centre provides a detailed </span><a href=\"http://www.dcc.ac.uk/resources/how-guides/cite-datasets\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">guide</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> on data citation, as does the </span><a href=\"https://www.datacite.org/\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">DataCite</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> website. Note that some data repositories also create links from datasets to their associated papers, thus increasing the visibility of the publications.</span></p>\r\n<p><a href=\"https://dataverse.scholarsportal.info/\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Scholars Portal Dataverse</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> and the </span><a href=\"https://www.frdr.ca/repo/\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Federated Research Data Repository (FRDR)</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> are available to York researchers and can assign a persistent identifier (DOI) for your dataset.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">For assistance in making your dataset visible and easily accessible, please contact York University Libraries at yul_rdm@yorku.ca</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>"},{"id":410,"question_id":565,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-11-13 17:21:34 UTC","updated_at":"2018-11-13 17:21:34 UTC","text":"7.1 Identify who will be responsible for managing this project's data during and after the project and the major data management tasks for which they will be responsible.","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Your data management plan has identified important data activities in your project. Identify who will be responsible -- individuals or organizations -- for carrying out these parts of your data management plan. This could also include the time frame associated with these staff responsibilities and any training needed to prepare staff for these duties.</span></p>"},{"id":411,"question_id":566,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-11-13 17:22:35 UTC","updated_at":"2018-11-13 17:22:35 UTC","text":"7.2 How will responsibilities for managing data activities be handled if substantive changes happen in the personnel overseeing the project's data, including a change of Principal Investigator?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Indicate a succession strategy for these data in the event that one or more people responsible for the data leaves (e.g. a graduate student leaving after graduation). Describe the process to be followed in the event that the Principal Investigator leaves the project. In some instances, a co-investigator or the department or division overseeing this research will assume responsibility.</span></p>"},{"id":412,"question_id":567,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-11-13 17:24:26 UTC","updated_at":"2018-11-15 21:06:32 UTC","text":"7.3 What resources will you require to implement your data management plan? What do you estimate the overall cost for data management to be?\r\n\r\nWhat additional resources will you require to implement your data management plan?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">This estimate should incorporate data management costs incurred during the project as well as those required for the longer-term support for the data after the project is finished. Items to consider in the latter category of expenses include the costs of curating and providing long-term access to the data. Some funding agencies state explicitly the support that they will provide to meet the </span><a href=\"https://www.ukdataservice.ac.uk/manage-data/plan/costing\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">cost of preparing data for deposit</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">. This might include technical aspects of data management, training requirements, file storage &amp; backup, and contributions of non-project staff. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">More information about estimating cost for data management is available through the UK Data Archive via their </span><a href=\"https://data-archive.ac.uk/media/247429/costingtool.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Data Management Costing Tool</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">. This information should be incorporated into any grant applications for your project. </span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>"},{"id":413,"question_id":568,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-11-13 18:33:53 UTC","updated_at":"2018-11-13 18:33:53 UTC","text":"8.1 If your research project includes sensitive data, how will you ensure that it is securely managed and accessible only to approved members of the project?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Consider where, how, and to whom sensitive data with acknowledged long-term value should be made available, and how long it should be archived. These decisions should align with </span><a href=\"http://research.info.yorku.ca/research-ethics/\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Research Ethics Board</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> requirements. The methods used to share data will be dependent on a number of factors such as the type, size, complexity and degree of sensitivity of data. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">If researchers seek to share openly de-identified data emerging from their research, it is crucial that consent be secured from participants during the informed consent process. Contact the </span><a href=\"http://research.info.yorku.ca/research-ethics/\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Office of Research Ethics</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> for further details. Further details can be found on </span><a href=\"https://yulink-new.yorku.ca/group/yulink/research-ethics\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">YULink</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Restrictions can be imposed by limiting physical access to storage devices, by placing data on computers that do not have external network access (i.e. access to the Internet), through password protection, and by encrypting files. Sensitive data should never be shared via email or cloud storage services such as Dropbox.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Outline problems anticipated in sharing data, along with causes and possible measures to mitigate these. Problems may include confidentiality, lack of consent agreements, or concerns about Intellectual Property Rights, among others. In some instances, an embargo period may be justified; these may be defined by a funding agency's policy on research data. (Reused from: DCC. (2013). Checklist for a Data Management Plan. v.4.0. Edinburgh: Digital Curation Centre)</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Check out the York University&rsquo;s </span><a href=\"https://research.info.yorku.ca/data-security-guideline-research-involving-human-participants/\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Data Security Guideline for Research Involving Human Participants</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">. </span></p>"},{"id":414,"question_id":569,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-11-13 18:35:48 UTC","updated_at":"2019-10-28 13:00:41 UTC","text":"8.2 If applicable, what strategies will you undertake to address secondary uses of sensitive data?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Obtaining the appropriate consent from research participants is an important step in assuring</span> <a href=\"http://research.info.yorku.ca/research-ethics/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Research Ethics Boards</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> that the data may be shared with researchers outside your project. The consent statement may identify certain conditions clarifying the uses of the data by other researchers. For example, it may stipulate that the data will only be shared for non-profit research purposes or that the data will not be linked with personally identified data from other sources.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Read more about data security: </span><a href=\"https://www.ukdataservice.ac.uk/manage-data/store.aspx\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">UK Data Archive</span></a></p>"},{"id":415,"question_id":570,"locale":"en","created_at":"2018-11-13 18:38:30 UTC","updated_at":"2018-11-13 18:38:30 UTC","text":"8.3 How will you manage legal, ethical, and intellectual property issues?","guidance":"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Compliance with privacy legislation and laws that may impose content restrictions in the data should be discussed with your </span><a href=\"http://ipo.info.yorku.ca/\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">institution's privacy officer</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> or </span><a href=\"http://research.info.yorku.ca/research-services/\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">research services office</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">. </span><a href=\"http://research.info.yorku.ca/research-ethics/\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Research Ethics Boards</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> are central to the research process.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Include here a description concerning ownership, licensing, and intellectual property rights of the data. Terms of reuse must be clearly stated, in line with the relevant legal and ethical requirements where applicable (e.g., subject consent, permissions, restrictions, etc.).</span></p>"},{"id":416,"question_id":571,"locale":"en","created_at":"2019-01-09 04:10:30 UTC","updated_at":"2019-01-09 04:10:30 UTC","text":"Project Title","guidance":""},{"id":417,"question_id":572,"locale":"en","created_at":"2019-01-09 04:17:44 UTC","updated_at":"2019-01-09 04:17:44 UTC","text":"List of Expected Data to be collected:","guidance":""},{"id":418,"question_id":573,"locale":"en","created_at":"2019-01-16 14:16:24 UTC","updated_at":"2019-01-18 16:16:51 UTC","text":"Quels types de données allez-vous recueillir, créer, lier, acquérir ou enregistrer?","guidance":"<p>Les donn&eacute;es de la recherche, ou donn&eacute;es de recherche, ou donn&eacute;es scientifiques, peuvent &ecirc;tre d&eacute;finies comme l&rsquo;ensemble des informations collect&eacute;es, observ&eacute;es ou cr&eacute;&eacute;es sous une forme num&eacute;rique dans le cadre d&rsquo;un projet de recherche.</p>\r\n<p>On distingue g&eacute;n&eacute;ralement les grandes cat&eacute;gories de donn&eacute;es suivantes&nbsp;:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>donn&eacute;es d&rsquo;observation&nbsp;</strong>: donn&eacute;es d&rsquo;enqu&ecirc;tes, donn&eacute;es de t&eacute;l&eacute;d&eacute;tection, donn&eacute;es d&rsquo;&eacute;chantillonnage, enregistrements sur le terrain, images num&eacute;riques en microscopie&hellip;donn&eacute;es exp&eacute;rimentales&nbsp;: s&eacute;quences de g&egrave;nes, chromatogrammes, r&eacute;sultats d&rsquo;essais agronomiques, de s&eacute;lection v&eacute;g&eacute;tale ou animale&hellip;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>mod&egrave;les et simulations&nbsp;</strong>: mod&egrave;les climatiques, mod&egrave;les &eacute;conomiques, mod&egrave;les de croissance des plantes, mod&egrave;les de production agricole, mod&egrave;les multi-agents de gestion des ressources renouvelables, mod&egrave;les d&rsquo;accompagnement ou <em>companion modelling</em>&hellip;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>donn&eacute;es d&eacute;riv&eacute;es ou compil&eacute;es</strong>&nbsp;: bases de donn&eacute;es issues de la compilation d&rsquo;un ensemble de donn&eacute;es collect&eacute;es et/ou cr&eacute;&eacute;es, r&eacute;sultats de fouille de texte (<em>text mining</em>) ou de fouille de donn&eacute;es (<em>data mining</em>).</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Deboin, M.C. 2017. S'initier en ligne aux donn&eacute;es de la recherche et &agrave; leur gestion, en 4 points. Montpellier (FRA) : CIRAD, 5 p.<br /><a href=\"http://url.cirad.fr/ist/initiation-donnees-recherche\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"color: #0066cc;\">http://url.cirad.fr/ist/initiation-donnees-recherche</span></a></p>"},{"id":419,"question_id":574,"locale":"en","created_at":"2019-01-16 14:20:40 UTC","updated_at":"2019-01-16 14:34:41 UTC","text":"Quels documents seront nécessaires pour que les données soient lues et interprétées correctement dans le futur?","guidance":""},{"id":420,"question_id":575,"locale":"en","created_at":"2019-01-16 14:26:11 UTC","updated_at":"2019-01-18 17:15:29 UTC","text":"Dans quels formats de fichier vos données seront-elles recueillies? Ces formats permettront-ils la réutilisation des données, le partage et l'accès à long terme aux données?","guidance":"<p>Les donn&eacute;es peuvent &ecirc;tre recueillies dans une multitude de formats. Toutefois, afin de pouvoir r&eacute;utiliser les donn&eacute;es &agrave; long terme, il est pr&eacute;f&eacute;rable de les conserver dans un format ouvert (non-propri&eacute;taire) et p&eacute;renne.</p>\r\n<p>Exemple de format&nbsp;:</p>\r\n<p><strong>Donn&eacute;es textuelles</strong>&nbsp;: .txt / .rtf ou / .xml</p>\r\n<p><strong>Donn&eacute;es tabul&eacute;es&nbsp;</strong>: .csv / .tab</p>\r\n<p><strong>Images&nbsp;</strong>: .tif</p>\r\n<p><strong>Vid&eacute;o&nbsp;</strong>: .mp4</p>\r\n<p>Pour la liste compl&egrave;te, veuillez visiter <a href=\"https://www.ukdataservice.ac.uk/manage-data/format/recommended-formats\" target=\"_blank\">https://www.ukdataservice.ac.uk/manage-data/format/recommended-formats</a></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>"},{"id":421,"question_id":576,"locale":"en","created_at":"2019-01-16 14:33:10 UTC","updated_at":"2019-01-16 14:33:10 UTC","text":"Quelles conventions et procédures utiliserez-vous pour structurer et nommer vos fichiers et en contrôler les versions afin de vous aider, ainsi que les utilisateurs potentiels, à mieux comprendre la façon dont vos données sont organisées?","guidance":""},{"id":422,"question_id":577,"locale":"en","created_at":"2019-01-16 14:35:10 UTC","updated_at":"2019-01-16 14:35:10 UTC","text":"Comment vous assurerez-vous de documenter le projet de façon systématique tout au long du processus?","guidance":""},{"id":423,"question_id":578,"locale":"en","created_at":"2019-01-16 14:35:30 UTC","updated_at":"2019-01-16 14:35:30 UTC","text":"Si vous utilisez une norme de métadonnées ou des outils pour documenter et décrire vos données, veuillez les indiquer ici.","guidance":""},{"id":424,"question_id":579,"locale":"en","created_at":"2019-01-16 14:40:29 UTC","updated_at":"2019-01-16 14:40:29 UTC","text":"Quels sont les besoins de stockage anticipés pour votre projet en matière d'espace (en mégaoctets, gigaoctets, téraoctets, etc.) et de durée de stockage?","guidance":""},{"id":425,"question_id":580,"locale":"en","created_at":"2019-01-16 14:40:55 UTC","updated_at":"2019-01-16 14:40:55 UTC","text":"Comment vos données seront-elles stockées et sauvegardées pendant votre projet de recherche et à quel endroit le seront-elles?","guidance":""},{"id":426,"question_id":581,"locale":"en","created_at":"2019-01-16 14:42:48 UTC","updated_at":"2019-01-16 14:42:48 UTC","text":"Où déposerez-vous vos données en vue de l'accès et de la préservation à long terme à la fin de votre projet de recherche?","guidance":""},{"id":427,"question_id":582,"locale":"en","created_at":"2019-01-16 14:43:31 UTC","updated_at":"2019-01-16 14:43:31 UTC","text":"Indiquez comment vous assurerez que vos données sont prêtes pour la conservation. À prendre en considération: formats de fichier appropriés pour la conservation mais qui préservent l'intégrité des données; anonymisation et dépersonnalisation des fichiers, y compris les fichiers de documentation.","guidance":""},{"id":428,"question_id":583,"locale":"en","created_at":"2019-01-16 14:46:44 UTC","updated_at":"2019-01-16 14:46:44 UTC","text":"Identifiez qui sera responsable de la gestion des données de ce projet pendant et après le projet ainsi que les principales tâches associées à ces responsabilités.","guidance":""},{"id":429,"question_id":584,"locale":"en","created_at":"2019-01-16 14:47:24 UTC","updated_at":"2019-01-16 14:47:24 UTC","text":"De quelle façon les responsabilités relatives à la gestion des données seront-elles gérées si des changements importants surviennent au sein du personnel qui supervise les données du projet, y compris un changement de chercheur principal?","guidance":""},{"id":430,"question_id":585,"locale":"en","created_at":"2019-01-16 14:47:53 UTC","updated_at":"2019-01-16 14:47:53 UTC","text":"De quelles ressources aurez-vous besoin pour mettre en œuvre votre plan de gestion des données? À combien évaluez-vous le coût total de la gestion des données?","guidance":""},{"id":431,"question_id":586,"locale":"en","created_at":"2019-01-16 14:49:10 UTC","updated_at":"2019-01-16 14:49:10 UTC","text":"Si votre projet comprend des données sensibles, comment vous assurerez-vous qu'il est géré de manière sécuritaire et que les données sont accessibles uniquement aux membres approuvés du projet?","guidance":""},{"id":432,"question_id":587,"locale":"en","created_at":"2019-01-16 14:49:44 UTC","updated_at":"2019-01-16 14:49:44 UTC","text":"Le cas échéant, quelles stratégies adopterez-vous pour traiter les utilisations secondaires des données sensibles?","guidance":""},{"id":433,"question_id":588,"locale":"en","created_at":"2019-01-16 14:50:08 UTC","updated_at":"2019-01-16 14:50:08 UTC","text":"Comment traiterez-vous les questions d'ordre juridique, éthique et de propriété intellectuelle?","guidance":""},{"id":434,"question_id":589,"locale":"en","created_at":"2019-01-16 14:51:25 UTC","updated_at":"2019-01-16 14:51:25 UTC","text":"Quelles données partagerez-vous et sous quelle forme? (p. ex. données brutes, traitées, analysées, définitives)","guidance":""},{"id":435,"question_id":590,"locale":"en","created_at":"2019-01-16 14:51:50 UTC","updated_at":"2019-01-16 14:51:50 UTC","text":"Avez-vous examiné quel type de licence d'utilisation inclure avec vos données?","guidance":""},{"id":436,"question_id":591,"locale":"en","created_at":"2019-01-16 14:52:19 UTC","updated_at":"2019-01-16 14:52:19 UTC","text":"Quelles mesures seront prises pour faire connaître l'existence de vos données au milieu de la recherche?","guidance":""},{"id":437,"question_id":576,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2019-01-21 14:09:54 UTC","updated_at":"2019-01-21 14:27:20 UTC","text":"Quelles conventions et procédures utiliserez-vous pour structurer et nommer vos fichiers et en contrôler les versions afin de vous aider, ainsi que les utilisateurs potentiels, à mieux comprendre la façon dont vos données sont organisées?","guidance":"<p>Utiliser une convention de nommage vous &eacute;vitera de perdre ou de supprimer des documents ou des fichiers de fa&ccedil;on accidentelle.</p>\r\n<p>Les meilleures pratiques en convention de nommage incluent:</p>\r\n<p>- Choisir des noms de fichiers brefs et significatifs</p>\r\n<p>- &Eacute;viter les espaces, les points et les caract&egrave;res sp&eacute;ciaux (? or &amp; or $)</p>\r\n<p>- Utiliser le trait de soulignement ou le trait d&rsquo;union ( _ ) ou ( - )</p>\r\n<p>- Inclure la version lorsque n&eacute;cessaire (v1, v2)</p>\r\n<p>- Inclure la date dans le nom du document (ex. 2018-10-03_sondage_v1.txt)</p>\r\n<p>Pour plus d'information: <a href=\"https://www.ukdataservice.ac.uk/manage-data/format/organising\" target=\"_blank\">https://www.ukdataservice.ac.uk/manage-data/format/organising</a></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>"},{"id":438,"question_id":574,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2019-01-21 15:01:11 UTC","updated_at":"2019-01-21 15:01:11 UTC","text":"Quels documents seront nécessaires pour que les données soient lues et interprétées correctement dans le futur?","guidance":"<p>La documentation n&eacute;cessaire pour pouvoir interpr&eacute;ter les donn&eacute;es peuvent comprendre&nbsp;:</p>\r\n<p>- D&eacute;tails contextuels entourant la m&eacute;thode de cueillette de donn&eacute;es</p>\r\n<p>- Informations qui permettent de reproduire les r&eacute;sultats de donn&eacute;es d&eacute;riv&eacute;es</p>\r\n<p>- Explications des codes et des variables qui apparaissent dans les fichiers de donn&eacute;es</p>"},{"id":439,"question_id":577,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2019-01-21 16:09:47 UTC","updated_at":"2019-01-21 16:16:24 UTC","text":"Comment vous assurerez-vous de documenter le projet de façon systématique tout au long du processus?","guidance":"<p>Id&eacute;alement, la m&eacute;thode utilis&eacute;e pour documenter le projet et les modifications sera d&eacute;termin&eacute;e avant de d&eacute;marrer le projet. Les r&ocirc;les individuels et les permissions de chacun des membres de votre &eacute;quipe de recherche devrait &eacute;galement faire l&rsquo;objet d&rsquo;une attention particuli&egrave;re et &ecirc;tre officiellement document&eacute;.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>"},{"id":440,"question_id":578,"locale":"fr","created_at":"2019-01-21 16:14:26 UTC","updated_at":"2019-01-21 16:15:33 UTC","text":"Si vous utilisez une norme de métadonnées ou des outils pour documenter et décrire vos données, veuillez les indiquer ici.","guidance":"<p>Les m&eacute;tadonn&eacute;es sont utilis&eacute;es pour d&eacute;crire vos donn&eacute;es. En utilisant une norme de m&eacute;tadonn&eacute;es, vous vous assurerez que celles-ci soient document&eacute;es de fa&ccedil;on structur&eacute;e et qu&rsquo;elles seront interop&eacute;rables, c&rsquo;est-&agrave;-dire interpr&eacute;table par d&rsquo;autres syst&egrave;mes. Vous vous assurez &eacute;galement, en utilisant un sch&eacute;ma de m&eacute;tadonn&eacute;es, que vos donn&eacute;es soient plus facile &agrave; rep&eacute;rer dans les bases de donn&eacute;es.</p>\r\n<p>Pour voir les sch&eacute;mas de m&eacute;tadonn&eacute;es&nbsp;: <a href=\"http://www.dcc.ac.uk/resources/metadata-standards\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.dcc.ac.uk/resources/metadata-standards</a></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>"},{"id":441,"question_id":592,"locale":"en","created_at":"2019-01-25 16:30:03 UTC","updated_at":"2019-01-25 16:30:03 UTC","text":"What types of data will you collect, create, link to, acquire and/or record as part of this project?","guidance":""},{"id":442,"question_id":598,"locale":"en","created_at":"2019-02-04 17:56:18 UTC","updated_at":"2019-02-04 17:56:18 UTC","text":"What types of data will you collect, create, link to, acquire and/or record?","guidance":"<p>Examples: numeric, images, audio, video, text, tabular data, modeling data, spatial data, instrumentation data.</p>"},{"id":443,"question_id":599,"locale":"en","created_at":"2019-02-04 18:10:00 UTC","updated_at":"2019-02-04 18:10:00 UTC","text":"In which file formats will your data be collected? Will these formats allow for data re-use, sharing and long-term access to the data?","guidance":"<p>Proprietary file formats requiring specialized software or hardware to use are not recommended, but may be necessary for certain data collection or analysis methods. Using open file formats or industry-standard formats (e.g. those widely used by a given community) is preferred whenever possible.</p>\r\n<p>Read more about file formats: <a href=\"https://guides.library.mun.ca/c.php?g=502039&amp;p=3433725\" target=\"_blank\">MUN Library</a> or <a href=\"https://www.ukdataservice.ac.uk/manage-data/format/file-formats\" target=\"_blank\">UK Data Archive</a></p>"},{"id":444,"question_id":600,"locale":"en","created_at":"2019-02-04 18:13:28 UTC","updated_at":"2019-02-04 18:13:28 UTC","text":"What conventions and procedures will you use to structure, name and version-control your files to help you and others better understand how your data are organized?","guidance":"<p>It is important to keep track of different copies or versions of files, files held in different formats or locations, and information cross-referenced between files. This process is called 'version control'.</p>\r\n<p>Logical file structures, informative naming conventions, and clear indications of file versions, all contribute to better use of your data during and after your research project. &nbsp;These practices will help ensure that you and your research team are using the appropriate version of your data, and minimize confusion regarding copies on different computers and/or on different media.</p>\r\n<p>Read more about file naming and version control: <a href=\"https://guides.library.mun.ca/c.php?g=502039&amp;p=3433725\" target=\"_blank\">MUN Library</a>, <a href=\"https://www.ukdataservice.ac.uk/manage-data/format/versioning\" target=\"_blank\">UK Data Archive</a> or <a href=\"https://researchdata.library.ubc.ca/plan/organize-your-data/\" target=\"_blank\">UBC Library</a></p>"},{"id":445,"question_id":601,"locale":"en","created_at":"2019-02-04 18:18:23 UTC","updated_at":"2019-02-04 18:18:23 UTC","text":"What documentation will be needed for the data to be read and interpreted correctly in the future?","guidance":"<p>Typically, good documentation includes information about the study, data-level descriptions, and any other contextual information required to make the data usable by other researchers. &nbsp;Other elements you should document, as applicable, include: research methodology used, variable definitions, vocabularies, classification systems, units of measurement, assumptions made, format and file type of the data, a description of the data capture and collection methods, explanation of data coding and analysis performed (including syntax files), and details of who has worked on the project and performed each task, etc.</p>\r\n<p>If you would like help determining what type of documentation you should keep, please contact Librarian <a href=\"mailto:alisonr@mun.ca\" target=\"_blank\">Alison Farrell</a></p>"},{"id":446,"question_id":602,"locale":"en","created_at":"2019-02-04 18:20:52 UTC","updated_at":"2019-02-04 18:20:52 UTC","text":"How will you make sure that documentation is created or captured consistently throughout your project?","guidance":"<p>Consider how you will capture this information and where it will be recorded, ideally in advance of data collection and analysis, to ensure accuracy, consistency, and completeness of the documentation. &nbsp;Often, resources you've already created can contribute to this (e.g. publications, websites, progress reports, etc.). &nbsp;It is useful to consult regularly with members of the research team to capture potential changes in data collection/processing that need to be reflected in the documentation. &nbsp;Individual roles and workflows should include gathering data documentation as a key element.</p>"},{"id":447,"question_id":603,"locale":"en","created_at":"2019-02-04 18:23:44 UTC","updated_at":"2019-02-04 18:24:19 UTC","text":"If you are using a metadata standard and/or tools to document and describe your data, please list here.","guidance":"<p>There are many general and domain-specific metadata standards. &nbsp;Dataset documentation should be provided in one of these standard, machine readable, openly-accessible formats to enable the effective exchange of information between users and systems. &nbsp;These standards are often based on language-independent data formats such as XML, RDF, and JSON. There are many metadata standards based on these formats, including discipline-specific standards.</p>\r\n<p>Read more about metadata standards: <a href=\"http://dcc.ac.uk/resources/metadata-standards\" target=\"_blank\">UK Digital Curation Centre's Disciplinary Metadata</a>.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>For help with choosing a metadata standard, please contact Librarian <a href=\"mailto:jpatterson13@mun.ca\" target=\"_blank\">Jordan Patterson</a></p>"},{"id":448,"question_id":604,"locale":"en","created_at":"2019-02-04 18:40:15 UTC","updated_at":"2019-02-04 18:40:15 UTC","text":"What are the anticipated storage requirements for your project, in terms of storage space (in megabytes, gigabytes, terabytes, etc.) and the length of time you will be storing it?","guidance":"<p>Storage-space estimates should take into account requirements for file versioning, backups, and growth over time.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>If you are collecting data over a long period (e.g. several months or years), your data storage and backup strategy should accommodate data growth. Similarly, a long-term storage plan is necessary if you intend to retain your data after the research project.</p>"},{"id":449,"question_id":605,"locale":"en","created_at":"2019-02-04 18:42:55 UTC","updated_at":"2019-02-04 18:42:55 UTC","text":"How and where will your data be stored and backed up during your research project?","guidance":"<p>The risk of losing data due to human error, natural disasters, or other mishaps can be mitigated by following the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://dataabinitio.com/?p=501\" target=\"_blank\">3-2-1 backup rule</a>:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Have at least three copies of your data.</li>\r\n<li>Store the copies on two different media.</li>\r\n<li>Keep one backup copy offsite</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Data may be stored using optical or magnetic media, which can be removable (e.g. DVD and USB drives), fixed (e.g. desktop or laptop hard drives), or networked (e.g. networked drives or cloud-based servers). Each storage method has benefits and drawbacks that should be considered when determining the most appropriate solution.</p>\r\n<p>Further information on storage and backup practices is available from the <a href=\"https://www.sheffield.ac.uk/library/rdm/safedata\" target=\"_blank\">University of Sheffield Library</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.data-archive.ac.uk/create-manage/storage/back-up\" target=\"_blank\">UK Data Archive</a>.</p>"},{"id":450,"question_id":606,"locale":"en","created_at":"2019-02-12 14:32:40 UTC","updated_at":"2019-02-12 14:32:40 UTC","text":"How will the research team and other collaborators access, modify, and contribute data throughout the project?","guidance":"<p>An ideal solution is one that facilitates co-operation and ensures data security, yet is able to be adopted by users with minimal training. Transmitting data between locations or within research teams can be challenging for data management infrastructure. Relying on email for data transfer is not a robust or secure solution. Third-party commercial file sharing services (such as Google Drive and Dropbox) facilitate file exchange, but they are not necessarily permanent or secure, and are often located outside Canada. Please contact&nbsp;your <a href=\"https://www.library.mun.ca/aboutus/contactus/\" target=\"_blank\">Library</a> to develop the best solution for your research project.</p>"},{"id":451,"question_id":607,"locale":"en","created_at":"2019-02-12 14:36:15 UTC","updated_at":"2019-02-12 14:36:15 UTC","text":"Where will you deposit your data for long-term preservation and access at the end of your research project?","guidance":"<p>The issue of data retention should be considered early in the research lifecycle. Data-retention decisions can be driven by external policies (e.g. funding agencies, journal publishers), or by an understanding of the enduring value of a given set of data. The need to preserve data in the short-term (i.e. for peer-verification purposes) or long-term (for data of lasting value), will influence the choice of data repository or archive. A helpful analogy is to think of creating a 'living will' for the data, that is, a plan describing how future researchers will have continued access to the data.</p>\r\n<p>If you need assistance locating a suitable data repository or archive, please contact librarian,<a href=\"mailto:alisonr@mun.ca\" target=\"_blank\"> Alison Farrell.</a></p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.re3data.org/\" target=\"_blank\">re3data.org</a> is a directory of potential open data repositories. Verify whether or not the data repository will provide a statement agreeing to the terms of deposit outlined in your Data Management Plan.</p>"},{"id":452,"question_id":608,"locale":"en","created_at":"2019-02-12 14:41:55 UTC","updated_at":"2019-02-12 14:41:55 UTC","text":"Indicate how you will ensure your data is preservation ready. Consider preservation-friendly file formats, ensuring file integrity, anonymization and de-identification, inclusion of supporting documentation.","guidance":"<p>Some data formats are optimal for long-term preservation of data. For example, non-proprietary file formats, such as text ('.txt') and comma-separated ('.csv'), are considered preservation-friendly. The <a href=\"https://www.ukdataservice.ac.uk/manage-data/format/recommended-formats.aspx\" target=\"_blank\">UK Data Archive</a> provides a useful table of file formats for various types of data. Keep in mind that preservation-friendly files converted from one format to another may lose information (e.g. converting from an uncompressed TIFF file to a compressed JPG file), so changes to file formats should be documented.</p>\r\n<p>Identify steps required following project completion in order to ensure the data you are choosing to preserve or share is anonymous, error-free, and converted to recommended formats with a minimal risk of data loss.</p>\r\n<p>Read more about anonymization:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://data-archive.ac.uk/create-manage/consent-ethics/anonymisation\" target=\"_blank\">UK Data Archive</a>.</p>"},{"id":453,"question_id":609,"locale":"en","created_at":"2019-02-12 14:44:54 UTC","updated_at":"2019-02-12 14:44:54 UTC","text":"What data will you be sharing and in what form? (e.g. raw, processed, analyzed, final).","guidance":"<p><strong>Raw data</strong> are the data directly obtained from the instrument, simulation or survey.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Processed data</strong> result from some manipulation of the raw data in order to eliminate errors or outliers, to prepare the data for analysis, to derive new variables, or to de-identify the human participants.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Analyzed data</strong> are the results of qualitative, statistical, or mathematical analysis of the processed data. They can be presented as graphs, charts or statistical tables.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Final data</strong> are processed data that have, if needed, been converted into a preservation-friendly format.</p>\r\n<p>Consider which data may need to be shared in order to meet institutional or funding requirements, and which data may be restricted because of confidentiality/privacy/intellectual property considerations.</p>"},{"id":454,"question_id":610,"locale":"en","created_at":"2019-02-12 14:50:24 UTC","updated_at":"2019-02-12 14:50:24 UTC","text":"Have you considered what type of end-user license to include with your data?","guidance":"<p>Licenses determine what uses can be made of your data. Funding agencies and/or data repositories may have end-user license requirements in place; if not, they may still be able to guide you in the development of a license. Once created, please consider including a copy of your end-user license with your Data Management Plan. Note that only the intellectual property rights holder(s) can issue a license, so it is crucial to clarify who owns those rights.</p>\r\n<p>There are several types of standard licenses available to researchers, such as the <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/choose/\" target=\"_blank\">Creative Commons licenses</a> and the <a href=\"http://opendatacommons.org/licenses/\" target=\"_blank\">Open Data Commons licenses</a>. In fact, for most datasets it is easier to use a standard license rather than to devise a custom-made one. Note that even if you choose to make your data part of the public domain, it is preferable to make this explicit by using a license such as Creative Commons' CC0.</p>\r\n<p>Read more about data licensing: <a href=\"http://www.dcc.ac.uk/resources/how-guides/license-research-data\" target=\"_blank\">UK Digital Curation Centre</a>.</p>"},{"id":455,"question_id":611,"locale":"en","created_at":"2019-02-12 14:52:56 UTC","updated_at":"2019-02-12 14:52:56 UTC","text":"What steps will be taken to help the research community know that your data exists?","guidance":"<p>Possibilities include: data registries, repositories, indexes, word-of-mouth, publications.</p>\r\n<p>How will the data be accessed (Web service, ftp, etc.)? If possible, choose a repository that will assign a persistent identifier (such as a DOI) to your dataset. This will ensure a stable access to the dataset and make it retrievable by various discovery tools.</p>\r\n<p>One of the best ways to refer other researchers to your deposited datasets is to cite them the same way you cite other types of publications (articles, books, proceedings). The Digital Curation Centre provides a detailed <a href=\"http://www.dcc.ac.uk/resources/how-guides/cite-datasets\" target=\"_blank\">guide</a> on data citation.Note that some data repositories also create links from datasets to their associated papers, thus increasing the visibility of the publications.</p>\r\n<p>Contact Librarian, <a href=\"mailto:alisonr@mun.ca\" target=\"_blank\">Alison Farrell</a>, for assistance in making your dataset visible and easily accessible.</p>\r\n<p>Reused from NIH. (2009). <a href=\"https://grants.nih.gov/grants/sharing_key_elements_data_sharing_plan.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Key Elements to Consider in Preparing a Data Sharing Plan Under NIH Extramural Support</a>. National Institutes of Health.</p>"},{"id":456,"question_id":612,"locale":"en","created_at":"2019-02-12 15:01:31 UTC","updated_at":"2019-02-12 15:01:31 UTC","text":"Identify who will be responsible for managing this project's data during and after the project and the major data management tasks for which they will be responsible.","guidance":"<p>Your data management plan has identified important data activities in your project. Identify who will be responsible -- individuals or organizations -- for carrying out these parts of your data management plan. This could also include the timeframe associated with these staff responsibilities and any training needed to prepare staff for these duties.</p>"},{"id":457,"question_id":613,"locale":"en","created_at":"2019-02-12 15:02:26 UTC","updated_at":"2019-02-12 15:02:26 UTC","text":"\r\n \r\nHow will responsibilities for managing data activities be handled if substantive changes happen in the personnel overseeing the project's data, including a change of Principal Investigator?","guidance":"<p>Indicate a succession strategy for these data in the event that one or more people responsible for the data leaves&nbsp;(e.g. a graduate student leaving after graduation). Describe the process to be followed in the event that the Principal Investigator leaves the project. In some instances, a co-investigator or the department or division overseeing this research will assume responsibility.</p>"},{"id":458,"question_id":614,"locale":"en","created_at":"2019-02-12 15:03:31 UTC","updated_at":"2019-02-12 15:03:31 UTC","text":"What resources will you require to implement your data management plan? What do you estimate the overall cost for data management to be?","guidance":"<p>This estimate should incorporate data management costs incurred during the project as well as those required for the longer-term support for the data after the project is finished. Items to consider in the latter category of expenses include the costs of curating and providing long-term access to the data. Some funding agencies state&nbsp;explicitly the support that they will provide to meet the cost of preparing data for deposit. This might include technical aspects of data management, training requirements, file storage &amp; backup, and contributions of non-project staff.</p>"},{"id":459,"question_id":615,"locale":"en","created_at":"2019-02-12 15:08:59 UTC","updated_at":"2019-02-12 15:08:59 UTC","text":"If your research project includes sensitive data, how will you ensure that it is securely managed and accessible only to approved members of the project?","guidance":"<p>Consider where, how, and to whom sensitive data with acknowledged long-term value should be made available, and how long it should be archived. These decisions should align with Research Ethics Board requirements. The methods used to share data will be dependent on a number of factors such as the type, size, complexity and degree of sensitivity of data. Outline problems anticipated in sharing data, along with causes and possible measures to mitigate these. Problems may include confidentiality, lack of consent agreements, or concerns about Intellectual Property Rights, among others. In some instances, an embargo period may be justified; these may be defined by a funding agency's policy on research data.</p>\r\n<p>Reused from: DCC. (2013). <a href=\"http://www.dcc.ac.uk/resources/data-management-plans\" target=\"_blank\">Checklist for a Data Management Plan</a>. v.4.0. Edinburgh: Digital Curation Centre</p>\r\n<p>Restrictions can be imposed by limiting physical access to storage devices, by placing data on computers that do not have external network access (i.e. access to the Internet), through password protection, and by encrypting files. Sensitive data should never be shared via email or cloud storage services such as Dropbox</p>"},{"id":460,"question_id":616,"locale":"en","created_at":"2019-02-12 15:11:08 UTC","updated_at":"2019-02-12 15:11:08 UTC","text":"If applicable, what strategies will you undertake to address secondary uses of sensitive data?","guidance":"<p>Obtaining the appropriate consent from research participants is an important step in assuring Research Ethics Boards that the data may be shared with researchers outside your project. The consent statement may identify certain conditions clarifying the uses of the data by other researchers. For example, it may stipulate that the data will only be shared for non-profit research purposes or that the data will not be linked with personally identified data from other sources.</p>\r\n<p>Read more about data security: <a href=\"http://data-archive.ac.uk/create-manage/storage/security\" target=\"_blank\">UK Data Archive</a></p>"},{"id":461,"question_id":617,"locale":"en","created_at":"2019-02-12 15:14:37 UTC","updated_at":"2019-02-12 15:14:37 UTC","text":"How will you manage legal, ethical, and intellectual property issues?","guidance":"<p>Compliance with privacy legislation and laws that may impose content restrictions in the data should be discussed with Memorial's <a href=\"mailto:iap@mun.ca\" target=\"_blank\">privacy officer</a> or research services office. Research Ethics Boards are central to the research process.</p>\r\n<p>Include here a description concerning ownership, licensing, and intellectual property rights of the data. Terms of reuse must be clearly stated, in line with the relevant legal and ethical requirements where applicable (e.g., subject consent, permissions, restrictions, etc.).</p>"},{"id":462,"question_id":659,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-03-26 13:06:11 UTC","updated_at":"2020-03-26 13:06:11 UTC","text":"Project Name","guidance":""},{"id":463,"question_id":660,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-03-26 13:07:30 UTC","updated_at":"2020-03-26 13:07:30 UTC","text":"Principle Investigator/Researcher: (Last name, First names)","guidance":"<p>List your name and the name of your project PIs or supervisors</p>"},{"id":464,"question_id":661,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-03-26 13:08:49 UTC","updated_at":"2020-03-26 15:17:11 UTC","text":"Principal Investigator Profile (ORCID)s: ","guidance":"<p>Please enter your ORCID. If you do not have one, you can get one at <a href=\"https://orcid.org/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">https://orcid.org/</a></p>"},{"id":465,"question_id":662,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-03-26 13:11:05 UTC","updated_at":"2020-03-26 13:11:05 UTC","text":"Project DMP Contact","guidance":""},{"id":466,"question_id":663,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-03-26 13:12:19 UTC","updated_at":"2020-03-26 13:12:19 UTC","text":"Description of project","guidance":"<p>Brief description of your project or thesis; aim for a maximum word limit of 250. This iis the \"elevator pitch\", adn mainly included here for conceptual reference.&nbsp;</p>"},{"id":467,"question_id":664,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-03-26 13:12:58 UTC","updated_at":"2020-03-26 13:12:58 UTC","text":"Institution","guidance":"<p>Add partner organizations as needed</p>"},{"id":468,"question_id":665,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-03-26 13:13:19 UTC","updated_at":"2020-03-26 13:13:19 UTC","text":"Language","guidance":""},{"id":469,"question_id":666,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-03-26 13:13:59 UTC","updated_at":"2020-03-26 13:13:59 UTC","text":"Date of issue: (version)","guidance":"<p>Format yyyy-mm-dd</p>"},{"id":470,"question_id":667,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-03-26 13:21:20 UTC","updated_at":"2020-03-26 14:18:20 UTC","text":"What types of research data will you collect, create, or acquire and modify from external sources for project?","guidance":"<p>Verbal description of the information you will be collecting and analyzing for your project. &nbsp;If you are collecting qualitative or social data, please indicate that here as well.&nbsp;</p>"},{"id":471,"question_id":668,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-03-26 13:31:35 UTC","updated_at":"2020-03-26 14:19:02 UTC","text":"Pertaining to your data inventory (above), what data formats and file types will you use?  You are encouraged to avoid proprietary file types whenever possible.","guidance":"<p>Description of the files types that will hold the information described in the previous question.&nbsp;</p>"},{"id":472,"question_id":669,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-03-26 13:34:39 UTC","updated_at":"2020-03-26 14:23:11 UTC","text":"Identify who will be responsible for managing this project's data during and after the project.  Which major data management tasks will this person or persons be responsible for?","guidance":"<p>See example answer.</p>"},{"id":473,"question_id":670,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-03-26 13:38:59 UTC","updated_at":"2020-03-26 13:38:59 UTC","text":"What resources will you require to implement your data management plan? What do you estimate the overall cost for data management to be?  Is this built into your current project budget?","guidance":"<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">For example, consider if you will need local or cloud storage for your data, and costs associated with that.&nbsp; If you require specialized support or software to manage your data, consider those costs.&nbsp; If your Module already has support in place, please indicate what/who in the space provided here.&nbsp; If this question was addressed in your grant award, you may wish to reference that document.</span></p>"},{"id":474,"question_id":671,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-03-26 13:40:06 UTC","updated_at":"2020-03-26 14:24:06 UTC","text":"Who “owns” or will be responsible for the data generated during the project? Who are the primary authors of research products generating during this project.   If there are changes in personnel overseeing the project’s data (including a change in PI) during the project’s life cycle, what will happen to the data?  ","guidance":"<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">For example, should the PI leave the project, will the data be retained by the broader project personnel at Memorial University?&nbsp; What might that transition look like?&nbsp; Who will adopt responsibility for data cleaning and sharing? &nbsp;</span></p>"},{"id":475,"question_id":672,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-03-26 13:42:28 UTC","updated_at":"2020-03-26 14:24:57 UTC","text":"What conventions and procedures will you use to structure, name and version-control your files to help you and others better understand how your data are organized?","guidance":"<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">If you have a standard file naming convention, please outline it here (with examples).&nbsp; If you&rsquo;d prefer Module E suggest one, please make a note. &nbsp;</span></p>"},{"id":476,"question_id":673,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-03-26 13:43:16 UTC","updated_at":"2020-03-26 15:19:39 UTC","text":"What metadata standard will be employed to describe your data?","guidance":"<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">Ecological Markup Language (EML) standard (<a href=\"https://eml.ecoinformatics.org/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">https://eml.ecoinformatics.org/</a>); Darwin Core (<a href=\"http://rs.tdwg.org/dwc/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">http://rs.tdwg.org/dwc/</a>); ISO 19115 (<a href=\"https://www.iso.org/standard/26020.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">https://www.iso.org/standard/26020.html</a>)</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">If no widely recognized standard, it could be an internal OFI project standard (describe here if so).</span></p>"},{"id":477,"question_id":674,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-03-26 13:57:18 UTC","updated_at":"2020-03-26 14:26:51 UTC","text":"What information and metadata elements will be needed for the data to be read and interpreted correctly in the future?  ","guidance":"<p>Consider telling the reader which programs will read the raw and processed files, or run compiled analytical code.&nbsp; Which metadata fields contain crucial information to reproduce your work accurately?</p>"},{"id":478,"question_id":675,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-03-26 14:28:01 UTC","updated_at":"2020-03-26 14:28:01 UTC","text":"What are the anticipated storage requirements need for your project’s active life cycle, in terms of 1) storage space [# megabytes, gigabytes, terabytes, etc.] and 2) length of time?","guidance":""},{"id":479,"question_id":676,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-03-26 14:28:51 UTC","updated_at":"2020-03-26 14:28:51 UTC","text":"How and where will your data be stored and backed up during the active project life cycle?  Specifically, comment on practices, hardware and software.","guidance":""},{"id":480,"question_id":677,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-03-26 14:29:48 UTC","updated_at":"2020-03-26 14:29:48 UTC","text":"How will the research team and other collaborators access, modify, and contribute data throughout the project life cycle?","guidance":""},{"id":481,"question_id":678,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-03-26 14:30:27 UTC","updated_at":"2020-03-26 14:30:27 UTC","text":"Will you require archiving beyond the length of time stated above?  What will that archive require in terms of storage type, space, and maintenance?","guidance":""},{"id":482,"question_id":679,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-03-26 14:33:13 UTC","updated_at":"2020-03-26 14:33:13 UTC","text":"Are there agreements in place for Intellectual Property (IP) management for this project?  ","guidance":"<p><span class=\"Heading7Char\">Agreements may include stipulations for data sharing, data transfer, or other agreements between researchers and Universities.</span><span lang=\"EN-US\">&nbsp; For more information, contact the Memorial University Information Access &amp; Privacy Office (<a href=\"https://www.mun.ca/iap/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">https://www.mun.ca/iap/</a>). Please specify the agreements.&nbsp;</span></p>"},{"id":483,"question_id":680,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-03-26 14:35:50 UTC","updated_at":"2020-03-26 14:49:16 UTC","text":"Does your study include human information or other sensitive data?  ","guidance":"<p>If no, you may move onto the next section.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>If yes, please complete all questions below.&nbsp;</p>"},{"id":484,"question_id":681,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-03-26 14:50:51 UTC","updated_at":"2020-03-26 14:50:51 UTC","text":"How will sensitive data be managed securely during the active research project life cycle?  Will non-disclosure agreements be required for researchers or participants?","guidance":"<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">Note: you may need to consult with University research data policy and ethics professionals to fully answer this question.&nbsp; As well, you may need to consult with University IT services to identify protocols for storing, working with, and sharing sensitive information securely.</span></p>"},{"id":485,"question_id":682,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-03-26 14:51:32 UTC","updated_at":"2020-03-26 14:51:32 UTC","text":"If any data are to be released publicly, what steps will be taken to ensure anonymization and/or data cleaning?","guidance":"<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">For guidance, please refer to the Memorial University Guide on Research Ethics (<a href=\"https://guides.library.mun.ca/c.php?g=502039&amp;p=5059458\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">https://guides.library.mun.ca/c.php?g=502039&amp;p=5059458</a>)</span></p>"},{"id":486,"question_id":683,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-03-26 14:59:50 UTC","updated_at":"2020-03-26 15:22:24 UTC","text":"Which datasets from this project will be shared publicly?","guidance":"<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">We encourage you to share as much of your data as possible, helping to support FAIR data sharing principles (Findable, Accessible, Interoperable, and Reusable; see e.g., Wilkinson, et al., 2016, DOI: <a href=\"https://www.nature.com/articles/sdata201618\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">10.1038/sdata.2016.18</a>).&nbsp; Remember it is also possible to have data and metadata shared and hosted in different repositories; using multiple metadata repositories or finding a metadata repository that is federated with others are both good practices to encourage broader findability and accessibility.&nbsp; </span></p>"},{"id":487,"question_id":684,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-03-26 15:00:29 UTC","updated_at":"2020-03-26 15:00:29 UTC","text":"When will data from this project be shared?","guidance":"<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">When answering this question, be mindful of the OFI Data Management Principles and Policy, as well as and your own research group&rsquo;s goals.&nbsp;</span></p>"},{"id":488,"question_id":685,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-03-26 15:04:05 UTC","updated_at":"2020-03-26 15:04:05 UTC","text":"What copyright or license should be applied to these datasets?","guidance":"<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">CC BY-NC-SA 4.0</a> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><a href=\"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">CC BY-SA 4.0</a> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><a href=\"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">CC BY 4.0</a> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>"},{"id":489,"question_id":686,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-03-26 15:04:56 UTC","updated_at":"2020-03-26 15:04:56 UTC","text":"To which public data repository/-ies do you intend to submit data?","guidance":"<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">If you need guidance, discuss options with your project&rsquo;s data manager, a University research data librarian, or visit <a href=\"https://www.re3data.org/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">https://www.re3data.org/</a>.&nbsp; Some possible considerations may include: institutional repository, discipline appropriateness, public access, presence/absence of a pay wall, and ability to generate a DOI or ISBN. </span></p>"},{"id":490,"question_id":687,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-03-26 15:05:22 UTC","updated_at":"2020-03-26 15:05:22 UTC","text":"Please list any datasets that will be submitted to CIOOS, and to which regional node (Atlantic, Pacific, St. Lawrence) you intended to submit. ","guidance":""},{"id":491,"question_id":688,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-03-26 15:05:44 UTC","updated_at":"2020-03-26 15:05:44 UTC","text":"What metadata catalog(s) will host your metadata (if different than above)?  ","guidance":""},{"id":492,"question_id":689,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-04-01 14:56:58 UTC","updated_at":"2020-04-01 14:56:58 UTC","text":"What types of research data will you collect, create, or acquire and modify from external sources for project?","guidance":"<p>Written description of the information you will be collecting and analyzing for your project. &nbsp;If you are collecting qualitative or social data, please indicate that here as well.&nbsp;</p>"},{"id":493,"question_id":713,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-04-01 14:58:47 UTC","updated_at":"2020-04-01 14:58:47 UTC","text":"Which datasets from this project will be shared publicly?","guidance":"<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">We encourage you to share as much of your data as possible, helping to support FAIR data sharing principles (Findable, Accessible, Interoperable, and Reusable; see e.g., Wilkinson, et al., 2016, DOI: <a href=\"https://www.nature.com/articles/sdata201618\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">10.1038/sdata.2016.18</a>). &nbsp;</span></p>"},{"id":494,"question_id":716,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-04-01 14:59:30 UTC","updated_at":"2020-04-01 14:59:30 UTC","text":"To which public data repository/-ies do you intend to submit data?","guidance":"<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">Remember it is also possible to have data and metadata shared and hosted in different repositories; using multiple metadata repositories or finding a metadata repository that is federated with others are both good practices to encourage broader findability and accessibility.&nbsp;If you need guidance, discuss options with your project&rsquo;s data manager, a University research data librarian, or visit <a href=\"https://www.re3data.org/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">https://www.re3data.org/</a>.&nbsp; Some possible considerations may include: institutional repository, discipline appropriateness, public access, presence/absence of a pay wall, and ability to generate a DOI or ISBN. </span></p>"},{"id":495,"question_id":714,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-04-01 15:00:06 UTC","updated_at":"2020-04-01 15:00:06 UTC","text":"When will data from this project be shared?","guidance":"<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">When answering this question, be mindful of the OFI Data Management Principles and Policy, as well as your own research group&rsquo;s goals.&nbsp;</span></p>"},{"id":496,"question_id":719,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-04-07 22:16:44 UTC","updated_at":"2020-04-07 22:16:44 UTC","text":"What types of research data will you collect, create, or acquire and modify from external sources for project?","guidance":"<p>Written description of the information you will be collecting and analyzing for your project. &nbsp;If you are collecting qualitative or social data, please indicate that here as well.&nbsp;</p>"},{"id":497,"question_id":720,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-04-07 22:19:29 UTC","updated_at":"2020-04-07 22:19:29 UTC","text":"Pertaining to your data inventory (above), what data formats and file types will you use? You are encouraged to avoid proprietary file types whenever possible.","guidance":"<p>Description of the files types that will hold the information described in the previous question.&nbsp;</p>"},{"id":498,"question_id":721,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-04-07 22:20:37 UTC","updated_at":"2020-04-07 22:20:37 UTC","text":"Identify who will be responsible for managing this project's data during and after the project. Which major data management tasks will this person or persons be responsible for?","guidance":"<p>See example answer.</p>"},{"id":499,"question_id":722,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-04-07 22:21:35 UTC","updated_at":"2020-04-07 22:21:35 UTC","text":"What resources will you require to implement your data management plan? What do you estimate the overall cost for data management to be? Is this built into your current project budget?","guidance":"<p>For example, consider if you will need local or cloud storage for your data, and costs associated with that. If you require specialized support or software to manage your data, consider those costs. If your Module already has support in place, please indicate what/who in the space provided here. If this question was addressed in your grant award, you may wish to reference that document.</p>"},{"id":500,"question_id":723,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-04-07 22:22:46 UTC","updated_at":"2020-04-09 18:23:43 UTC","text":"Who “owns” or will be responsible for the data generated during the project? Who are the primary authors of research products generating during this project. If there are changes in personnel overseeing the project’s data (including a change in PI) during the project’s life cycle, what will happen to the data?","guidance":"<p>For example, should the PI leave the project, will the data be retained by the broader project personnel at Dalhousie University?&nbsp; What might that transition look like?&nbsp; Who will adopt responsibility for data cleaning and sharing? &nbsp;</p>"},{"id":501,"question_id":724,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-04-07 22:24:33 UTC","updated_at":"2020-04-07 22:24:33 UTC","text":"What conventions and procedures will you use to structure, name and version-control your files to help you and others better understand how your data are organized?","guidance":"<p>If you have a standard file naming convention, please outline it here (with examples).&nbsp; If you&rsquo;d prefer Module E suggest one, please make a note. &nbsp;</p>"},{"id":502,"question_id":725,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-04-07 22:25:18 UTC","updated_at":"2020-04-09 18:24:15 UTC","text":"What metadata standard will be employed to describe your data?","guidance":"<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">Ecological Markup Language (EML) standard (<a href=\"https://eml.ecoinformatics.org/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">https://eml.ecoinformatics.org/</a>); Darwin Core (<a href=\"http://rs.tdwg.org/dwc/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">http://rs.tdwg.org/dwc/</a>); ISO 19115 (<a href=\"https://www.iso.org/standard/26020.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">https://www.iso.org/standard/26020.html</a>)</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-US\">If no widely recognized standard, it could be an internal OFI project standard (describe here if so).</span></p>"},{"id":503,"question_id":726,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-04-07 22:25:57 UTC","updated_at":"2020-04-07 22:25:57 UTC","text":"What information and metadata elements will be needed for the data to be read and interpreted correctly in the future?","guidance":"<p>Consider telling the reader which programs will read the raw and processed files, or run compiled analytical code.&nbsp; Which metadata fields contain crucial information to reproduce your work accurately?</p>"},{"id":504,"question_id":727,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-04-07 22:26:59 UTC","updated_at":"2020-04-07 22:26:59 UTC","text":"What are the anticipated storage requirements need for your project’s active life cycle, in terms of 1) storage space [# megabytes, gigabytes, terabytes, etc.] and 2) length of time?","guidance":""},{"id":505,"question_id":728,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-04-07 22:28:57 UTC","updated_at":"2020-04-07 22:28:57 UTC","text":"How and where will your data be stored and backed up during the active project life cycle? Specifically, comment on practices, hardware and software.","guidance":""},{"id":506,"question_id":729,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-04-07 22:31:08 UTC","updated_at":"2020-04-07 22:31:08 UTC","text":"How will the research team and other collaborators access, modify, and contribute data throughout the project life cycle?","guidance":""},{"id":507,"question_id":730,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-04-07 22:32:06 UTC","updated_at":"2020-04-07 22:32:06 UTC","text":"Will you require archiving beyond the length of time stated above? What will that archive require in terms of storage type, space, and maintenance?","guidance":""},{"id":508,"question_id":731,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-04-07 22:34:59 UTC","updated_at":"2020-04-07 22:35:36 UTC","text":"Are there agreements in place for Intellectual Property (IP) management for this project?","guidance":"<p><span class=\"Heading7Char\">Agreements may include stipulations for data sharing, data transfer, or other agreements between researchers and Universities.</span><span lang=\"EN-US\">&nbsp; For more information, contact the Office of Research Services at Dalhousie University <a href=\"https://www.dal.ca/dept/research-services.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">https://www.dal.ca/dept/research-services.html</a>). Please specify the agreements.&nbsp;</span></p>"},{"id":509,"question_id":732,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-04-07 22:36:05 UTC","updated_at":"2020-04-07 22:36:05 UTC","text":"Does your study include human information or other sensitive data?","guidance":"<p>If no, you may move onto the next section.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>If yes, please complete all questions below.&nbsp;</p>"},{"id":510,"question_id":733,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-04-07 22:37:22 UTC","updated_at":"2020-04-09 18:33:57 UTC","text":"How will sensitive data be managed securely during the active research project life cycle? Will non-disclosure agreements be required for researchers or participants?","guidance":"<p>Note: you may need to consult with University research data and ethics professionals to fully answer this question.&nbsp; As well, you may need to consult with Dalhousie University's Office of Research Services (ORS) and Information Technology Services (ITS) to identify protocols for storing, working with, and sharing sensitive information securely.</p>"},{"id":511,"question_id":734,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-04-07 22:39:49 UTC","updated_at":"2020-04-09 18:41:19 UTC","text":"If any data are to be released publicly, what steps will be taken to ensure anonymization and/or data cleaning?","guidance":"<p>For guidance, please refer to the Dalhousie University Research Ethics resources: <a href=\"https://www.dal.ca/dept/research-services/responsible-conduct-/research-ethics-.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">https://www.dal.ca/dept/research-services/responsible-conduct-/research-ethics-.html</a> An additional resource is here: <a href=\"https://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/content/deposit/guide/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">https://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/content/deposit/guide/</a>&nbsp;</p>"},{"id":512,"question_id":735,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-04-07 22:40:52 UTC","updated_at":"2020-04-07 22:40:52 UTC","text":"Which datasets from this project will be shared publicly?","guidance":"<p>We encourage you to share as much of your data as possible, helping to support FAIR data sharing principles (Findable, Accessible, Interoperable, and Reusable; see e.g., Wilkinson, et al., 2016, DOI:&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.nature.com/articles/sdata201618\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">10.1038/sdata.2016.18</a>).</p>"},{"id":513,"question_id":736,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-04-07 22:41:19 UTC","updated_at":"2020-04-07 22:41:19 UTC","text":"When will data from this project be shared?","guidance":"<p>When answering this question, be mindful of the OFI Data Management Principles and Policy, as well as your own research group&rsquo;s goals.&nbsp;</p>"},{"id":514,"question_id":737,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-04-07 22:44:26 UTC","updated_at":"2020-04-07 22:44:26 UTC","text":"What copyright or license should be applied to these datasets?\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nNote","guidance":"<p>CC BY-NC-SA 4.0 <br />CC BY-SA 4.0 <br />CC BY 4.0</p>"},{"id":515,"question_id":738,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-04-07 22:45:36 UTC","updated_at":"2020-04-07 22:45:36 UTC","text":"To which public data repository/-ies do you intend to submit data?","guidance":"<p>Remember it is also possible to have data and metadata shared and hosted in different repositories; using multiple metadata repositories or finding a metadata repository that is federated with others are both good practices to encourage broader findability and accessibility. If you need guidance, discuss options with your project&rsquo;s data manager, a University Research Data Librarian, or visit <a href=\"https://www.re3data.org/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">https://www.re3data.org/</a>.&nbsp; Some possible considerations may include: institutional repository, discipline appropriateness, public access, presence/absence of a pay wall, and ability to generate a DOI or ISBN.</p>"},{"id":516,"question_id":739,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-04-07 22:46:03 UTC","updated_at":"2020-04-07 22:46:03 UTC","text":"Please list any datasets that will be submitted to CIOOS, and to which regional node (Atlantic, Pacific, St. Lawrence) you intended to submit.","guidance":""},{"id":517,"question_id":740,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-04-07 22:46:28 UTC","updated_at":"2020-04-07 22:46:28 UTC","text":"What metadata catalog(s) will host your metadata (if different than above)?","guidance":""},{"id":518,"question_id":741,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-04-08 15:43:01 UTC","updated_at":"2020-04-08 15:43:01 UTC","text":"What types of data will you collect, create, link to, acquire and/or record?","guidance":"<p>Examples: numeric, images, audio, video, text, tabular data, modeling data, spatial data, instrumentation data.</p>"},{"id":519,"question_id":742,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-04-08 15:43:44 UTC","updated_at":"2020-04-09 12:43:26 UTC","text":"What file formats will your data be collected in? Will these formats allow for data re-use, sharing and long-term access to the data?","guidance":"<p>Proprietary file formats requiring specialized software or hardware to use are not recommended, but may be necessary for certain data collection or analysis methods. Using open file formats or industry-standard formats (e.g. those widely used by a given community) is preferred whenever possible.</p>\r\n<p>Read more about file formats:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://researchdata.library.ubc.ca/plan/format-your-data/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">UBC Library</a> or UK Data Service <a href=\"https://www.ukdataservice.ac.uk/manage-data/format/file-formats.aspx\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">here</a> and <a href=\"https://www.ukdataservice.ac.uk/manage-data/format/recommended-formats.aspx\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">here</a>.&nbsp;</p>"},{"id":520,"question_id":743,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-04-08 15:44:16 UTC","updated_at":"2020-04-09 12:39:52 UTC","text":"What conventions and procedures will you use to structure, name and version-control your files to help you and others better understand how your data are organized?","guidance":"<p>It is important to keep track of different copies or versions of files, files held in different formats or locations, and information cross-referenced between files. This process is called 'version control'.</p>\r\n<p>Logical file structures, informative naming conventions, and clear indications of file versions, all contribute to better use of your data during and after your research project. &nbsp;These practices will help ensure that you and your research team are using the appropriate version of your data, and minimize confusion regarding copies on different computers and/or on different media.</p>\r\n<p>Read more about file naming and version control:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://researchdata.library.ubc.ca/plan/organize-your-data/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">UBC Library</a>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.ukdataservice.ac.uk/manage-data/format/versioning.aspx\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">UK Data Service</a>.</p>"},{"id":521,"question_id":744,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-04-08 15:45:12 UTC","updated_at":"2020-04-08 15:45:12 UTC","text":"What documentation will be needed for the data to be read and interpreted correctly in the future?","guidance":"<p>Typically, good documentation includes information about the study, data-level descriptions, and any other contextual information required to make the data usable by other researchers. &nbsp;Other elements you should document, as applicable, include: research methodology used, variable definitions, vocabularies, classification systems, units of measurement, assumptions made, format and file type of the data, a description of the data capture and collection methods, explanation of data coding and analysis performed (including syntax files), and details of who has worked on the project and performed each task, etc.</p>"},{"id":522,"question_id":745,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-04-08 15:45:44 UTC","updated_at":"2020-04-08 15:45:44 UTC","text":"How will you make sure that documentation is created or captured consistently throughout your project?","guidance":"<p>Consider how you will capture this information and where it will be recorded, ideally in advance of data collection and analysis, to ensure accuracy, consistency, and completeness of the documentation. &nbsp;Often, resources you've already created can contribute to this (e.g. publications, websites, progress reports, etc.). &nbsp;It is useful to consult regularly with members of the research team to capture potential changes in data collection/processing that need to be reflected in the documentation. &nbsp;Individual roles and workflows should include gathering data documentation as a key element.</p>"},{"id":523,"question_id":746,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-04-08 15:46:19 UTC","updated_at":"2020-04-08 15:46:19 UTC","text":"If you are using a metadata standard and/or tools to document and describe your data, please list here.","guidance":"<p>There are many general and domain-specific metadata standards. &nbsp;Dataset documentation should be provided in one of these standard, machine readable, openly-accessible formats to enable the effective exchange of information between users and systems. &nbsp;These standards are often based on language-independent data formats such as XML, RDF, and JSON. There are many metadata standards based on these formats, including discipline-specific standards.</p>\r\n<p>Read more about metadata standards:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://dcc.ac.uk/resources/metadata-standards\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">UK Digital Curation Centre's Disciplinary Metadata</a>.&nbsp;</p>"},{"id":524,"question_id":747,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-04-08 15:47:48 UTC","updated_at":"2020-04-08 15:47:48 UTC","text":"What are the anticipated storage requirements for your project, in terms of storage space (in megabytes, gigabytes, terabytes, etc.) and the length of time you will be storing it?","guidance":"<p>Storage-space estimates should take into account requirements for file versioning, backups, and growth over time.&nbsp;If you are collecting data over a long period (e.g. several months or years), your data storage and backup strategy should accommodate data growth. Similarly, a long-term storage plan is necessary if you intend to retain your data after the research project.</p>"},{"id":525,"question_id":748,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-04-08 15:48:16 UTC","updated_at":"2020-04-09 16:09:26 UTC","text":"How and where will your data be stored and backed up during your research project?","guidance":"<p>The risk of losing data due to human error, natural disasters, or other mishaps can be mitigated by following the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://dataabinitio.com/?p=501\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">3-2-1 backup rule</a>:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Have at least three copies of your data.</li>\r\n<li>Store the copies on two different media.</li>\r\n<li>Keep one backup copy offsite</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Data may be stored using optical or magnetic media, which can be removable (e.g. DVD and USB drives), fixed (e.g. desktop or laptop hard drives), or networked (e.g. networked drives or cloud-based servers). Each storage method has benefits and drawbacks that should be considered when determining the most appropriate solution.</p>\r\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://www.dal.ca/dept/its/current.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Information Technology Services (ITS)</a> </strong>has information on file sharing and storage resources at Dalhousie University. Further information on storage and backup practices is available from the <a href=\"https://www.ukdataservice.ac.uk/manage-data/store.aspx\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">UK Data Service</a>.</p>"},{"id":526,"question_id":749,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-04-08 15:48:47 UTC","updated_at":"2020-04-09 16:13:11 UTC","text":"How will the research team and other collaborators access, modify, and contribute data throughout the project?","guidance":"<p>An ideal solution is one that facilitates co-operation and ensures data security, yet is able to be adopted by users with minimal training. Transmitting data between locations or within research teams can be challenging for data management infrastructure. Relying on email for data transfer is not a robust or secure solution. Third-party commercial file sharing services (such as Google Drive and Dropbox) facilitate file exchange, but they are not necessarily permanent or secure, and are often located outside Canada. Please contact your Library to develop the best solution for your research project.</p>\r\n<p>Dalhousie University also has resources.&nbsp; <strong><a href=\"https://www.dal.ca/dept/its/current.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Information Technology Services (ITS)</a>&nbsp;</strong>has information on file sharing and storage The Office of Research Services (ORS) has information on <strong><a href=\"https://www.dal.ca/dept/research-services/responsible-conduct-/research-ethics-/resources-.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Protecting Electronically Stored Personally Identifiable Research Data.&nbsp;</a></strong></p>"},{"id":527,"question_id":750,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-04-08 15:49:58 UTC","updated_at":"2020-04-09 16:27:46 UTC","text":"Where will you deposit your data for long-term preservation and access at the end of your research project?","guidance":"<p>The issue of data retention should be considered early in the research lifecycle. Data-retention decisions can be driven by external policies (e.g. funding agencies, journal publishers), or by an understanding of the enduring value of a given set of data. The need to preserve data in the short-term (i.e. for peer-verification purposes) or long-term (for data of lasting value), will influence the choice of data repository or archive. A helpful analogy is to think of creating a 'living will' for the data, that is, a plan describing how future researchers will have continued access to the data.</p>\r\n<p>If you need assistance locating a suitable data repository or archive, please contact the <a href=\"mailto:data.management@dal.ca\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">RDM Team</a> at the Dalhousie Libraries. The Dalhousie Libraries has an institutional Dataverse available at <a href=\"https://dataverse.scholarsportal.info/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Scholars Portal.</a> In addition, <a href=\"https://portagenetwork.ca/planning-managing-data/research-data-repositories/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">The Portage Network</a> also has a good overview of potential repositories.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.re3data.org/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">re3data.org</a> is a directory of potential open data repositories. Verify whether or not the data repository will provide a statement agreeing to the terms of deposit outlined in your Data Management Plan.&nbsp;</p>"},{"id":528,"question_id":751,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-04-08 15:50:24 UTC","updated_at":"2020-04-09 16:26:57 UTC","text":"Indicate how you will ensure your data is preservation ready. Consider preservation-friendly file formats, ensuring file integrity, anonymization and de-identification, inclusion of supporting documentation.","guidance":"<p>Some data formats are optimal for long-term preservation of data. For example, non-proprietary file formats, such as text ('.txt') and comma-separated ('.csv'), are considered preservation-friendly. The UK Data Archive provides a useful table of file formats for various types of data. Keep in mind that preservation-friendly files converted from one format to another may lose information (e.g. converting from an uncompressed TIFF file to a compressed JPG file), so changes to file formats should be documented.</p>\r\n<p>Identify steps required following project completion in order to ensure the data you are choosing to preserve or share is anonymous, error-free, and converted to recommended formats with a minimal risk of data loss.</p>\r\n<p>Read more about anonymization:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://researchdata.library.ubc.ca/plan/format-your-data/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">UBC Library</a>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.ukdataservice.ac.uk/manage-data/legal-ethical/anonymisation.aspx\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">UK Data Service</a>.</p>"},{"id":529,"question_id":752,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-04-08 17:36:29 UTC","updated_at":"2020-04-08 17:36:29 UTC","text":"What data will you be sharing and in what form? (e.g. raw, processed, analyzed, final).","guidance":"<p><strong>Raw data</strong>&nbsp;are the data directly obtained from the instrument, simulation or survey.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Processed data</strong>&nbsp;result from some manipulation of the raw data in order to eliminate errors or outliers, to prepare the data for analysis, to derive new variables, or to de-identify the human participants.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Analyzed data</strong>&nbsp;are the the results of qualitative, statistical, or mathematical analysis of the processed data. They can be presented as graphs, charts or statistical tables.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Final data</strong>&nbsp;are processed data that have, if needed, been converted into a preservation-friendly format.</p>\r\n<p>Consider which data may need to be shared in order to meet institutional or funding requirements, and which data may be restricted because of confidentiality/privacy/intellectual property considerations.</p>"},{"id":530,"question_id":753,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-04-08 17:37:12 UTC","updated_at":"2020-04-08 17:37:12 UTC","text":"Have you considered what type of end-user license to include with your data?","guidance":"<p>Licenses determine what uses can be made of your data. Funding agencies and/or data repositories may have end-user license requirements in place; if not, they may still be able to guide you in the development of a license. Once created, please consider including a copy of your end-user license with your Data Management Plan. Note that only the intellectual property rights holder(s) can issue a license, so it is crucial to clarify who owns those rights.</p>\r\n<p>There are several types of standard licenses available to researchers, such as the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/choose/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Creative Commons licenses</a>&nbsp;and the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://opendatacommons.org/licenses/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Open Data Commons licenses</a>. In fact, for most datasets it is easier to use a standard license rather than to devise a custom-made one. Note that even if you choose to make your data part of the public domain, it is preferable to make this explicit by using a license such as Creative Commons' CC0.</p>\r\n<p>Read more about data licensing:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.dcc.ac.uk/resources/how-guides/license-research-data\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">UK Digital Curation Centre</a>.</p>"},{"id":531,"question_id":754,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-04-08 17:37:47 UTC","updated_at":"2020-04-08 17:37:47 UTC","text":"What steps will be taken to help the research community know that your data exists?","guidance":"<p>Possibilities include: data registries, repositories, indexes, word-of-mouth, publications.</p>\r\n<p>How will the data be accessed (Web service, ftp, etc.)? If possible, choose a repository that will assign a persistent identifier (such as a DOI) to your dataset. This will ensure a stable access to the dataset and make it retrievable by various discovery tools.</p>\r\n<p>One of the best ways to refer other researchers to your deposited datasets is to cite them the same way you cite other types of publications (articles, books, proceedings). The Digital Curation Centre provides a detailed&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.dcc.ac.uk/resources/how-guides/cite-datasets\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">guide</a>&nbsp;on data citation.Note that some data repositories also create links from datasets to their associated papers, thus increasing the visibility of the publications.</p>\r\n<p>Contact your Library for assistance in making your dataset visible and easily accessible.</p>\r\n<p>Reused from NIH. (2009).&nbsp;<a href=\"https://grants.nih.gov/grants/sharing_key_elements_data_sharing_plan.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Key Elements to Consider in Preparing a Data Sharing Plan Under NIH Extramural Support</a>. National Institutes of Health.</p>"},{"id":532,"question_id":755,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-04-08 17:39:29 UTC","updated_at":"2020-04-08 17:39:29 UTC","text":"Identify who will be responsible for managing this project's data during and after the project and the major data management tasks for which they will be responsible.","guidance":"<p>Your data management plan has identified important data activities in your project. Identify who will be responsible -- individuals or organizations -- for carrying out these parts of your data management plan. This could also include the timeframe associated with these staff responsibilities and any training needed to prepare staff for these duties.</p>"},{"id":533,"question_id":756,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-04-08 17:40:08 UTC","updated_at":"2020-04-08 17:40:08 UTC","text":"How will responsibilities for managing data activities be handled if substantive changes happen in the personnel overseeing the project's data, including a change of Principal Investigator?","guidance":"<p>Indicate a succession strategy for these data in the event that one or more people responsible for the data leaves&nbsp;(e.g. a graduate student leaving after graduation). Describe the process to be followed in the event that the Principal Investigator leaves the project. In some instances, a co-investigator or the department or division overseeing this research will assume responsibility.</p>"},{"id":534,"question_id":757,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-04-08 17:40:34 UTC","updated_at":"2020-04-08 17:40:34 UTC","text":"What resources will you require to implement your data management plan? What do you estimate the overall cost for data management to be?","guidance":"<p>This estimate should incorporate data management costs incurred during the project as well as those required for the longer-term support for the data after the project is finished. Items to consider in the latter category of expenses include the costs of curating and providing long-term access to the data. Some funding agencies state&nbsp;explicitly the support that they will provide to meet the cost of preparing data for deposit. This might include technical aspects of data management, training requirements, file storage &amp; backup, and contributions of non-project staff.</p>"},{"id":535,"question_id":758,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-04-08 17:41:50 UTC","updated_at":"2020-04-08 17:41:50 UTC","text":"If your research project includes sensitive data, how will you ensure that it is securely managed and accessible only to approved members of the project?","guidance":"<p>Consider where, how, and to whom sensitive data with acknowledged long-term value should be made available, and how long it should be archived. These decisions should align with Research Ethics Board requirements. The methods used to share data will be dependent on a number of factors such as the type, size, complexity and degree of sensitivity of data. Outline problems anticipated in sharing data, along with causes and possible measures to mitigate these. Problems may include confidentiality, lack of consent agreements, or concerns about Intellectual Property Rights, among others. In some instances, an embargo period may be justified; these may be defined by a funding agency's policy on research data.</p>\r\n<p>Reused from: DCC. (2013).&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.dcc.ac.uk/resources/data-management-plans\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Checklist for a Data Management Plan</a>. v.4.0. Edinburgh: Digital Curation Centre</p>\r\n<p>Restrictions can be imposed by limiting physical access to storage devices, by placing data on computers that do not have external network access (i.e. access to the Internet), through password protection, and by encrypting files. Sensitive data should never be shared via email or cloud storage services such as Dropbox.</p>"},{"id":536,"question_id":759,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-04-08 17:42:19 UTC","updated_at":"2020-04-09 16:35:42 UTC","text":"If applicable, what strategies will you undertake to address secondary uses of sensitive data?","guidance":"<p>Obtaining the appropriate consent from research participants is an important step in assuring Research Ethics Boards that the data may be shared with researchers outside your project. The consent statement may identify certain conditions clarifying the uses of the data by other researchers. For example, it may stipulate that the data will only be shared for non-profit research purposes or that the data will not be linked with personally identified data from other sources.</p>\r\n<p>Read more about data security:&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.ukdataservice.ac.uk/manage-data/store/security.aspx\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">UK Data Service</a>. The Office of Research Services (ORS) at Dalhousie University also has <a href=\"https://www.dal.ca/dept/research-services/responsible-conduct-/research-ethics-.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Research Ethics</a> resources available.&nbsp;</p>"},{"id":537,"question_id":760,"locale":"en","created_at":"2020-04-08 17:42:54 UTC","updated_at":"2020-04-08 17:42:54 UTC","text":"How will you manage legal, ethical, and intellectual property issues?","guidance":"<p>Compliance with privacy legislation and laws that may impose content restrictions in the data should be discussed with your institution's privacy officer or research services office. Research Ethics Boards are central to the research process.</p>\r\n<p>Include here a description concerning ownership, licensing, and intellectual property rights of the data. Terms of reuse must be clearly stated, in line with the relevant legal and ethical requirements where applicable (e.g., subject consent, permissions, restrictions, etc.).</p>"},{"id":538,"question_id":781,"locale":"en","created_at":"2021-01-29 19:06:20 UTC","updated_at":"2021-02-09 15:58:34 UTC","text":"Provide an overview of the data that will be generated, collected or acquired from third-party sources to support this project.","guidance":"<p>Briefly explain how the data will inform your findings.</p>"},{"id":539,"question_id":782,"locale":"en","created_at":"2021-01-29 19:07:52 UTC","updated_at":"2021-02-03 15:24:10 UTC","text":"What method(s) of data collection will be employed?","guidance":""},{"id":540,"question_id":783,"locale":"en","created_at":"2021-01-29 19:09:24 UTC","updated_at":"2021-01-29 19:09:24 UTC","text":"If data will be acquired from a third party, specify the source.","guidance":""},{"id":541,"question_id":784,"locale":"en","created_at":"2021-01-29 19:10:25 UTC","updated_at":"2021-02-03 15:47:11 UTC","text":"What types of data will be included? ","guidance":""},{"id":542,"question_id":785,"locale":"en","created_at":"2021-01-29 19:11:46 UTC","updated_at":"2021-02-03 15:49:48 UTC","text":"What software or digital formats will be used to collect and manage the data?","guidance":""},{"id":543,"question_id":786,"locale":"en","created_at":"2021-01-29 19:13:21 UTC","updated_at":"2021-02-03 15:51:35 UTC","text":"Provide an indication of the scope of the data?","guidance":""},{"id":544,"question_id":787,"locale":"en","created_at":"2021-02-01 18:37:17 UTC","updated_at":"2021-02-03 15:56:15 UTC","text":"Estimate the size of data storage that will be required. ","guidance":"<p>A rough estimate based on other data of similar scope would be adequate.</p>"},{"id":545,"question_id":788,"locale":"en","created_at":"2021-02-01 18:38:16 UTC","updated_at":"2021-02-01 18:38:16 UTC","text":"Where will your data be stored during the collection, collation and analysis phases of the project? ","guidance":"<p>We recommend more than one storage location.</p>"},{"id":546,"question_id":789,"locale":"en","created_at":"2021-02-01 18:38:47 UTC","updated_at":"2021-02-01 18:38:47 UTC","text":"What backup strategy will be employed?","guidance":""},{"id":547,"question_id":790,"locale":"en","created_at":"2021-02-01 18:39:41 UTC","updated_at":"2021-02-08 15:13:16 UTC","text":"How will your data files be organized? What file naming conventions will you use? A brief overview or example would be adequate.  ","guidance":"<p>See the Library's page for suggestions on organizing your files including file naming conventions:</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"https://www.lib.uoguelph.ca/scholarship-publishing/research-data-management/organizing-your-files\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Organizing Your Files</a></p>"},{"id":548,"question_id":791,"locale":"en","created_at":"2021-02-01 20:09:02 UTC","updated_at":"2021-02-01 20:09:02 UTC","text":"What metadata will be developed for your data? Will there be supplemental documentation prepared to assist with the interpretation and analysis of your data?","guidance":""},{"id":549,"question_id":792,"locale":"en","created_at":"2021-02-02 15:45:30 UTC","updated_at":"2021-02-02 15:45:30 UTC","text":"Will you use the UG data repository for long-term preservation of your data? If not, why not? Where will your data be preserved if not in the UG repository?","guidance":""},{"id":550,"question_id":793,"locale":"en","created_at":"2021-02-02 15:47:21 UTC","updated_at":"2021-02-02 15:47:21 UTC","text":"Discuss any data transformations that will be needed so your data is preserved in appropriate, non-proprietary formats.","guidance":""},{"id":551,"question_id":794,"locale":"en","created_at":"2021-02-02 15:48:48 UTC","updated_at":"2021-02-02 15:48:48 UTC","text":"If some of your data will not be preserved, how will you manage it? Will the non-preserved data be destroyed?","guidance":""},{"id":552,"question_id":795,"locale":"en","created_at":"2021-02-02 15:50:41 UTC","updated_at":"2021-02-02 15:50:41 UTC","text":"Will you use the UG data repository for sharing of your data? If not, why not? Will you use a different repository for sharing your data?","guidance":""},{"id":553,"question_id":796,"locale":"en","created_at":"2021-02-02 15:52:11 UTC","updated_at":"2021-02-02 15:52:11 UTC","text":"Explain which version of your data or subset of your data will be shared.","guidance":""},{"id":554,"question_id":797,"locale":"en","created_at":"2021-02-02 15:53:24 UTC","updated_at":"2021-02-02 15:53:24 UTC","text":"When will your data be available for discovery by other researchers? Will you impose an embargo on publication of your data?","guidance":""},{"id":555,"question_id":798,"locale":"en","created_at":"2021-02-02 15:54:40 UTC","updated_at":"2021-02-02 15:54:40 UTC","text":"Will you limit who can access your data? If so, who will that be and why are you limiting the data's reuse?","guidance":""},{"id":556,"question_id":799,"locale":"en","created_at":"2021-02-02 15:56:08 UTC","updated_at":"2021-02-11 17:47:24 UTC","text":"Are there specific license terms you will assign to users of your data?","guidance":"<p>Use the Creative Commons tool to easily create a license that meets your needs. <a href=\"https://creativecommons.org/share-your-work/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Creative Commons - Share your work</a></p>"},{"id":557,"question_id":800,"locale":"en","created_at":"2021-02-03 14:29:31 UTC","updated_at":"2021-02-03 14:29:31 UTC","text":"Are there limitations or constraints on how you manage your data resulting from legal, ethical or intellectual property concerns? ","guidance":""},{"id":558,"question_id":801,"locale":"en","created_at":"2021-02-03 14:32:12 UTC","updated_at":"2021-02-03 14:32:12 UTC","text":"Would your data need to be anonymized or de-identified before being shared with others?","guidance":""}]